<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-18 00:38 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Report: Thomas Has Paid CBA Debt  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO (AP) -- Isiah Thomas has paid off the $750,000 he owed
team owners in the Continental Basketball Association, the minor
league's president told the Chicago Sun-Times.
</P>
<P>
   The newspaper said that clears the way for the Hall of Famer to
be hired as coach of the Indiana Pacers later this week.
</P>
<P>
   CBA president Don Welsh said Thomas, one of two acknowledged
candidates to succeed Larry Bird as the coach of the Pacers, made
the payments.
</P>
<P>
   ''We sent out all those checks by registered mail on Thursday,
and they should have gotten them on Friday,'' Welsh told the
Sun-Times.
</P>
<P>
   ''So we have paid off every penny of that installment. The job
of consolidating nine ownerships into one took much more accounting
time than expected,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas has been told by NBA officials that he must sell his
ownership of the CBA, which he bought last year for $10 million, in
order to accept any NBA coaching job.
</P>
<P>
   Pacers assistant coach Rick Carlisle is the other candidate for
the coaching job.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, Jay Frye, former owner of the Fort Wayne Fury, said
Thomas planned to use advance payments from the Pacers' coaching
position to pay off the $750,000 installment that was due to CBA
owners on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Welsh spoke out against Frye on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   ''What Frye has done is totally improper. He had engaged in a
campaign to publicly embarrass Isiah and to try to keep him from
getting the Indiana Pacer coaching job. We hear he has been calling
Pacers president Donnie Walsh trying to discourage him from hiring
Isiah,'' Welsh told the Sun-Times.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
