<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-18 00:43 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Track Trials Notebook  </HEADLINE>
By BOB BAUM
<TEXT>
<P>
   SACRAMENTO, Calif. (AP) -- Mark Croghan won his heat in the
3,000-meter steeplechase, but his heart was with his infant son who
is in the intensive care unit at Rainbow Babies and Children's
Hospital in Cleveland.
</P>
<P>
   Ten-month-old Griffin Croghan, born with a congenital heart
defect, has been in the hospital for six weeks. While there, he's
undergone two surgeries and had a stroke.
</P>
<P>
   Doctors had predicted he would need a heart transplant, but the
boy has done better since a pacemaker was installed in the latest
operation on Monday, Croghan said.
</P>
<P>
   ''He's had some ups and downs but the last week he's been able
to put seven good days back to back,'' Croghan said. ''He hasn't
been able to do that before, but he's hanging tough. He's going to
be a tough kid.''
</P>
<P>
   Crogan, the 1997 national champion who finished fifth in the
1996 Olympic Games, has altered his training schedule, working out
early in the morning so he can spend the day at the hospital
</P>
<P>
   ''I've got a new focus as far as track goes. It's not life or
death for me anymore,'' he said. ''I mean, I would love to make the
team. I was really happy with my performance today. But I can
honestly say that if I don't finish in the top three on Thursday,
I'll be disappointed. I'll hang my head for maybe a day, but it's
not going to be the end of my life.''
</P>
<P>
   Croghan said it was a tough decision whether to leave Cleveland
to run.
</P>
<P>
   ''In the beginning, I didn't want to be away,'' he said. ''As
more time passed, I realized that my being there really wasn't
going to matter one way or another. It was in God's hands.''
</P>
<P>
   Running is a relief, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ''This is a nice diversion,'' Croghan said. ''This is something
that takes my mind off of his situation an hour or two a day.''
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   TEEN SENSATION@: What a week for 18-year-old Katy Polansky of
South Eugene High School in Oregon.
</P>
<P>
   Polansky broke the national high school women's javelin record
twice, in Sunday's preliminaries and again in Monday night's
finals. Her best on Monday, 174 feet, 2 inches, was good enough for
sixth place in a field where she was by far the youngest.
</P>
<P>
   She knows she should have been satisfied, but she wasn't.
</P>
<P>
   ''I had a p.r. again, and to do it in this caliber of meet is as
much as you can ask for,'' she said. ''But I think there could have
been a little bit more there. That's me, always wanting more.''
</P>
<P>
   Polansky plans to enroll at the University of Oregon, but
doesn't plan to compete in track unless she is allowed to continue
to work under her present coach. She will be a walk-on in
basketball.
</P>
<P>
   But she knows there could be an Olympics in her future. She'll
only be 22 when the next trials rolls around.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think it definitely shows great signs for the future,'' she
said. ''Obviously, I was by far the youngest one out there.
Hopefully, that will speak for my longevity.''
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   DIFFERENT DRUMMER@: In a sport filled with individualists,
1,500-meters champion Gabe Jennings is in a league of his own, and
he comes by it naturally.
</P>
<P>
   Raised and home-schooled in a remote region of Northern
California, Jennings literally runs to the beat of different
drummers.
</P>
<P>
   With his parents providing the lead, friends and relatives pound
a primitive, steady beat on drums in the grandstands as he runs.
Jennings, whose shaggy hair makes him look like some latter-day
Beatle, said it provides him with the rhythm he needs on the track.
</P>
<P>
   A music major at Stanford, Jennings held a news conference like
no other after his victory Sunday. He spent several minutes
explaining how the sunlight floating off the leaves earlier in the
day had helped his preparation. He cried, he said, and knew it was
going to be a good day.
</P>
<P>
   He had reporters laughing with his discourse on the stages of
life.
</P>
<P>
   ''Life is in three stages,'' Jennings said. ''Athletics, that's
the initial stage, to get the body healthy. I'm trying to do that
with running. The other two stages are music and philosophy. When
I'm 50, I see myself being a jazz musician.''
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   GREENSPAN HONORED@: Bud Greenspan, the filmmaker who has
chronicled some of the greatest and most infamous moments in
Olympic sports, will be presented the lifetime achievement award by
USA Track &AMP; Field.
</P>
<P>
   The award will be presented at the Century of Champions dinner
Wednesday night. Among those scheduled to attend are former Olympic
greats Billy Mills, Evelyn Ashford, Bob Mathias, Bob Richards,
Tommie Smith, Wyomia Tyus, Al Oerter and Dick Fosbury.
</P>
<P>
   The Sydney Games will mark the sixth in a series of official
Olympic films produced by Greenspan.
</P>
<P>
   In a news release, USA Track &AMP; Field said Greenspan would be
honored ''for dedication and service to creating a historical
record of track and field's greatest memories.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1997, Greenspan received the George Foster Peobody Award, the
broadcast and cable television's most prestigious honor, for his
lifetime of work. He also won three Emmy Awards in 1994 for his
official film, ''Lillehammer '94: 16 Days of Glory.''
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   TRACK REBIRTH@: In Sacramento, for 10 days in July, track and
field is alive and well in America.
</P>
<P>
   Spirited, standing-room-only crowds have packed Hornet Stadium
to watch a sport that has barely has a pulse in the public
consciousness in non-Olympic years.
</P>
<P>
   Maurice Greene, Jackie Joyner-Kersee and many other competitors
at the U.S. track and field trials have lauded the atmosphere.
</P>
<P>
   ''They say track is dead,'' Greene said. ''Track ain't dead.''
</P>
<P>
   Attendance for the first three days were 23,211, 23,450 and
23,500.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think this is a new beginning for track and field,'' said
Joyner-Kersee, competing in her sixth Olympic trials. ''The fans
have been very, very supportive. They've been wonderful. I think
the Sacramento Sports Commission did a great job of getting the
volunteers and pulling everybody together.
</P>
<P>
   ''This atmosphere is far greater than any Olympic trials that I
have experienced. Like Saturday, I'm sitting there watching and
they're all into the shot put. That was really great. As athletes,
that's what you want.''
</P>
</TEXT>
