<HEADLINE> Man who once saved tot from drowning dies in swimming accident  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   BELVIDERE, N.J. (AP) - A man once honored for pulling an
unconscious girl from a Phillipsburg swimming pool drowned while
trying to swim across the Delaware River, authorities said Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Patrick Reddy, 45, of Belvidere died after he tried to swim from
the New Jersey side to Pennsylvania, south of the Belvidere boat
launch, about 4:45 p.m. Sunday, The Express-Times of Easton, Pa.,
reported in Tuesday's editions.
</P>
<P>
   Using a private boat, Belvidere first aid squad members
recovered Reddy's body and performed cardiopulmonary resuscitation
on him in an unsuccessful attempt to revive him.
</P>
<P>
   He was pronounced dead at 5:05 a.m. Monday, more than 12 hours
after rescue workers had taken him to Warren Hospital, according to
a statement from the Warren County prosecutor.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Malcolm Cowen of the Warren County Medical Examiner's
Office, said the death was an accidental drowning. Reddy had been
drinking before the incident, and Cowen said Reddy's blood-alcohol
level was higher than the 0.10 percent limit for drivers, the
Express-Times reported.
</P>
<P>
   Thirty-three years ago, a 12-year-old Reddy pulled a 3-year-old
girl's unconscious body from a pool in Walters Park, enabling
rescue workers and a lifeguard to resuscitate her.
</P>
<P>
   Reddy, along with others at pool, had been ordered out because
of rain, but Reddy returned when he spotted a girl's body floating,
the newspaper reported.
</P>
<P>
   He carried the girl out of the pool to a lifeguard who performed
mouth-to-mouth resuscitation until rescue workers arrived. The girl
survived.
</P>
<P>
   Reddy was honored with two Boy Scout certificates for his role
in the rescue.
</P>
</TEXT>
