<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Basque Separatists Wage Offensive  </HEADLINE>
By DANIEL WOOLLS
<TEXT>
<P>
   MADRID, Spain (AP) -- A journalist returning from an errand in a
Basque town is shot in the back of the head. One of Madrid's
busiest shopping areas is rocked by a car bomb blast. A politician
in Malaga is riddled with bullets as he heads to a party with his
wife and daughter.
</P>
<P>
   Seven months after the Basque separatist group ETA called off a
14-month cease-fire that had encouraged hopes for peace, once again
it seems no place -- and perhaps no one -- in Spain is safe.
</P>
<P>
   The Spanish government says its initial wariness of the truce
has proved well-founded, insisting that ETA used the cease-fire to
reorganize, resupply and recruit and has now launched a
full-fledged offensive in its battle to create an independent
Basque state.
</P>
<P>
   ''Today ETA has new logistics, a new infrastructure which the
security forces must be able to detect,'' Interior Minister Jaime
Mayor Oreja said Sunday in Malaga.
</P>
<P>
   Minutes after he spoke, another car bomb exploded -- this time
outside a police barracks in the town of Agreda in northern Soria
province. The wife of an officer was slightly injured. There was no
claim of responsibility, but officials pointed to ETA.
</P>
<P>
   Since Jan. 21, ETA has been blamed for nearly a dozen shootings
and car bombings that have left six people dead. Most of the
targets have been politicians, police or military officers, as has
been the case throughout ETA's 30-year armed campaign, which has
killed nearly 800.
</P>
<P>
   So Spaniards were especially shocked last Wednesday when a car
bomb exploded outside one of Madrid's most popular department
stores in a bustling commercial district.
</P>
<P>
   The blast came as dawn broke, before business hours, and no one
was killed, although nine people were injured.
</P>
<P>
   Then came the Saturday night killing of Jose Maria Martin
Carpena, a 50-year-old ruling Popular Party councilor in Malaga,
followed 17 hours later by Sunday's car bomb in Agreda.
</P>
<P>
   Traditionally, the organization tends to regroup for weeks or
even months after an attack, so these back-to-back ones are
especially chilling.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts say ETA's muscle-flexing is aimed at debunking the
government's pre-ceasefire contention that ETA was a spent force,
its ranks decimated by arrests.
</P>
<P>
   Ramon Cotarelo, professor of political science at Complutense
University in Madrid, said it is also highly significant that ETA
is operating all over Spain, not just in the Basque country, and
appears to be keeping the death toll low on purpose.
</P>
<P>
   He said ETA wants to show that ''it is in better shape than
ever, and more importantly, that it strikes when it wants and where
it wants and that if it does not do more damage, it's because it
choses not to.''
</P>
<P>
   As to why ETA is intensifying its campaign now, both he and a
Basque official said a shadowy organization like ETA is virtually
impossible to gauge. But the Basque official, who spoke on
condition of anonymity, rejected suggestions the show of force is a
prelude to another cease-fire. ''That's wishful thinking,'' he
said. ''I fear we in are for some bad times.''
</P>
<P>
   ETA has been fighting for an independent Basque state in
northern Spain and southwest France since the late 1960s. Six
months after it declared the 1998 truce, the group held a single
round of peace talks with the government, the first in a decade.
The dialogue went nowhere, with the government refusing even to
discuss ETA's goal of independence.
</P>
<P>
   Many Spaniards express frustration and puzzlement with Basque
nationalists who claim to suffer repression from the central
government in Madrid.
</P>
<P>
   That complaint was valid under the dictator Gen. Francisco
Franco, who cracked down on Basques and other regional groups with
distinctive cultures and languages other than Castilian Spanish.
Speaking Basque or Catalan, for instance, was a crime.
</P>
<P>
   But Franco died 25 years ago, Spain is now a stable democracy
and the Basque country is one of its most prosperous areas. The
Basque region also enjoys more self-rule than just about any other
under the 1978 constitution, which divided Spain into 17 regions
with varying degrees of say in running their affairs.
</P>
<P>
   The government rules out resuming talks with ETA while bombs are
going off. It is focusing peace efforts on pressuring the moderate
Basque Nationalist Party, which controls the regional government,
to sever all ties with ETA's political wing as a way to isolate ETA
and persuade it to lay down arms again, this time for good.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-07-18-00 0049 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
