<DOCNO> APW20000718.0014 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-18 00:57 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Auction of Triassic winged reptile fossil stirs debate  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   SAN FRANCISCO (AP) - The fossil of a winged reptile that dates
to the Triassic period is headed for the auction block, peeving
paleontologists who argue the relic belongs in a museum.
</P>
<P>
   Lesser known as the Icarosaurus siefkeri, the reptile resembles
a huge dragonfly that's about 7 inches long and stretches about 10
inches from wingtip to wingtip. Its fossilized imprint could fetch
$300,000.
</P>
<P>
   The fossil is about 200 millions years old, meaning the creature
lived some 50 million years before dinosaurs and Archaeopteryx -
evolution's first true bird - emerged.
</P>
<P>
   A trio of teen-agers excavated it from the black shale of an
abandoned New Jersey quarry 39 years ago. At the time, it was the
oldest airborne vertebrate known to scientists.
</P>
<P>
   ''It proves that vertebrates attempted flight some 10 million
years earlier than anyone suspected,'' Edwin H. Colbert said at a
crowded news conference in 1961, when the find was first exhibited.
Colbert was chairman of the American Museum of Natural History in
New York, where the fossil was kept to be studied for 30 years.
</P>
<P>
   The shape of the fossil's delicate web-like wings and body
indicates that the ancient creature could not actually fly, Colbert
said, but probably was a glider, using its wings to soar from tree
to tree in what was then a verdant tropical forest.
</P>
<P>
   Ten years ago, Alfred Siefker, the man who found the fossil when
he was 17 and whose name museum scientists gave to it, reclaimed
the relic. Now 56 years old and ill, Siefker is selling it because
he needs the money, according to David Herskowitz, the natural
history specialist at Butterfield &AMP; Butterfield, where the fossil
will be auctioned Aug. 27.
</P>
<P>
   Also on the block for the ''natural history auction'' are a nest
of 15 dinosaur eggs, two other theropod eggs and a single egg, all
from the Xia Xia formation in China's Henan province.
</P>
<P>
   ''The Icarosaurus is our most outstanding object and really
belongs on exhibit in a museum, not in some private collector's
living room,'' Herskowitz said. ''So we've notified every natural
history museum about it, and they ought to get some of their
wealthy trustees to buy it and donate it.''
</P>
<P>
   Scientists agree that fossils such as these belong in museums,
and they are disturbed by the increasing commercialization of
fossil collections.
</P>
<P>
   Mark B. Goodwin, a vertebrate paleontologist and principal
scientist at the Museum of Paleontology in Berkeley, blasted any
sale of the Icarosaurus as a ''highly unethical event that will
only increase commercialization and encourage the theft of fossils
from museums.''
</P>
<P>
   Paleontologist Kevin Padian, coeditor of the Dinosaur
Encyclopedia, said objects like the Icarosaurus fossil should
belong to everyone. ''Professional scientists are constantly trying
to protect these things for future generations,'' he said, ''and
yet objects like this one often wind up on someone's mantelpiece
where they can never be cared for professionally, or shown to
students, and then they become completely lost to science.''
</P>
<P>
   Herskowitz said the Butterfield's auction will indicate a sale
price range of between of between $250,000 and $350,000 for the
Icarosaurus fossil. The nest with 15 dinosaur eggs from China could
go for $20,000 to $30,000; the pair of eggs for $17,000 to $20,000,
and the single ''fine dinosaur egg'' for $1,800 to $2,250.
</P>
<P>
   As for the site where the Icarosaurus was found: It's home to a
supermarket, a parking lot and a bunch of stores.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-07-18-00 0057 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000718.0015 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-18 01:01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Queen Elizabeth II To Open Embassy  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   BERLIN (AP) -- Much has changed since Queen Elizabeth II visited
the German capital eight years ago, including the street corner
where her country has a sparkling new embassy.
</P>
<P>
   On a trip to open the building Tuesday, the queen and her
husband, Prince Philip, had a tight program of glimpses at the city
that became Europe's biggest construction site after the Berlin
Wall fell in 1989.
</P>
<P>
   The royal couple last came in 1992 to lay the British Embassy's
cornerstone and were staying not quite 24 hours this time.
</P>
<P>
   Two 10-year-old girls will present the queen with a posy and
traditional ''moving-in'' gifts of bread and salt as she arrives to
tour the building and give a speech.
</P>
<P>
   Most countries that had embassies in the old West German capital
of Bonn are moving back to reunified Berlin after the German
government made the trek last year. The United States and France,
among others, plan new diplomatic headquarters nearby.
</P>
<P>
   The new British building, around the corner from Berlin's
signature Brandenburg Gate, replaces one destroyed in air raids
during World War II. It was built on the same site where the
British had their embassy from 1875 to 1939, and even incorporates
a wrought-iron gate salvaged from the rubble of the old building.
</P>
<P>
   Behind the smooth sandstone facade, the $27 million embassy has
modern, angular touches, with bold accents of red and purple, a
glassy interior courtyard and an Internet-based information center
for the public. It's meant to symbolize vibrant British culture and
the openness of British society.
</P>
<P>
   After a speech in the courtyard, the royals were scheduled to
head to Bellevue Palace for lunch with President Johannes Rau, then
play tourist at the Brandenburg Gate and the Reichstag parliament
building -- newly renovated by British architect Norman Foster.
</P>
<P>
   The queen's last stop was at the new British Council cultural
center in Berlin's trendy Mitte neighborhood.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
