<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-18 01:31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Activist Wants Nader on Mich Ballot  </HEADLINE>
By KATHY BARKS HOFFMAN
<TEXT>
<P>
   LANSING, Mich. (AP) -- Craig Harvey is striking fear into the
hearts of Michigan Democrats by pushing to get the Green Party --
and its presidential candidate Ralph Nader -- onto Michigan's ballot
for the first time.
</P>
<P>
   By Thursday, Harvey and other Green Party supporters plan to
turn in more than 50,000 petition signatures. At least 30,272
signatures must be valid for the party to qualify for the November
ballot and Thursday is the last day to hand in petitions.
</P>
<P>
   ''The ones that sign ... are just so happy to have a viable
alternative'' to Bush and Gore, Harvey said. ''We get everything
from being cursed out to getting hugs for what we're doing.''
</P>
<P>
   With a recent statewide poll showing Nader taking away votes
from Vice President Al Gore, Democrats have reason to worry about
the feisty consumer advocate being on the ballot.
</P>
<P>
   The most recent poll, done by EPIC/MRA of Lansing earlier this
month, put Gore at 40 percent and Texas Gov. George W. Bush at 45
percent. But in a hypothetical four-way race with Nader and likely
Reform Party candidate Pat Buchanan, Gore got only 34 percent to
Bush's 46 percent, while Nader got 8 percent and Buchanan got 3
percent. The margin of error was 4 percentage points.
</P>
<P>
   Nader has been helped in Michigan by the United Auto Workers and
Teamsters unions' decisions to hold off endorsing Gore after he
supported granting permanent normal trade relations with China.
Teamsters leaders have met with Nader, while UAW head Steven Yokich
has mentioned him as a possible alternative to Gore.
</P>
<P>
   Michigan voters have a habit of backing anti-establishment
candidates -- Jesse Jackson won the 1988 Democratic caucuses, and
Sen. John McCain defeated Bush in February's GOP presidential
primary.
</P>
<P>
   Bloomfield Township Sen. Gary Peters said there are plenty of
reasons to worry that Nader will cost Gore votes -- and possibly the
election. ''We will probably see a very close race for president,
so any third-party candidate out there could mean the difference,''
said Peters, a member of the Michigan Democratic Party's executive
board.
</P>
<P>
   Harvey, who voted for Nader in 1996 as a write-in candidate,
isn't feeling much sympathy.
</P>
<P>
   ''If someone is worried about Bush getting elected, then they
should look at who's stronger against him. And if it's Gore against
Bush or Nader against Bush, Nader is the stronger candidate,'' said
Harvey, a 45-year-old resident of Pittsfield Township near Ann
Arbor.
</P>
<P>
   Harvey has leaned toward Democratic candidates in the past but
went for Ross Perot in 1992, a year when 19 percent of Michigan
voters supported the Texas billionaire and his United We Stand
America party. By 1996, Nader had Harvey's attention.
</P>
<P>
   ''Nader has been saying the same basic things and working the
same basic issues for 35 years now, not changing his tone with
every poll that comes down,'' Harvey said. ''I trust him.''
</P>
<P>
   He recognizes that in car-crazy Michigan -- home of General
Motors Corp., Ford Motor Co. and the Chrysler division of
DaimlerChrysler AG -- not everyone is going to embrace the man who
trashed the Corvair in his 1965 book, ''Unsafe at Any Speed: The
Designed-In Dangers of the American Automobile.''
</P>
<P>
   He expects Nader's call to renegotiate trade agreements, protect
the environment and force Congress to listen to citizens rather
than corporations is going to appeal to Michigan voters.
</P>
<P>
   Nader is on the ballot in 19 states so far but hopes to be on
the ballot in 45 by November.
</P>
<P>
   During a town hall meeting Thursday in Saginaw, Gore avoided
mentioning Nader by name, even though one woman told him she was
considering voting for the Green Party candidate because ''the
Clinton-Gore administration gave an awful lot of ground back to the
right.''
</P>
<P>
   Pollster Ed Sarpolus of EPIC/MRA said many of those now in
Nader's corner probably will vote for Gore when the election comes.
</P>
<P>
   ''Once labor wakes up from its stupor and realizes it has to get
back on track,'' Sarpolus said, ''many of those will come back to
Gore.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
