<HEADLINE> Quake Jolts Afghanistan Residents  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   KABUL, Afghanistan (AP) -- An earthquake with a preliminary
magnitude of 6.2 jolted residents in this capital Tuesday morning,
sending them fleeing from their homes.
</P>
<P>
   The quake, centered in the central Afghan Hindu Kush mountain
range barely 60 miles north of the capital, caused windows to
rattle and furniture to tremble, witnesses said.
</P>
<P>
   There were no immediate reports of injuries or damage.
</P>
<P>
   People grabbed their children and ran into the streets of Kabul,
said witnesses waiting for the rumbling to subside.
</P>
<P>
   The quake was felt as far away as Islamabad, the federal capital
of neighboring Pakistan, some 240 miles away.
</P>
<P>
   A powerful earthquake in 1998 killed more than 5,000 people and
left tens of thousands of people homeless in northern Afghanistan.
</P>
</TEXT>
