<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-18 02:04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Gore Boosts Victims' Rights in Tenn  </HEADLINE>
By SANDRA SOBIERAJ
<TEXT>
<P>
   MEMPHIS, Tenn. (AP) -- Criticized for halfhearted support of a
victims' rights resolution in the Senate, Al Gore is wrapping the
proposed Constitutional amendment into his presidential campaign --
first with a TV ad and, now, with a campaign appearance at the side
of crime victims.
</P>
<P>
   At Rhodes College in his home state, the vice president was
expected Tuesday to echo his exhortation in the Democratic National
Committee's most recent ad: ''Accused criminals have all kinds of
rights. But the victims of crimes do not have rights that are
always protected and guaranteed.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore, promising to ''lead the fight to pass a Victims' Rights
Amendment'' to the U.S. Constitution, said crime victims should be
notified if a prisoner is released -- or escapes -- from jail and
should have the right to speak to a jury at trial.
</P>
<P>
   Under the proposal, aides said, victims would also be granted
the right to consult on trial preparation and to be heard on
sentencing and plea bargains.
</P>
<P>
   The Democratic presidential candidate's proposed amendment
borrows heavily from the Senate resolution sponsored by Dianne
Feinstein, D-Calif., and Jon Kyl, R-Ariz.
</P>
<P>
   Kyl yanked that measure from debate in late April, after
negotiations with the White House failed to reach agreement on one
point: the administration's insistence that it give police,
prosecutors and judges the flexibility to limit victims' rights if
they threatened to jeopardize a fair trial.
</P>
<P>
   At that time, Kyl blamed the resolution's failure on the
Clinton-Gore administration's refusal to endorse it. Kyl planned --
at the behest of Republican presidential contender George W. Bush's
campaign -- a conference call to reporters on Tuesday to counter
Gore's effort to champion the issue.
</P>
<P>
   ''Gore will champion his support for crime victims' rights, but
his administration just killed a bipartisan bill two months ago,''
said Bush spokesman Dan Bartlett.
</P>
<P>
   Thirty-two states have enacted some form of victims' rights.
</P>
<P>
   The DNC ad, which pictures Gore with uniformed police officers,
began airing in 17 states six days ago. Under campaign finance
laws, the DNC, which uses unregulated ''soft money'' for the ads,
is not supposed to coordinate their production or placement with
Gore's presidential campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Gore was back on the DNC fund-raising circuit Monday night, with
a $400,000 pair of receptions. At the more intimate
$25,000-per-person gathering, where guests were treated to a silver
notepad engraved with the vice presidential seal and Gore's
signature, Gore asked Democrats to rally for the fight against
Bush.
</P>
<P>
   ''The other side is arguing to put the old guard back in power
with their old ideas,'' Gore said.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's father was president from 1989-1993, when he lost the
White House to Bill Clinton and Gore.
</P>
<P>
   At that same reception, Gore made a plea for racial harmony,
referring to ethnic conflicts overseas. He raised eyebrows among
his aides when he called the Bosnians ''Bosniacs.'' A spokeswoman,
aware of the ridicule Bush faced for calling Greeks ''Grecians,''
hastened to clarify for reporters that Bosniacs is a common and
acceptable term in Europe.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
