<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iloilo Sworn In As Fiji President  </HEADLINE>
By PAUL ALEXANDER
<TEXT>
<P>
   SUVA, Fiji (AP) -- Fiji's new president, a frail and elderly
tribal chief, was sworn in Tuesday and urged reconciliation in the
ethnically divided nation that had been paralyzed by a two-month
hostage crisis. But Ratu Josefa Iloilo later named a Cabinet that
included no ethnic Indians.
</P>
<P>
   The Cabinet does have at least two supporters of nationalist
coup leader George Speight, whose men stormed parliament on behalf
of indigenous Fijians. Still, Speight rejected the Cabinet and
predicted a return to unrest.
</P>
<P>
   ''It will result in a backlash,'' he said. ''The fun is just
beginning.''
</P>
<P>
   The only Indian involved in Iloilo's administration will be
George Shiu Raj, appointed one of two assistant ministers for
multiethnic affairs -- a non-Cabinet post. Iloilo said in a
statement that members of Fiji's ethnic Indian minority initially
accepted Cabinet posts but later withdrew ''due to concern for the
safety of their families.''
</P>
<P>
   The statement did not elaborate. But the presence of Speight
supporters and total absence of Indians is likely to prompt more
nations to follow New Zealand's lead and slap sanctions on Fiji to
press for a return to multiracial democracy.
</P>
<P>
   Iloilo took the oath of office in a stately official residence
overlooking the harbor of the capital, Suva.
</P>
<P>
   ''We are one, as one nation and one people,'' Iloilo told an
audience that included Speight, the country's former military head
of state Commodore Frank Bainimarama, and former Prime Minister
Sitiveni Rabuka.
</P>
<P>
   Iloilo, his left hand shaking from Parkinson's disease, said he
would be ''dedicated to promoting national unity and encouraging
moderation, inclusiveness, consideration and compassion of all in
our country.''
</P>
<P>
   Speight, who backed Iloilo's appointment, said: ''We are
pleased, it's a good day for the Fijian people.''
</P>
<P>
   Prime Minister Laisenia Qarase stayed in the post he was
appointed to just last week heading an unelected interim government
that has a mandate to guide Fiji to elections in about 18 months.
</P>
<P>
   There were reports Speight was unhappy with a scenario that
would include few of his men and allow Qarase, who was sworn in two
weeks ago by the military as interim prime minister, to keep his
job.
</P>
<P>
   Qarase's prospects rose Friday, however, after he released a
blueprint for Fiji's future that was branded as racist for
guaranteeing political superiority and affirmative action for
indigenous Fijians and promising redistribution of resources to
benefit them.
</P>
<P>
   Those were the stated goals of the May 19 coup that Speight led.
The last 18 of dozens of legislators taken hostage in Parliament
were freed last Thursday as part of a deal that Speight said would
disenfranchise ethnic Indians, who make up 44 percent of the
population.
</P>
<P>
   Speight has vowed a renewal of the civil disturbances that
wracked the country for 11 days until the hostage release if he
finds the Cabinet unacceptable. He is particularly interested in
ensuring that his backers dominate a commission that will write a
new constitution.
</P>
<P>
   New Zealand did not wait even for the Cabinet lineup to be
announced, imposing sanctions Monday. The sanctions include
suspension of joint military exercises, reduced development aid and
ending student visits and sporting visas.
</P>
<P>
   Asked if he would find ethnic Indians acceptable in the Cabinet,
Speight replied, ''Not at the moment, not if I can help it.''
</P>
<P>
   He described deposed Prime Minister Mahendra Chaudhry's declared
intention to return to office as ''misguided.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked about Chaudhry being beaten up while being held by Speight
and a gang of gunmen for two months in Fiji's Parliament, Speight
said, ''He's OK, he was roughed up once and beaten once. He's lucky
he's alive.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-07-18-00 0205 </TRAILER>
