<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-18 02:21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mexicans Fed Up With Ruling Party  </HEADLINE>
By LISA J. ADAMS
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANENECUILCO, Mexico (AP) -- In rural communities like this -- the
birthplace of Mexico's greatest revolutionary hero, Emiliano Zapata
-- the country's ruling party thought it had an unshakable bastion
of support.
</P>
<P>
   But people here say they've been fed up with the party for years
-- and on July 2, their votes helped elect Mexico's first opposition
president in 71 years. Now, they say the victory of Vicente Fox has
given them a sliver of hope.
</P>
<P>
   For one, many people here believe Fox will help them improve
their lives. For another, they know the ruling Institutional
Revolutionary Party, or PRI, will have to redouble its efforts in
the countryside if it wants to win them back.
</P>
<P>
   ''They will have to make a much bigger effort to help the
people,'' said Zapata's great-granddaughter, 32-year-old Herlinda
Zapata. ''Because if they don't, people know that the next time,
they can support someone else.''
</P>
<P>
   Rufino Castillo Rodriguez, a 53-year-old farmer and school
teacher unloading bunches of dried onion leaves off the back of a
truck, said support for the party used to be strong here, but now,
''people are tired of seeing the same authorities working just to
enrich themselves.''
</P>
<P>
   ''Now they've woken up and are reacting in a different way in
the hopes of improving their situation.''
</P>
<P>
   No matter how tight the race -- and the PRI looked at Fox as one
of its greatest threats ever -- party members never expected to fare
so badly in the countryside.
</P>
<P>
   On election day, after receiving early exit polls showing he'd
lost, PRI presidential candidate Francisco Labastida reportedly
held out, saying ''Let's wait for the rural vote.'' That
overwhelming victory never came. Labastida won the countryside by
only 10 points.
</P>
<P>
   Zapata's home state of Morelos was the first of the southern
states -- the PRI's strongest base of support -- to elect a governor
who wasn't with the PRI. Upcoming gubernatorial elections in the
southern states of Chiapas and Tabasco will be yet another test of
the PRI's endurance.
</P>
<P>
   Anenecuilco is one of several small communities of Ayala, a
Morelos municipality of 70,000 people ringed by farmland and
rolling hills 65 miles south of Mexico City.
</P>
<P>
   Images of the mustachioed, sombrero-wearing Zapata appear
everywhere here: A bronze statue in his likeness keeps watch over
the town square. He rides to victory on a painted mural outside the
tourist site that guards the ruins of his humble stone home. His
name is used to identify everything from beauty salons to
stationery stores.
</P>
<P>
   The PRI has long portrayed itself as a champion of Zapata's
fight for the poor, but Angel Mina, curator of the Zapata house for
18 years, scoffs at such an idea.
</P>
<P>
   ''If Zapata was alive, he would not back the PRI. Zapata was
honest, a clean man. We have seen that the PRI is a big rat,'' he
said, using the Mexican slang word for thief. ''It is a party that
no longer works for us.''
</P>
<P>
   Castillo said even the PRI's ability to hold onto the Ayala
mayor's seat this year was just a fluke. And Jose Guadalupe Vega, a
66-year-old farmer playing dominoes in the main square of the Ayala
village of Tenextepango, said as far he's concerned, ''the PRI is
dead.''
</P>
<P>
   Ayala's new mayor, Miguel Octavio, admits that the party must
work hard to maintain its local support in the face of state and
nationwide election losses.
</P>
<P>
   Echoing the declarations of national party leaders scrambling to
reorganize and redefine the ''New PRI,'' Octavio says his
administration's most important goal is ''to work more closely and
intimately with the community, together with the people ... with
the spirit of service.''
</P>
<P>
   With that in mind, the 41-year-old gynecologist and neophyte
politician, accompanied by a small cadre of campaign workers, made
a special visit to a poor neighborhood of Tenextepango on a recent
evening to thank farmers for their support and to reiterate a
pledge to complete a much-needed health clinic.
</P>
<P>
   ''We're going to share the benefits of our hard work with the
whole community,'' Octavio told sun-bronzed farmers and their
families who sat in folding chairs or leaned against the walls of
the one-room cement building.
</P>
<P>
   The response of his audience, while enthusiastic, also reflected
the nascent skepticism of lifelong PRI voters.
</P>
<P>
   ''The people are interested in seeing a project like the health
center actually finished,'' said Isidro Ramirez. ''None of the
(PRI) presidents before would authorize it. ... We hope with you we
are closer to making it happen.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
