<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-18 02:46 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tough Questions at Mideast Summit  </HEADLINE>
By LAURA KING
<TEXT>
<P>
   THURMONT, Md. (AP) -- There's a reason they're called ''core
issues'' -- they go straight to the heart of the conflict that has
raged between Israel and the Palestinians for more than half a
century.
</P>
<P>
   Refugees. Borders. Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
   The parties came to the Camp David talks hoping to produce a
sweeping Middle East agreement, but they may wind up settling for
partial solutions.
</P>
<P>
   So explosive are the so-called core issues that in seven years
of peacemaking, the two sides repeatedly put off talks about them.
Now, with President Clinton declaring he wants an agreement by
Wednesday, they find themselves with only a matter of hours to edge
toward tentative compromise.
</P>
<P>
   In the secluded presidential retreat, negotiators and the
leaders themselves have argued and discussed and debated late into
the rainy summer nights.
</P>
<P>
   While only they know what has been said in private, here is a
look at some possible dealmaking that, while not comprehensive
solutions, could emerge in response to the toughest questions.
------
</P>
<P>
Borders of a Palestinian State
</P>
<P>
   The struggle for land is as old as the West Bank's stony hills,
a battle that persists to this day.
</P>
<P>
   Seized by Israel in the 1967 Six-Day War along with the Gaza
Strip and East Jerusalem, the West Bank -- only the size of Delaware
-- is regarded by many Jewish settlers as their biblical birthright.
</P>
<P>
   The Palestinians already control the West Bank's major cities
and have partial autonomy in Gaza. But they fear the Israelis will
try to hand them an archipelago state, a patchwork of territory
crisscrossed by Israeli-controlled roads and Jewish settlements.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly 200,000 Jewish settlers have made homes for themselves in
the West Bank and Gaza. Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak has said
up to one-quarter of those may be left outside the umbrella of
Israeli sovereignty in any peace accord.
</P>
<P>
   Although the Palestinians headed into the negotiations demanding
all the West Bank and Gaza, they have quietly suggested they are
willing to compromise.
</P>
<P>
   Days before the Camp David talks began, Palestinian leader
Yasser Arafat's senior economic adviser, Mohammed Rashid,
essentially gave his blessing to a land swap that would leave large
settlement blocs under Israeli sovereignty in exchange for
unpopulated land elsewhere in Israel proper.
------
</P>
<P>
Palestinian Refugees
</P>
<P>
   In the chaos of Israel's war of independence, and again 19 years
later in the Six-Day War, they fled or were driven from their
homes. They long for them still.
</P>
<P>
   In the West Bank and Gaza Strip, as well as Jordan, Lebanon and
Syria, several million Palestinian refugees and their descendants
live in crowded cement-block camps, administered by the United
Nations, that were supposed to have provided only temporary refuge.
</P>
<P>
   For as long as the Palestinians have been fighting for a
homeland, one of their sacred tenets has been the ''right of
return'' -- the refugees' claim on homes in Israel proper, some in
towns and villages that no longer exist.
</P>
<P>
   Israel flatly refuses to accept all the refugees, saying they
would overwhelm a country of only 6 million and undermine its
character as a Jewish state.
</P>
<P>
   However, Barak is said to be considering Israel's recognition of
a U.N. resolution on Palestinians' right of return, but only in
principle and not in practice. Under this scenario, Israel would
not accept moral responsibility for causing the refugees' plight.
</P>
<P>
   The respected Haaretz newspaper, citing Israeli sources,
reported an idea under which Israel would absorb several thousand
refugees to be reunited with immediate families. A future
Palestinian state would take in others, and a massive international
aid package would assist other refugees in their current places of
residence.
------
</P>
<P>
Jerusalem
</P>
<P>
   Sacred to three faiths, this ancient city is the scene of a
modern-day holy war. Conflicting claims resonate through Jerusalem,
from the cobblestone streets of the Old City to the Arab souks
(marketplaces) and the modern buildings of the Jewish western
sector.
</P>
<P>
   Israel wants to keep Jerusalem exclusively under Israeli
sovereignty, keeping the status quo of freedom of access to holy
sites. The Palestinians seek to divide the city into two capitals,
theirs in the east and the Israelis' in the west.
</P>
<P>
   Some alternatives put forward in the past include the so-called
Beilin-Abbas plan, informally negotiated five years ago and named
for its architects: Yossi Beilin, now Israel's justice minister,
and Mahmoud Abbas, a top aide to Arafat. This would expand the
borders of the city to include West Bank suburbs, where the
Palestinians would base their capital.
</P>
<P>
   Another idea is the so-called boroughs approach. This would
allow the Palestinians partial administrative control in Arab
neighborhoods, including health, education and utilities. In the
sensitive Old City, some holy sites would be managed by the
Palestinians, while overall sovereignty would be retained by
Israel.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-07-18-00 0246 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000718.0032 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-18 02:47 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton Steps Up Mideast Talks  </HEADLINE>
By LAURA KING
<TEXT>
<P>
   THURMONT, Md. (AP) -- The Camp David summit was entering a
make-or-break day Tuesday, with President Clinton saying through a
spokesman he hopes the parties will have ''wrapped up their
business'' by the time he is to leave to Japan the following
morning.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's chief spokesman Joe Lockhart said Monday the president
intended to keep to his scheduled departure, but nonetheless
suggested that the hours leading up to it could be a cliffhanger.
</P>
<P>
   ''You'll know that we're following through on the schedule when
you see the president walk to the top of the steps (of the plane)
and wave and the door close,'' he told reporters.
</P>
<P>
   Another White House spokesman amplified that later. ''The
schedule won't change until it changes,'' P.J. Crowley said late
Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Lockhart said the leaders, Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak and
Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat, had a clear view of the time
constraints at the week-old summit in the mountains of western
Maryland.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think that the parties understand the schedule here,'' he
said. ''They understand that they're working toward that.''
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, Clinton met with Barak, then Arafat, then Barak
again. No formal dinner with the delegations was scheduled, unlike
the first five evenings of the summit.
</P>
<P>
   With the clock ticking down on the talks, Lockhart said, ''I
think the pace and intensity have both quickened.''
</P>
<P>
   Negotiators in two parallel sets of talks -- the primary ones at
the Camp David presidential retreat, addressing so-called core
issues, and lower-level secondary discussions in nearby Emmitsburg,
Md. -- have both been keeping long hours, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton has shuttled back and forth between the two leaders
during the week of talks, bringing them together twice for
three-way meetings, in addition to informal encounters at meals.
</P>
<P>
   Israeli officials said they knew the negotiations had reached a
critical juncture.
</P>
<P>
   ''It is clear we are at a very historic and delicate moment,''
Cabinet Secretary Yitzhak Herzog told Associated Press Television
News. ''I guess we will know in the next 48 hours whether there is
a breakthrough, and whether we can reach an agreement or not.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton appeared to be using the three-day summit of industrial
powers in Japan as a means to prod the two sides toward compromises
aimed at resolving their bitter half-century-old dispute.
</P>
<P>
   The main issues on the table are the borders of a future
Palestinian state, the fate of several million Palestinian refugees
and the status of Jerusalem, which both sides claim as their
capital.
</P>
<P>
   ''The negotiations are very difficult and our position is
clear,'' said Hassan Abdel Rahman, the Washington envoy of Arafat's
Palestine Liberation Organization. On the key matters, he said,
''We cannot make concessions.''
</P>
<P>
   Lockhart, though, said no one was ready to throw in the towel.
</P>
<P>
   ''I don't think we would be here if there wasn't a chance to get
this done,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   At one point, the White House spokesman was asked, half in jest,
whether Clinton might take Barak and Arafat with him to Japan so
they could continue their negotiations in flight.
</P>
<P>
   ''Thirteen and a half hours on a plane? I don't think so,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton is due to met in Tokyo on Thursday with Japanese Prime
Minister Yoshiro Mori and other leaders before their Friday-Sunday
summit on Okinawa.
</P>
<P>
   Both Barak and Arafat face political problems at home if they
arrive at a compromise -- or if they fail to.
</P>
<P>
   Barak's governing coalition collapsed on the eve of his
departure for the summit, and he is likely to face early elections.
Hard-liners have been staging demonstrations urging him not to make
broad territorial concessions to the Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
   Arafat's aides said heading into the talks that it was not the
right time for a summit, because gaps between the two sides needed
to be narrowed first. But once he was here, top aides including
Nabil Amr, the parliamentary affairs minister, said he wanted to
try to make a deal. Palestinians have been frustrated by the slow
pace of peacemaking since Barak's election in May 1999, and that
anger has sometimes erupted into deadly street clashes in the West
Bank and Gaza Strip.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. hosts have sought to keep a veil of secrecy over the
substance of summit talks. Clinton himself broke the silence to say
in an interview with the New York Daily News published Monday that
the talks were ''so hard'' that he did not know whether an accord
could be reached.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
