<HEADLINE> Former Starr Aide on Trial  </HEADLINE>
By LARRY MARGASAK
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Prosecutors are trying to portray Charles
Bakaly III, former spokesman for Kenneth Starr, as an official who
leaked information to ''send a message'' that the investigation of
President Clinton would not end with his impeachment trial.
</P>
<P>
   Bakaly, who resumes testimony today, took the stand Monday in
his contempt of court trial. He is accused of misleading a federal
judge by denying in a court statement that he leaked information to
a New York Times reporter.
</P>
<P>
   Bakaly contended during direct examination he never misled the
court about his cooperation with the Times, and even tried to edit
a court document submitted on behalf of Starr, the former
independent counsel, in order to fully explain his role.
</P>
<P>
   Bakaly said the personal account he submitted of his meetings
with Times reporter, Don Van Natta Jr., was accurate when presented
to a judge in February 1999. But he testified that lawyers for
Starr omitted some of his proposed changes from an accompanying
court filing on the leaked material -- changes that would have shown
that he provided the reporter with public information.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. District Judge Norma Holloway Johnson is conducting the
trial without a jury. Bakaly could get up to six months in prison
if convicted.
</P>
<P>
   In cross-examination, Justice Department prosecutor John
Griffith tried to show that Bakaly had motives to leak information.
</P>
<P>
   The focus of the trial is a Times story of Jan. 31, 1999, which
said that Starr -- who was investigating Monica Lewinsky's affair
with the president -- had decided that a sitting president could be
indicted. The article, written during Clinton's impeachment trial,
also said that a group of prosecutors in Starr's office concluded
the president should be indicted.
</P>
<P>
   Griffith portrayed the defendant as a willing participant in the
leaks, asking Bakaly whether he intended to ''send a message'' that
Starr's investigation would not end with the Senate impeachment
trial. Bakaly acknowledged that he wanted to convey to the public
that ''our office would stay in business'' -- but contended he never
provided any secret material.
</P>
<P>
   Griffith also questioned whether the Senate's decision against
calling live impeachment trial witnesses led to frustration by
Bakaly and played a role in his cooperation with the Times.
</P>
<P>
   Bakaly, without acknowledging any connection to the article,
said that prosecutors would have liked live witnesses as a
''preview'' of Clinton's defense.
</P>
<P>
   In direct questioning from defense lawyer Michele Roberts, the
former spokesman said Starr's lawyers, in their filing, made it
appear he was denying providing any material to the Times when, in
fact, he gave the reporter public information.
</P>
<P>
   Bakaly admitted he gave Van Natta a Watergate-era memo studied
by Starr's lawyers and a copy of Starr's congressional testimony on
the power to indict a sitting president.
</P>
<P>
   ''Was it true?'' defense lawyer Michele Roberts asked Bakaly
about his personal statement to the court in 1999.
</P>
<P>
   ''Yes it was,'' Bakaly responded.
</P>
<P>
   ''Does it remain true today?''
</P>
<P>
   ''Yes it is.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-07-18-00 0249 </TRAILER>
