<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-18 02:51 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Japan Seeks a New Role  </HEADLINE>
By JOJI SAKURAI
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIYAZAKI, Japan (AP) -- As Asia's lone economic superpower and
biggest donor of development aid, Japan has grown accustomed to
having a key -- if not high-profile -- position in world affairs.
</P>
<P>
   As Japan prepares to welcome the leaders of the Group of Eight
leading industrialized countries and Russia for a July 21-23 summit
on Okinawa, Tokyo is maneuvering to bolster its image.
</P>
<P>
   There are signs its efforts are bearing fruit.
</P>
<P>
   ''Japan can't take the lead all at once, but it is making
efforts to shed its status as an outsider and become an insider,''
said political analyst Minoru Morita. ''Japan feels that the G-8
gathering is an initial step toward taking a more central role in
diplomatic affairs.''
</P>
<P>
   Before the summit, the late Prime Minister Keizo Obuchi toured
Asian countries to hear their views, and reassured them that, as
Asia's sole representative in the elite G-8, he would take regional
concerns to the summit roundtable.
</P>
<P>
   Since his sudden death in April, the administration of his
successor, Prime Minister Yoshiro Mori, has tried to keep that
promise.
</P>
<P>
   At this week's foreign ministers' conference, held in this
southern Japan city, Japan made sure regional issues got an
abundant hearing.
</P>
<P>
   The dramatic detente between North and South Korea was mentioned
in the joint communique ahead of other world hot spots such as
Yugoslavia and the Mideast.
</P>
<P>
   Japanese Foreign Minister Yohei Kono was instrumental in
convincing G-8 foreign ministers to spotlight the landmark
encounter between South Korean President Kim Dae-jung and the
North's Kim Jong Il.
</P>
<P>
   To keep the ball rolling, Kono flew to Seoul after the
conference here to consult with President Kim on the wording of a
special statement to be issued at the G-8 summit in support of
Korean reconciliation.
</P>
<P>
   Kono said after the foreign ministers' meeting that Western
powers are beginning to pay heed to Japan's views on regional
issues.
</P>
<P>
   ''As the only foreign minister from Asia, I shared my views
about the Korean Peninsula and many of the ministers indicated a
strong interest,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Backing for democratic reform in Indonesia and infrastructure
building in East Timor were also mentioned prominently in the joint
communique, which urged ''the full support of the international
community to further promote peace and stability in the entire
region.''
</P>
<P>
   Tokyo was able to push its agenda in other ways at the foreign
ministers' gathering.
</P>
<P>
   Its initiative to curb the small arms trade topped the list of
measures agreed upon to help prevent global conflicts. And despite
opposition from some G-8 countries, the foreign ministers endorsed
beefing up the U.N. security council in line with the wishes of
Japan, which has long been lobbying for a permanent seat.
</P>
<P>
   The diplomatic successes could signal a gradual coming of age
for Japan in its fitful efforts to become more than just a
financier greasing the wheels of world markets and giving handouts
to needy nations -- often with an eye to bolstering its own business
interests in those nations.
</P>
<P>
   But obstacles abound to Japan taking a wider Asian role.
</P>
<P>
   One problem is the suspicion Japan still evokes among neighbors
for its brutal invasion of Asia in the decades leading up to World
War II.
</P>
<P>
   Tokyo's inability to offer an unambiguous apology for wartime
atrocities has created an uncomfortable imbalance between the close
economic rapport it enjoys with its neighbors and their often
frosty diplomatic ties.
</P>
<P>
   Any sign that Japan may try to expand its military clout by
revising its pacifist constitution or beefing up its defense
capabilities is also greeted by protests from China and other Asian
countries.
</P>
<P>
   And Japan's current leadership has aggravated that problem.
</P>
<P>
   While Foreign Minister Yohei Kono is known as a political dove
with well-honed diplomatic skills, Mori, who will host the G-8
leaders summit, has made blunder after blunder with comments
evoking Japan's militaristic past.
</P>
<P>
   Still, there is no denying that Japan has made progress in
forging a new leadership role in the region.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, it became the first major industrialized nation to
conclude an agreement on terms for China's accession to the World
Trade Organization.
</P>
<P>
   The accord came amid acrimony with the United States over the
bombing of Beijing's embassy in Yugoslavia, and may have helped
defuse tensions between China and the West.
</P>
<P>
   Finance Minister Kiichi Miyazawa's plan in 1997 to create a
regional monetary fund to help economies battered by the Asian
currency crisis was quashed by Washington, but received widespread
support among countries burdened by the harsh conditions imposed by
the IMF.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-07-18-00 0251 </TRAILER>
