<HEADLINE> Senate Battle Waging Over Parks  </HEADLINE>
By ALAN FRAM
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Western senators are challenging Clinton
administration actions and rules that have expanded national
parklands and limited the recreational activities allowed on them.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate planned to vote Tuesday on a proposal by Senate
Majority Whip Don Nickles, R-Okla., that would block President
Clinton from creating any additional national monuments. With
several Republican senators from politically moderate Northeastern
states facing re-election in November, the language seemed likely
to be rejected.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, many Westerners have opposed Clinton's use of a 1906
law to add nearly 2 million acres this year alone to the federal
lands protected as national monuments. The lands are nearly all in
Arizona, California, Colorado, Oregon and Washington state.
</P>
<P>
   Also expected was a vote on an effort by Sen. Craig Thomas,
R-Wyo., to block a National Park Service ban on snowmobiling in
nearly all national parks, monuments and recreation areas. The
administration has said the ban, issued last April, is aimed at
reducing noise and environmental damage in the parks. It has been
opposed by the recreation industry.
</P>
<P>
   ''The issue is access to lands that belong to the people of this
country,'' Thomas said during debate on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Both proposals were offered as amendments to a $15.5 billion
measure financing the Interior Department and federal cultural
programs in the coming fiscal year.
</P>
<P>
   The House approved a $14.6 billion version of the bill last
month containing no language on snowmobiles or national monuments.
House opponents of Clinton's monument designations lost an effort
to virtually undo all the monuments he has named this year.
</P>
<P>
   The House and Senate versions of the bill both face an
administration veto threat because they provide less than Clinton
wants for parkland purchases, some programs for Indians, and the
National Endowment for the Arts.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
