<DOCNO> APW20000718.0040 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-18 10:23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Stocks Slip in Early Trading  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks slumped at the open Tuesday despite some
strong profit reports by major companies and a generally
unsurprising inflation report.
</P>
<P>
   After the first 15 minutes of trading, the Dow Jones industrial
average was off 31.11 at 10,773.16.
</P>
<P>
   Among broader market indicators, the Nasdaq composite index was
down 49.86 at 4,224.81, the Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 was down 8.84 at
1,499.26, and the Russell 2000 index of smaller companies was off
4.25 at 540.93.
</P>
<P>
   Before the open, the Labor Department reported that consumer
inflation jumped 0.6 percent in June, chiefly reflecting surging
gasoline prices and a record rise in the cost of natural gas.
</P>
<P>
   Most other prices posted modest increases. June's performance,
close to the 0.5 percent rise in consumer prices many analysts were
expecting, was the largest increase since March.
</P>
<P>
   The Federal Reserve has boosted interest rates six times over
the past 13 months to slow economic growth and keep inflation in
check. Some economic reports have suggested that the Fed's rate
increases are working to slow economic growth. Given that, some
economists believe the central bank will leave rates unchanged at
its meeting on Aug. 22.
</P>
<P>
   Merrill Lynch and General Motors led the morning parade of
reports on second-quarter profits with better-than-expected
results. Among other leading companies, Honeywell and Phillip
Morris matched most Wall Street profit forecasts.
</P>
<P>
   On a more worrisome note, Aetna issued a waning that its
second-quarter results would come in well below analyst
expectations.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
