<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-18 11:37 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Dow Down 85; Nasdaq Falls 95  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks slumped Tuesday morning despite some
strong profit reports by major companies and a mostly unsurprising
inflation report.
</P>
<P>
   By late morning on Wall Street, the Dow Jones industrial average
was down 84.85 at 10,719.42.
</P>
<P>
   Among broader market indicators, the Nasdaq composite index was
down 94.74 at 4,179.93, the Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 was down 17.30 at
1,493.19, and the Russell 2000 index of smaller companies was down
7.86 at 537.32.
</P>
<P>
   Declining issues outnumbered advancers by a 3-to-2 margin on the
New York Stock Exchange, where volume came to 310.22 million
shares, up from 294.35 at the same point on Monday. Nasdaq
decliners led by a 2-to-1 ratio.
</P>
<P>
   Before the open, the Labor Department reported that consumer
inflation jumped 0.6 percent in June, chiefly reflecting surging
gasoline prices and a record rise in the cost of natural gas.
</P>
<P>
   Most other prices posted modest increases. June's performance,
which was close to the 0.5 percent rise in consumer prices many
analysts were expecting, was the largest increase since March.
</P>
<P>
   The Federal Reserve has boosted interest rates six times over
the past 13 months to slow economic growth and keep inflation in
check. With recent reports suggesting that the Fed's rate increases
are working, some economists believe the central bank will leave
rates unchanged at its meeting Aug. 22.
</P>
<P>
   Merrill Lynch and General Motors led the morning parade of
reports on second-quarter profits with better-than-expected
results, but the day's most anxiously awaited reports, from Intel
and Microsoft, weren't due until after the close.
</P>
<P>
   Shares of Merrill slipped 87.5 cents to $131.125 while GM's rose
62.5 cents to $61. Among other leading companies, Honeywell, down
37.5 cents at $36.688, and Phillip Morris, up 43.8 cents at
$23.938, matched most Wall Street profit forecasts.
</P>
<P>
   On a more worrisome note, Aetna issued a warning that its
second-quarter results would come in well below analyst
expectations. The insurer's stock tumbled more than 13 percent,
falling $8.875 to $57.75.
</P>
<P>
   Overseas, Japan's Nikkei stock average fell 1.98 percent. In
afternoon trading, Germany's DAX index was down 0.05 percent,
Britain's FT-SE 100 was down 1.05 percent, and France's CAC-40 was
down 1.05 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
