<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ex-General Faces Trial in Sri Lanka  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   COLOMBO, Sri Lanka (AP) -- A retired general has been charged in
the deaths and disappearances of thousands of leftists, the first
high-ranking military officer to face trial in the more than
decade-old murders.
</P>
<P>
   The trial against retired Maj. Gen. Ananda Weerasekera and two
of his subordinates will begin July 31, according to an order
issued Monday by Judge Sumudhu Premachandran in the central city of
Anuradhapura.
</P>
<P>
   The men are charged with murder, abduction and unlawful
detention in connection with the disappearances of members of the
People's Freedom Front.
</P>
<P>
   The Marxist group, known as JVP, has been blamed for killing
hundreds of political opponents and government officials during a
1987-89 attempt to topple the government and seize power.
</P>
<P>
   In retaliation, human rights groups say, death squads abducted
suspected JVP supporters.
</P>
<P>
   Unmarked mass graves still turn up in the mountains and forests
of this Indian Ocean island.
</P>
<P>
   Weerasekera was the commander of an army camp in Anuradhapura
when JVP members disappeared from the area. A state appointed
commission found Weerasekera and his subordinates responsible for
the disappearances and deaths of JVP members, prompting authorities
to order a trial.
</P>
<P>
   Neither the general nor his attorneys were available for
comment.
</P>
<P>
   The JVP, which has rejoined mainstream politics, says 60,000 of
its members and supporters were killed during the uprising and
10,000 during a previous revolt in 1971.
</P>
<P>
   Formed in 1965, the JVP was banned twice after 1971. The
government lifted the ban in the early 1990s and the party
estimates it now has 50,000 members.
</P>
<P>
   The JVP won 10 percent of the votes in provincial elections this
year.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
