<DOCNO> APW20000718.0051 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-18 12:19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> House Votes For W-2 Form Disclosure  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- A worker's annual W-2 tax form would have to
also include how much the employer pays in Social Security and
Medicare taxes under legislation that passed the House Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Supporters of the measure, which passed by voice vote and now
goes to the Senate, contended that employees don't realize how much
employers pay for Social Security and Medicare.
</P>
<P>
   Employees and employers split the 12.4 percent Social Security
tax and the 2.9 percent Medicare tax, but only the employee share
shows up on the W-2 form.
</P>
<P>
   The bill, said sponsor Rep. Peter Hoekstra, R-Mich., ''helps
workers understand the constraints employers face when seeking to
create jobs, increase pay and compete effectively in a global
economy, and shatters the myth that taxes and mandates can be
placed on employers without affecting the workers themselves.''
</P>
<P>
   Workers ''are entitled to know the whole truth about how
Washington secretly takes more of their hard-earned money than they
might realize,'' said Rep. Sam Johnson, R-Texas.
</P>
<P>
   But Rep. Bob Matsui, D-Calif., said there was no secrecy
involved because the Social Security Administration this year has
begun sending out annually the aggregate amount, broken down
between employee and employer, an individual has paid in payroll
tax over his lifetime.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   The bill is H.R. 1264.
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: Congressional summary: http://thomas.loc.gov
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-07-18-00 1219 </TRAILER>
