<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-18 13:04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Arms Negotiator Cautious on China  </HEADLINE>
By ROBERT BURNS
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Although Russia strongly opposes a U.S.
national missile shield and European allies doubt its usefulness,
the toughest political obstacle may be China, the chief U.S. arms
control official said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ''The ones that we have to work on most assiduously are the
China concerns,'' Undersecretary of State John D. Holum told
reporters. ''It will take considerable work to demonstrate that
this system isn't aimed at them.''
</P>
<P>
   Defense Secretary William Cohen met with President Jiang Zemin
and other top Chinese officials in Beijing last week but reported
making little headway in overcoming their objections to missile
defense.
</P>
<P>
   In Beijing on Tuesday, Jiang and Russian President Vladimir
Putin released a joint statement accusing the United States of
using the system ''to seek unilateral military and security
advantages that will pose the most grave, adverse consequences'' to
China, Russia and the United States.
</P>
<P>
   After nearly three hours of closed talks, Putin and Jiang urged
Washington to adhere to the 28-year-old Anti-Ballistic Missile
Treaty, which prohibits the missile defense system. Their statement
asserted that altering the treaty ''will trigger an arms race and
lead to an about-face in the positive trend that appeared in world
politics after the end of the Cold War.''
</P>
<P>
   China has only a couple dozen ballistic missiles of
intercontinental range. Although the Pentagon has said its proposed
U.S. national missile shield is designed to counter a threat from
North Korea, not China or Russia, it acknowledges that the system
could defend against as many as two dozen incoming missiles.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton is expected to decide this summer or fall
whether to move forward with a plan that would build a force of 20
missile interceptors in Alaska, operating with a network of
tracking radars and high-speed computers, by 2005. The plan calls
for expanding that to 100 interceptors by 2007.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton has said that one of the factors he will consider before
making his decision is the likely international response, including
the likely effect on arms control arrangements with China and other
nations.
</P>
<P>
   ''When we tell them the system is not aimed at them, ... they
can say, 'Yes, but we have to focus on capabilities, not
intentions, and it looks to us like if you're building 100
interceptors and we have far fewer (offensive missiles) than that,
then you're building a capability against us,''' Holum said.
</P>
<P>
   ''The fact of the matter is, we're not,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   Holum said it was his ''personal expectation'' that at some
point the United States will build a national missile defense,
despite objections by other nations. ''I think national missile
defense is in our future. It's something we'll have to come to
terms with.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-07-18-00 1304 </TRAILER>
