<HEADLINE> Britain Wont't Try Bombing Suspect  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON (AP) -- Britain said Tuesday it will not prosecute a
Northern Ireland woman who is wanted for the IRA bombing of a
British army barracks in Germany.
</P>
<P>
   Roisin McAliskey was freed from jail in Britain two years ago on
compassionate grounds after supporters argued that her physical and
mental health had declined while she was in prison, where she gave
birth to a daughter.
</P>
<P>
   Home Secretary Jack Straw ruled at the time that the medical
condition made her unfit for extradition to Germany.
</P>
<P>
   In a statement to Parliament on Tuesday, the Crown Prosecution
Service said it did not have enough evidence to try McAliskey, 26,
for the 1996 bombing of a British army barracks in Osnabruck,
Germany.
</P>
<P>
   The prosecution service said that because of the time that has
elapsed since the bombing, McAliskey could claim that she would not
receive a fair trial.
</P>
<P>
   McAliskey is still wanted by German police in the attack, which
damaged buildings but injured no one.
</P>
<P>
   They believe McAliskey, the daughter of former lawmaker
Bernadette McAliskey, was part of an Irish Republican Army unit
that carried out the bombing.
</P>
<P>
   She could have been prosecuted in the Britain under the terms of
a European counterterrorism agreement.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
