<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-18 14:21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chernobyl Nuclear Plant Restarted  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   KIEV, Ukraine (AP) -- The only working reactor at the Chernobyl
atomic power plant, site of the world's worst nuclear accident, was
restarted this week after repairs, plant officials said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The reactor was shut down due to flooding caused by a storm July
10; two of its electric generators needed repairs.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday evening, one electric generator was restarted. The
other needs further work, the Chernobyl press service reported. The
reactor will work at 50 percent of capacity until the second
generator is restarted July 24, the press service said.
</P>
<P>
   A reactor at Chernobyl exploded and caught fire in 1986,
contaminating large areas in Ukraine, Russia and Belarus and
spewing a radioactive cloud across Europe. At least 8,000 people
have died as a result of the disaster, most of them from
radiation-related diseases, according to Ukrainian officials. An
estimated 3.4 million people in Ukraine still suffer from its
effects.
</P>
<P>
   Ukraine has promised to permanently shut down the plant's only
working reactor on Dec. 15.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
