<HEADLINE> Clinton Is Okinawa Summit Dean  </HEADLINE>
By The Associated Press	   Three new faces -- the prime ministers of Japan and
Italy and
Russia's new president -- will be at the table when the leaders of
the world's major industrial countries sit down Friday at their
26th annual economic summit in Nago on the Japanese island Okinawa.
<TEXT>
<P>
   President Clinton is the dean of the gatherings. The Okinawa
summit will be his eighth, tying the American record held by
another two-term president, Ronald Reagan. The overall record is
held by former German Chancellor Helmut Kohl, who attended 16.
</P>
<P>
   The annual meetings of rich countries were begun in 1975, in
response to the first global oil shock, when Gerald Ford was
president. The group reached its current size of eight countries by
officially adding Russia in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   A look at the leaders who will be around the table:
</P>
<P>
   UNITED STATES:
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton's last economic summit will be in the country
where he attended his first one, Japan. The administration is
making much of the contrast between then and now. In 1993, the
United States was in a weak recovery from recession with high
unemployment and record budget deficits, which America's allies saw
as a threat to the global economy. On Okinawa, Clinton will have
bragging rights, with the United States in the midst of its longest
economic expansion and enjoying record budget surpluses. The good
economy has kept Clinton's approval ratings high, even during his
impeachment travails, and his current approval ratings are around
60 percent. The major flaw in the good economy is a record trade
deficit, which has added to protectionist pressures. The
administration also suffered a fiasco in the riot-marred failure to
launch a new round of global trade talks in Seattle last December.
In an effort to demonstrate that globalization can work for poor
nations, Clinton will be pushing an agenda of debt relief for the
world's poorest as well as support for education and health
assistance in undeveloped countries.
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA:
</P>
<P>
   President Vladimir Putin is one of the new heads of government,
attending his first summit as successor to Boris Yeltsin. Elected
to a four-year term by a substantial margin in March, Putin
currently enjoys a 62 percent approval rating despite a continuing
bloody war in Chechnya that contradicts the Kremlin's claim that it
has broken the back of resistance in 10 months of fighting. The
Russian economy, long a basket case, is performing better, but much
of that results from recent high oil prices. If prices should fall,
Russia, a leading oil exporter, easily could see its economy stall
again. Seeking to restore some of Russia's lost global power, Putin
was making stops in China and North Korea on his way to Japan. At
the summit, he will push Clinton to abandon plans to build a
national missile defense system, which Russia sees as a significant
threat to its security.
</P>
<P>
   JAPAN:
</P>
<P>
   Prime Minister Yoshiro Mori was elevated to host of this year's
summit only last spring after the late Prime Minister Keizo Obuchi
suffered a stroke in April. Mori's short time in office has been
marked by a series of gaffes, including his reference to Japan as a
''divine nation,'' which stirred up painful memories of the
nationalistic rhetoric that led the country into World War II. A
poll showed this month a disapproval rating for Mori's Cabinet at
61.4 percent, much of the voter unhappiness stemming from Japan's
decade-long economic stagnation. Some positive signs have emerged
as the economy managed to eke out a growth rate of 0.5 percent for
the year ending in March. Unemployment remains high, however, and
government spending to stimulate the economy has driven the public
debt to record levels.
</P>
<P>
   GERMANY:
</P>
<P>
   Chancellor Gerhard Schroeder has gained in stature since playing
host to last year's summit in Cologne. He has been helped by a
slush fund scandal engulfing Helmut Kohl, his predecessor, and a
booming German economy. The growth rate is expected to be the
highest this year since German unification in 1990. A big worry for
Schroeder going into the summit is Russian debt. Germany is
Russia's biggest creditor, accounting for half the debt owed by the
government in Moscow. Germany is ready to grant generous
rescheduling terms but adamantly opposes forgiving any of the debt.
German officials worry that the Clinton administration will push
its allies to go further and offer some degree of a debt write-off
to help Putin's new government.
</P>
<P>
   BRITAIN:
</P>
<P>
   Prime Minister Tony Blair, who took office after a landslide
victory in 1997, is suffering midterm blues and looks vulnerable
after a string of embarrassments, including being booed and heckled
during a speech to a women's group and the recent arrest of his
16-year-old son Euan on a charge of being drunk in a public square.
Blair's problems include a public perception that there has been
little progress improving government services or cutting waiting
times for the National Health Service. Still, polls show Blair's
Labor Party with a double-digit lead over the opposition
Conservatives. Much of this comes from the strong British economy,
which has pushed unemployment to a 20-year low. Blair, like the
other G-8 leaders, plans to stress how rich countries can help the
poor in debt relief, education, health and technology.
</P>
<P>
   FRANCE:
</P>
<P>
   President Jacques Chirac slightly trails Prime Minister Lionel
Jospin in the public opinion polls as both have found
''cohabitation'' between a conservative president and a Socialist
prime minister to be trying. Globalization is a major issue in
France, where it is often a code word for what the French see as
America's overbearing stance on international issues. Jose Bove, a
radical French farmer who vandalized a McDonald's restaurant as a
blow against globalization is a folk hero in France. Chirac will
try for support to regulate globalization to ensure that national
cultures, traditions and products can survive in the new world
economic order.
</P>
<P>
   CANADA:
</P>
<P>
   Prime Minister Jean Chretien, who took office in 1993, is the
second longest-serving G-8 leader after Clinton. Unlike the U.S.
president, who is constitutionally limited to two terms, Chretien
has said he wants to run for a third term next year. He still has
the strongest poll numbers of any major political figure in Canada,
and his Liberal Party is considered the likely winner in federal
elections expected within a year. Chretien has supported free trade
and globalization. Officials of the Canadian government said that
Chretien would use the summit to increase Third World countries'
access to the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   ITALY:
</P>
<P>
   Guiliano Amato was sworn in as head of Italy's 58th postwar
government in April on the resignation of Massimo D'Alema after a
poor showing in regional elections by the ruling center-left
coalition. Amato, a Socialist-turned-independent, is the third
premier from the center-left since that bloc won power in 1996
parliamentary elections. The 10-party governing coalition, which
includes Communists, environmentalists and former Christian
Democrats, has squabbled constantly and has yet to decide on a
premier candidate, although Amato has hinted he would resign before
his term ended if the center-left should choose another candidate.
High unemployment, the government budget deficit and rising
inflation are the biggest economic issues facing the country. On
the eve of the G-8 summit, Italy's parliament pledged to forgive
more than $4 billion in debt owed by 62 poor countries over the
next three years under easier terms than those set by the others.
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: Japan's summit site:
http://www.g8kyushu-okinawa.go.jp
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
