<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Study Links Reflux, Genetics  </HEADLINE>
By LINDSEY TANNER
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO (AP) -- Researchers have zeroed in on a possible genetic
cause for a common ailment in children that has been linked to
recurring respiratory illnesses and perhaps even some crib deaths.
</P>
<P>
   The study was small and the findings are preliminary, but it
could eventually lead to better diagnosis and treatment of
gastroesophageal reflux disease, scientists said.
</P>
<P>
   The study in Wednesday's Journal of the American Medical
Association comes less than a week after Propulsid -- a drug that is
commonly used to treat the disease in infants but has been linked
to serious heart problems and 80 deaths -- was taken off the market.
</P>
<P>
   Using genetic mapping techniques on five families with affected
children, investigators found a marker suggesting there is a gene
that causes at least one form of the disease.
</P>
<P>
   They didn't actually find the gene but discovered evidence that
one exists.
</P>
<P>
   Previous research suggested the ailment is inherited. The study
is believed to be the first to locate a genetic marker.
</P>
<P>
   The disease affects an estimated 10 million children each year,
though the researchers said it is vastly underdiagnosed. It causes
stomach acid to back up into the esophagus, usually because of a
relaxation of the valve-like muscle that keeps the lower end of the
esophagus closed after eating or drinking.
</P>
<P>
   In children, the main symptom is spitting up or coughing. Most
youngsters outgrow it. It is also believed to be a cause of
recurring colds and upper respiratory infections.
</P>
<P>
   In very few cases, experts think it is a cause of some choking
deaths mistakenly attributed to Sudden Infant Death Syndrome, said
Dr. Christopher Post, a co-author of the study by researchers at
Allegheny General Hospital in Pittsburgh.
</P>
<P>
   Heartburn is the major symptom in 40 million adults affected by
the ailment. It can cause constant throat irritation that can lead
to esophageal cancer. Treatment includes diet, drugs and sometimes
surgery.
</P>
<P>
   If a culprit gene is found, doctors may be able to diagnose the
disease with a simple blood test instead of an invasive procedure,
Post said.
</P>
<P>
   Doctors outside the study agreed it could be a breakthrough.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's novel, it's provocative and I think it raises a lot of
important things that need to be looked at long-term,'' said Dr.
Benjamin D. Gold, director of pediatric gastroenterology and
nutrition at Emory University.
</P>
<P>
   One drawback is that so few families were studied, said Dr.
Frank Hamilton of the National Institute of Diabetes and Digestive
and Kidney Diseases. Still, he called the results promising.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: National Institutes of Health:
http://www.niddk.nih.gov/health/digest/pubs/heartbrn/heartbrn.htm
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-07-18-00 1601 </TRAILER>
