<DOCNO> APW20000718.0078 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-18 16:03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Archaeologist to return Indian remains, artifacts under settlement  </HEADLINE>
By CAROLYN THOMPSON
<TEXT>
<P>
   HAMBURG, N.Y. (AP) - An archaeologist who dug up remains at an
Indian burial site and stored them in boxes in an office hallway
will return them to the Senecas under a settlement that state
officials say will protect sacred grounds in the future.
</P>
<P>
   The Seneca Nation of Indians, Tonawanda Seneca Nation and
Attorney General Eliot Spitzer last year sued R. Michael Gramly
under a 1990 federal statute to protect Indian remains and
artifacts. It was the first such action taken by a state under the
Native American Graves Protection and Repatriation Act, Spitzer
said.
</P>
<P>
   Gramly was accused of digging up graves at the site of a 17th
Century Indian village about 15 miles south of Buffalo as part of a
field course offered at Canisius College, where he is an adjunct
professor. The excavations took place over two years beginning in
1998.
</P>
<P>
   ''Dr. Gramly had come to this site, dug up artifacts and abused
them, taken them back to his office, and human artifacts simply
laid in boxes, unpreserved,'' Spitzer said at the site Tuesday.
''No effort was made to ensure the integrity of those artifacts.''
</P>
<P>
   Spitzer said the college was not aware federal law was violated.
</P>
<P>
   Under the settlement, Gramly, a former curator at the Buffalo
Museum of Science, agreed to repatriate all human remains and
cultural items to the Indians and to refrain from excavating any
other Native American burial grounds in New York.
</P>
<P>
   Gramly did not return telephone calls to his business seeking
comment. His lawyer, Richard Yellin, described Gramly as a
professional and told The Buffalo News Gramly only undertook the
excavation because the land owner wanted to build at the site.
</P>
<P>
   ''If there is no protection, this is what happens,'' said Seneca
Nation President Duane Ray.
</P>
<P>
   David Schenne, an antiques dealer from Brant, said in court
papers that he saw boxes of bones in the hallway at Gramly's
office.
</P>
<P>
   ''Gramly said they contained the remains of seven Native
Americans from the Kleis site,'' Schenne said. He said Gramly also
told him a ceramic pot displayed in his office was also from the
site.
</P>
<P>
   Ray said death begins a journey for Native Americans. ''When
these sites are disturbed ... that journey stops.''
</P>
<P>
   The remains and other items have been reburied on the Tonawanda
reservation, said Richard Hill, chairman of the Haudenosaunee
Standing Committee on Burial Rules and Regulations.
</P>
<P>
   The settlement removes some of the sadness over seeing the site
disturbed, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's kind of amazing in the year 2000 that our dead people are
considered archaeological resources that are meant for study,''
Hill said. ''They're not artifacts. They were real live people at
one time.''
</P>
<P>
   The site across from the Erie County Fairgrounds, known as the
Kleis Site after its former owner, was believed to have been a
village of the Erie tribe from 1620 to 1640.
</P>
<P>
   The Eries were defeated in a 17th Century battle with the
Senecas and were either eliminated as a tribe or incorporated into
the Senecas.
</P>
<P>
   Spitzer said the settlement would establish a template for
protection of all Indian burial sites. The 1990 statute requires
that lineal descendants of those buried approve excavations and
requires permits be obtained.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-07-18-00 1603 </TRAILER>
