<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sleep Evasive at Camp David  </HEADLINE>
By LAURA KING
<TEXT>
<P>
   THURMONT, Md. (AP) -- There's something about Middle East
peacemaking that just doesn't lend itself to anyone getting a good
night's sleep.
</P>
<P>
   As at past peace summits, the negotiators at the 8-day-old Camp
David talks have taken to pulling all-nighters in their final push
to hammer out an accord.
</P>
<P>
   ''A variety of people have been up for most of the night for the
last three nights, so I think you can expect that they're tired,
but they're staying at it,'' said President Clinton's chief
spokesman, Joe Lockhart.
</P>
<P>
   With late nights the norm at Camp David, the presidential
retreat in the Catoctin Mountains, negotiators at parallel talks
being held in nearby Emmitsburg, Md., were burning the midnight oil
as well, the American organizers said.
</P>
<P>
   It helps that Clinton is a confirmed night owl, as are his
negotiating partners, Prime Minister Ehud Barak and Palestinian
leader Yasser Arafat.
</P>
<P>
   Back home, talks by Barak and Arafat are usually late at night.
The Palestinian leader, in particular, has a reputation for wearing
out his aides with the grueling hours he routinely keeps.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday night, Clinton headed into a meeting with Barak that
didn't break until after 4 a.m. Tuesday, the White House said. But
the night's work still wasn't over -- he then conferred with aides
before turning in.
</P>
<P>
   ''The president's night, or more accurately morning, ended at
about 5 a.m.,'' Lockhart told reporters. Clinton was up again at
about 10 a.m. to meet with his negotiating team.
</P>
<P>
   Keeping long hours is a time-honored bargaining tactic at Middle
East summits. When Israel and the Palestinians talked peace two
years ago at Wye River, Clinton several times led talkfests that
lasted into the early morning, insisting the sessions continue long
after some participants wanted to beg off and go to bed.
</P>
<P>
   Accounts in the Israeli press afterward suggested Clinton had
cannily used sheer fatigue to wear down the parties and get them to
soften their positions. The summit resulted in an interim peace
accord.
</P>
<P>
   At the first Camp David summit, in 1978, then-President Jimmy
Carter spent one sleepless night not in negotiations, but fretting
about the health and well-being of Egyptian President Anwar Sadat.
</P>
<P>
   After Sadat retired unexpectedly early one night, former
National Security Council staffer William Quandt related in a
memoir about the watershed negotiations that Carter called the
Secret Service at 4 a.m., worried that something might have
happened to the Egyptian leader.
</P>
<P>
   ''When the sun rose, Sadat was out for his usual morning walk,
and Carter breathed a sigh of relief,'' Quandt wrote.
</P>
<P>
   With the current Camp David talks facing an unofficial deadline
of Wednesday, when Clinton is to depart for Japan, Lockhart was
asked if the president was prepared to once again talk all night.
</P>
<P>
   ''Sure,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
