<HEADLINE> Au Pair's Ex-Lawyer:Claim Was False  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHESTER, England (AP) -- A former lawyer for Louise Woodward
testified at the trial of the British au pair's parents on Tuesday
that an expense claim submitted by the couple was ''a complete
forgery.''
</P>
<P>
   Susan and Gary Woodward are charged with defrauding an appeal
fund set up in their daughter's name by claiming false expenses.
The couple claimed $15,400 to cover Susan Woodward's accommodations
in Boston, where Louise Woodward was tried on murder charges in
1997.
</P>
<P>
   But the lawyer, Elaine Whitfield Sharp -- who represented Louise
Woodward during her trial for the death of a baby in her care --
said she had put Susan Woodward up at her home before the trial
free of charge.
</P>
<P>
   The invoice -- which Whitfield Sharp called ''a complete
forgery'' -- was submitted to the Louise Woodward and Family Trust,
stating that the lawyer charged Woodward $2,200 a month to stay in
her spare bedroom.
</P>
<P>
   The Woodwards, both 44 and now estranged, deny fraud.
</P>
<P>
   Under questioning by prosecution lawyer Bernard Lever, Whitfield
Sharp told the court, ''That would be outrageous. It would be
extortionate.''
</P>
<P>
   ''Apart from the fact I wouldn't charge somebody to stay in the
spare bedroom after inviting them into my home, I think $2,200 is
an outlandish figure.''
</P>
<P>
   She also said the Woodwards had sold an interview to a British
newspaper without telling her.
</P>
<P>
   ''They denied they had sold any story. Indeed, a press release
was issued under my name denying a story had been sold when in fact
it had,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Louise Woodward was charged with killing 8-month-old Matthew
Eappen while working as an au pair at his parents' home. She was
convicted of second-degree murder in October 1997, but the trial
judge reduced the verdict to manslaughter and she was freed after
spending 279 days in jail.
</P>
<P>
   Whitfied Sharp rejected accusations by defense lawyer Nick
Johnson that she ''had it in for the Woodwards'' and that her
husband had been paid thousands of dollars in cash by Gary
Woodward.
</P>
<P>
   Louise Woodward, now 22, is listed as a defense witness in the
trial, which is expected to last three weeks.
</P>
</TEXT>
