<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-18 16:24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Treasury Secretary Promotes Savings  </HEADLINE>
By JEANNINE AVERSA
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- With the rate of personal savings at a record
low, Treasury Secretary Lawrence Summers announced some measures
Tuesday aimed at boosting participation in retirement savings
plans.
</P>
<P>
   ''We must raise the level of personal saving, by encouraging
individual Americans to save more,'' Summers said in a speech at a
Labor Department event underscoring the importance of saving for
retirement.
</P>
<P>
   Roughly 75 million Americans do not participate in any
retirement savings plan and have little or no savings, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Specifically, Summers said that the Internal Revenue Service is
issuing new rules making it easier for small businesses, public
schools, charitable organizations and state and local governments
to automatically enroll employees in retirement savings plans.
</P>
<P>
   Under automatic enrollment, employers that sponsor retirement
savings plans such as 401(k) plans can assume employees are
participating and deduct a stated amount from their pay to
contribute to the savings plan. Employees have the right to opt out
of these plans. Traditionally, employees must specifically request
to participate in a retirement savings plan.
</P>
<P>
   Separately, House lawmakers are expected to consider legislation
Thursday intended to beef up tax-free contributions and deductions
to private retirement plans. The measure, among other things, would
gradually raise the current $2,000 annual contribution limit for
traditional and Roth individual retirement accounts to $5,000 in
2003. The limit would thereafter rise each year based on inflation.
</P>
<P>
   The new IRS rulings extend the option of automatic enrollment to
so-called 403(b) retirement plans, which serve millions of
employees of public schools and other educational and charitable
organizations, and to 457(b) plans that serve employees of state
and local governments, Summers said.
</P>
<P>
   Another IRS ruling allows the automatic enrollment to be offered
in standardized retirement plans most often used by small
businesses. And, under another IRS ruling, employers are allowed to
automatically roll over a departing employee's balance to an IRA
set up for that employee, unless the employee explicitly directs
otherwise.
</P>
<P>
   In the first three months of 2000, the nation's personal savings
rate -- savings as a percentage of disposable income -- fell to a
quarterly low of 0.3 percent. That's not as dire as it seems
because the rate doesn't capture such things as rising stock values
and higher real-estate values for homes.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: The Treasury Department site:
http://www.ustreas.gov/
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
