<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Hunt Continues for Penguin  </HEADLINE>
By MIKE COHEN
<TEXT>
<P>
   CAPE TOWN, South Africa (AP) -- Scientists want to study him,
journalists want to photograph him and millions of South Africans
just want reassurance that their beloved Peter is OK after he
survived an oil spill and swam 470 miles back to his home.
</P>
<P>
   The only problem is no one knows exactly where the celebrity
penguin is.
</P>
<P>
   Driving rain and howling wind prevented people from taking the
boat trip to Peter's home to greet the 18-inch tall hero on his
return Tuesday to Robben Island.
</P>
<P>
   Scientists, who glued a tracking device to his back, know he's
there somewhere. But even when boats begin running again, the
search for Peter will be a difficult one: the device tracks him
only to within about 500 feet, and the island, four miles off Cape
Town, is covered with thick bush under which the penguins nest in
burrows.
</P>
<P>
   ''It will take a couple of days of astute detective work to
track him down,'' said Les Underhill of the University of Cape
Town's avian demography unit, which has been tracking the birds.
</P>
<P>
   Peter was among 20,000 penguins trucked to the town of Port
Elizabeth and released to make the long swim home, giving
authorities time to clean up an oil spill from a tanker that sank
June 23.
</P>
<P>
   About 23,000 other penguins, which had been coated by oil, are
being cared for by volunteers and the Southern African National
Foundation for the Conservation of Coastal Birds in rehabilitation
centers in Cape Town.
</P>
<P>
   But authorities were not able to capture all the penguins soiled
or threatened by the spill, and there has been no estimate on how
many birds were killed.
</P>
<P>
   The local media, meanwhile, have turned Peter, along with two
other tracked penguins, Percy and Pamela, into celebrities, and
thousands have followed their progress via the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Percy, who lives on Dassen Island about 40 miles northwest of
Cape Town and was released July 5, was expected home within a day
or two. Pamela, who was released July 3, was taking her time
getting back, swimming only about 25 miles a day.
</P>
<P>
   African penguins, which are listed as vulnerable to extinction,
are found only off the coast of southern Africa. The population is
estimated at between 150,000 and 180,000 -- 10 percent of what it
was thought to be 100 years ago, according to the World Wildlife
Fund.
</P>
<P>
   Dassen Island, where an estimated 55,000 birds lived, holds the
world's largest colony of African penguins. The third-largest
colony is on Robben Island, a nature reserve and museum that used
to serve as a prison for apartheid-era political prisoners,
including former President Nelson Mandela.
</P>
<P>
   Scientists want to weigh Peter and check his condition after his
19-day swim, which began June 30, while television crews and
photographers are scrambling for pictures of him after his odyssey.
</P>
<P>
   ''Welcome home Pete, wherever you might be,'' read a headline on
the front page of Tuesday's Cape Times newspaper.
</P>
<P>
   Dozens of tagged penguins taken from Dassen Island to Port
Elizabeth had begun arriving home, some of them taking as little as
11 days to complete the trip using their natural homing instinct,
Underhill said.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, more than 8,000 of the captured, soiled birds have
been washed, and the first batch of 300 were released Tuesday in
Port Elizabeth, said Simon Pope of the International Fund for
Animal Welfare, which has flown in international bird experts to
help cope with the crisis.
</P>
<P>
   Fewer than 400 captured birds had died, Pope said.
</P>
<P>
   Bird experts are hailing the rehabilitation project as one of
the most successful ever undertaken.
</P>
<P>
   The Panamanian tanker the Treasure was carrying 1,300 tons of
oil when it sank. About 205 tons of the oil remaining in the wreck
have been pumped into other vessels.
</P>
<P>
   Captain Bill Dernier of the South African Maritime Authority
said while salvage operations had been halted by bad weather it
seemed as if no more heavy bunker oil was trapped in its tanks.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   Penguin site, http://www.uct.ac.za/depts/stats/adu/
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
