<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-18 16:38 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Haiti Risks Aid for Election Result  </HEADLINE>
By MICHAEL NORTON
<TEXT>
<P>
   PORT-AU-PRINCE, Haiti (AP) -- Defying threats of an international
aid cutoff, Haiti's leaders are sticking with disputed election
results that could give former President Jean-Bertrand Aristide a
stranglehold on power for a decade.
</P>
<P>
   After more than a week there are no results from the second
round of voting -- but Aristide's Lavalas Party seems firmly in
charge.
</P>
<P>
   Hotly disputed first-round results gave Lavalas the Senate and
local posts key to wielding and perpetuating power, and the second
will almost certainly give it the lower house of Parliament.
</P>
<P>
   Since Aristide truly is popular, many ask why Lavalas would
bother to cheat.
</P>
<P>
   ''Lavalas would have won, even if it had played fair,'' said
taxi driver Marc Descollines, 32. ''But it wanted to wipe out the
opposition.''
</P>
<P>
   It is widely considered inevitable that Aristide, whom many see
as a savior, will win back the presidency in voting later this
year.
</P>
<P>
   That has helped his party. Hungry and hopeless while their
politicians bickered and enriched themselves, Haitians tired of
government gridlock; many voted for Lavalas -- which didn't control
the outgoing Parliament but has the presidency and the real strings
of power -- to ensure lawmakers and local leaders could work with
the president.
</P>
<P>
   But opposition leaders say Lavalas wanted more. They say they
were intimidated during the campaign, robbed of a proper
poll-watcher presence, and denied victories in fraudulent counting
of the May 21 first round.
</P>
<P>
   They fear the goal is not only single-party rule but a one-party
state.
</P>
<P>
   That would make a mockery of the 1994 U.S.-led invasion to
restore Aristide -- the first freely elected Haitian ruler, deposed
in an army coup three years before -- and the multibillion-dollar
international aid effort that followed.
</P>
<P>
   Some $500 million is currently frozen, awaiting a legitimate
government -- a situation oddly reminiscent of the international
sanctions during military rule that left Haiti in utter ruin.
</P>
<P>
   The European Union, the United States and Canada -- Haiti's
biggest donors -- all threatened last week to further withhold aid
if there are no new elections for Senate seats improperly awarded
to Lavalas.
</P>
<P>
   Haitian law requires an absolute majority to win -- but officials
counted ballots cast for only the top four contenders,
unapologetically skewing percentages for Aristide candidates who,
while front-runners, would have faced a second round.
</P>
<P>
   Electoral council chairman Leon Manus, who fled to the United
States last month fearing for his life, said Lavalas won five seats
in the 27-seat Senate, and not 16 of the 17 contested seats as
announced. Manus also cited the ''active role played by some
elements of the police in certain fraudulent acts: theft of ballot
boxes and falsification of tally sheets.''
</P>
<P>
   Haitian authorities ignored international pleas for new
elections and went ahead with July 9 runoffs that opposition
parties boycotted. Less than 10 percent of voters turned out --
compared to 55 percent in the first round.
</P>
<P>
   The opposition points to first-round results giving Lavalas 80
percent of city halls and a majority of urban and rural councils --
bodies that appoint judges and shape the electoral council that
will organize voting for the next nine years.
</P>
<P>
   ''In one fell swoop, Aristide has won decisive power over future
elections and control of the judicial system,'' said Myrlande
Manigat, a professor of constitutional law who was an opposition
Senate candidate. ''What is at stake is control of Haitian
institutions for at least a decade.''
</P>
<P>
   There are also fears Lavalas might eliminate the clause in
Haiti's constitution forbidding consecutive terms -- restoring a
tradition of one-man rule through lifetime presidencies.
</P>
<P>
   ''Aristide for life!'' supporters yelled at a rally last week.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-07-18-00 1638 </TRAILER>
