<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-18 16:39 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> NRC to begin hearing on spent fuel storage  </HEADLINE>
dsnldrh
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW LONDON, Conn. (AP) - With no solution in sight to the need
for a nuclear fuel dump, Northeast Utilities is asking federal
regulators to increase the capacity of the Millstone Three spent
fuel rod pool.
</P>
<P>
   The Atomic Safety and Licensing Board is reviewing Northeast
Utilities' plans and the concerns of area residents and
anti-nuclear activists during at least two days of hearings this
week.
</P>
<P>
   A public hearing was scheduled for Tuesday night. A formal
hearing before the board was scheduled for Wednesday, continuing
Thursday if necessary.
</P>
<P>
   Northeast Utilities says the spent fuel rod pool is designed to
hold many more used rods than its license allows. The company is
asking to increase the number of fuel rods permitted in the pool.
</P>
<P>
   The system looks like a 40-foot-deep, L-shaped swimming pool.
The fuel rods are stored in bundles called assemblies, which are
held on racks submerged at the bottom of the pool.
</P>
<P>
   Water laced with boron is circulated around the pool to keep the
fuel cool and prevent a nuclear reaction.
</P>
<P>
   The issue has attracted attention on both sides of Long Island
Sound near the Waterford nuclear complex. Anti-Millstone groups
from Connecticut and New York have been given permission to
participate in the hearing.
</P>
<P>
   Currently, the Millstone Three pool contains about 450
assemblies. The plant is licensed to store up to 756 assemblies. NU
wants to store up to 1,800 but says the pool is big enough to
safely accommodate 2,000.
</P>
<P>
   Company spokesman Joe Pillittere said the storage plan is safe
and has been analyzed from many angles as required by the Nuclear
Regulatory Commission.
</P>
<P>
   ''To put this in terms a homeowner would understand, we're not
talking about adding a new room to our house. We're just finishing
the basement,'' Pillittere said.
</P>
<P>
   Nuclear plant operators need to store spent fuel on site because
the federal government has not yet come up with a permanent storage
place.
</P>
<P>
   Some anti-nuclear activists believe it would be safer to store
the fuel in secure concrete vaults, since the water storage system
could fail if pumps broke or water leaks out.
</P>
<P>
   Others oppose any expansion of the fuel storage capacity at all,
hoping that the plant will have to shut down if there is no place
to store the waste.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-07-18-00 1639 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000718.0087 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-18 16:39 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 'Survivor' Thrives in TV Ratings  </HEADLINE>
By DAVID BAUDER
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Maybe NBC should force major league baseball's
all-stars to dine on rats or live together in the same house for a
couple of months.
</P>
<P>
   Anything to stem the loss of viewers. In a week when the CBS
series ''Survivor'' continued on its ratings roll, baseball's
annual All-Star Game had the fewest number of households tuned in
since 1969, Nielsen Media Research said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   An estimated 14.7 million people watched the American League's
victory last week, an audience barely more than half of what the
game routinely drew in the mid-1980s.
</P>
<P>
   It couldn't even nudge NBC out of third place in last week's
ratings race, although the network narrowly won among the 18-49 age
demographic it covets.
</P>
<P>
   ''Survivor'' was again the week's most-watched program, with an
estimated 24.5 million people watching the Pagong and Tagi tribes
merge into the Rattana tribe.
</P>
<P>
   ''Big Brother'' routinely draws a much smaller audience. But in
one positive development for CBS, the reality show beat a rerun of
''Friends'' on Thursday as the houseguests nominated two of their
own for banishment.
</P>
<P>
   Summer TV viewership took its traditional dive. The top four
broadcasters had an average prime-time viewership of 34 million
last week, compared to the 45 million they draw on a typical week.
</P>
<P>
   ABC, with the help of three new ''Who Wants to Be a
Millionaire'' editions, won the week with an average viewership of
9.6 million (6.6 rating, 12 share). CBS had 9.2 million viewers
(6.5, 12) and NBC had 9 million viewers (6.3, 12). Fox had 6.2
million viewers (4.0, 7)
</P>
<P>
   UPN led the smaller networks with 3.1 million viewers (2.1
rating, 4 share), the WB had 2.4 million viewers (1.8, 3) and Pax
TV had 1.3 million (1,0, 2). The premiere of the WB's summer
series, ''Young Americans'' was the network's second most-watched
show.
</P>
<P>
   NBC's ''Nightly News'' dominated the evening news ratings race
with 9.5 million viewers (7.1 rating, 16 share). ABC's ''World News
Tonight'' had 8.6 million viewers (6.7, 15), while the ''CBS
Evening News'' had 7.5 million viewers (5.8, 13).
</P>
<P>
   A rating point represents 1,008,000 households, or 1 percent of
the nation's estimated 100.8 million TV homes. The share is the
percentage of in-use televisions tuned to a given show.
</P>
<P>
   For the week of July 10-16, the top 10 shows, their networks and
ratings were:
</P>
<P>
   ''Survivor,'' CBS, 15.0; ''Who Wants to Be a Millionaire''
(Thursday), ABC, 14.7; ''Who Wants to Be a Millionaire'' (Tuesday),
ABC, 14.1; ''Who Wants to Be a Millionaire'' (Sunday), ABC, 13.7;
''20/20 Downtown,'' ABC, 10.2; ''Major League Baseball All-Star
Game,'' NBC, 10.1; ''The Practice,'' ABC, 9.5; ''Law and Order,''
NBC, 9.1; ''Everybody Loves Raymond,'' CBS, 8.8; ''Judging Amy''
special, CBS, 8.4.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: http://www.nielsenmedia.com
</P>
</TEXT>
