<HEADLINE> Hearing for suspect in 1975 rapes scheduled for Friday  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   OSWEGO, N.Y. (AP) - Gary Burns eluded prosecution for raping two
Oswego County teen-age girls in 1975, and all these years later
he'll try to avoid the witness stand again.
</P>
<P>
   The lawyer representing Burns, 60, who now lives in Canon City,
Colo., goes to court Friday to have the case against his client
dismissed, arguing that Burns never received a speedy trial.
</P>
<P>
   Burns eluded prosecution by leaving the state in 1976 after
being indicted on two counts of first-degree rape, a felony, said
Chief Assistant District Attorney Donald Dodd. Although authorities
in Texas picked him up on a warrant shortly afterward, Burns
challenged his extradition and a Texas judge let him go, Dodd said.
</P>
<P>
   Burns has been out of sight since then, local authorities said.
Until January, when a state police investigator tracked him down
again and brought him back to answer the charges.
</P>
<P>
   Burns' lawyer, Jim Nicholson, paints a different picture. He
said Burns was arrested three other times in Texas since the judge
set him free and questions whether authorities tried hard enough to
find Burns over the years.
</P>
<P>
   Nicholson filed a motion in June to dismiss the case. Nicholson
and Dodd are scheduled to argue the motion Friday in front of
Oswego County Court Judge Walter Hafner.
</P>
<P>
   Burns is accused of committing two rapes in July and November
1975. When he was indicted, Burns fled to Texas, Dodd said.
Authorities there caught him on a warrant based on the indictments.
</P>
<P>
   Burns spent three months in jail during the extradition process,
Nicholson said.
</P>
<P>
   Burns contested the warrant and placed the burden on the
authorities to justify his detention and extradition, Dodd and
Nicholson said. A judge threw out the extradition papers as
defective, Nicholson said.
</P>
<P>
   Burns thought that was the end of his case in New York,
Nicholson said. It wasn't.
</P>
<P>
   In early January, state police Investigator Lee Pavlot plugged
Burns' name into the same database to which the U.S. marshals
subscribe and came up with possible leads to Burns' whereabouts in
Colorado.
</P>
<P>
   Pavlot is with the state police violent felony warrant squad,
responsible for tracking down people charged with such crimes as
rape or murder, he said. He had recently begun using the marshal's
database, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Before that, the process wasn't quite so simple, Pavlot said.
</P>
<P>
   The warrant squad, formed in 1979, gets a weekly printout of all
outstanding warrants in its jurisdiction, and Burns has been on
that list for about 20 years.
</P>
<P>
   Without access to the marshal's database, investigators would
periodically plug the fugitives' names into a national crime
information database. All that would show is whether a warrant was
still valid, Pavlot said.
</P>
<P>
   Here's the catch: When someone is arrested, police across the
country are supposed to check the database for an outstanding
warrant. If there is one, police are supposed to notify the
previous police agency, he said. If that doesn't happen, the
original police agency is left in the dark.
</P>
<P>
   Burns was arrested three times in Texas after the judge first
set him free in 1976, and even went to jail once, Nicholson said.
</P>
<P>
   But the information apparently never was passed on to Oswego
County. Dodd said he was not aware of those arrests.
</P>
<P>
   Pavlot followed up on the initial lead from the marshal's
database and found an address for Burns in Canon City, in central
Colorado.
</P>
<P>
   A marshal and two Canon City police detectives knocked on the
door and arrested Burns without a struggle on Jan. 19, said Chief
Deputy Larry Homenick of the U.S. marshals office.
</P>
<P>
   Two Oswego County sheriff's investigators brought Burns back to
New York in April, Sheriff Reuel Todd said. Burns has been in the
Oswego County jail since, held without bail.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
