<HEADLINE> Spitzer gets a little help from his family  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) - State Attorney General Eliot Spitzer's
campaign committee raised $851,874 during the first six months of
this year, including $200,000 from his mother and father, records
showed Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Democrat Spitzer's filing with the state Board of Elections
showed he had $767,878 on hand as of the end of June for his
expected re-election race in 2002.
</P>
<P>
   The filing also showed his father, New York City real estate
developer Bernard Spitzer, gave his son's campaign committee
$100,000 while his mother, Anne Spitzer, also kicked in $100,000
earlier this year. Spitzer's brother, Dr. David Spitzer,
contributed $6,000 to his brother's campaign committee.
</P>
<P>
   Spitzer unsuccessful run for attorney general in 1994 and his
winning run in 1998 were financed in large part by loans from his
father and bank loans taken out against Spitzer's real estate
holdings. Spitzer spent more than $10 million on his 1998 campaign.
</P>
<P>
   The latest campaign filing shows Spitzer ''will run in 2002 with
a solid financial base,'' spokesman Darren Dopp said.
</P>
<P>
   Spitzer's list of contributors for the first six months of this
year runs to 57 pages.
</P>
</TEXT>
