<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-18 16:44 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Judge weighs whether Cayugas deserve interest on jury award  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   SYRACUSE, N.Y. (AP) - According to real estate notebooks from
the late 1700s, the land around Cayuga Lake was classified as of
particular high value, an anthropologist testified Tuesday at the
trial that will determine whether the Cayuga Indian Nation gets
interest on its $37 million land claim award.
</P>
<P>
   Professor Peter Whiteley, an expert in America's indigenous
societies from Sarah Lawrence College in Bronxville, N.Y., said
that New York state got a real deal when it purchased land from the
Cayugas, who by the early 1800s were basically landless.
</P>
<P>
   ''The Cayugas had no other means of economic support'' (at that
time),'' Whiteley said. ''New York State paid $4,800 for land
valued at least three times that much.''
</P>
<P>
   Whiteley, the first witness called as the Cayugas attempt to
convince U.S. District Judge Neal McCurn to increase their land
claim award, also said that in the mid-1800s the New York state
Legislature approved measures saying that the Cayugas should be
compensated for the differences between the purchase price and sale
of their land. In both instances, funds were never provided, he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Whiteley, who is being paid $120 an hour by the Cayugas for
research and testimony in the case, also testified that a special
investigator recommended to top state officials to pay $247,609 to
the Cayugas a century ago and that both sides agreed. However, the
governor did not, and a later report from the state attorney
general's office advised against settling for that figure.
</P>
<P>
   McCurn will hear from as many as 13 witnesses as he decides
whether to increase the Cayuga's award. The trial, which began
Monday, is expected to last at least four weeks.
</P>
<P>
   A jury in February awarded the Cayugas $36.9 million in damages
for the loss of 64,027 acres of ancestral homelands in Cayuga and
Seneca counties.
</P>
<P>
   McCurn ruled in 1994 that New York illegally acquired the land
in 1795 and 1807 by purchasing it from the Cayugas without the
federal government's required approval.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
