<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-18 16:49 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> French Troops Battle Angry Serbs  </HEADLINE>
By ROBERT H. REID
<TEXT>
<P>
   KOSOVSKA MITROVICA, Yugoslavia (AP) -- Angry over the arrest of a
Serb militant for allegedly attacking ethnic Albanians, thousands
of Serbs blocked roads Tuesday into their part of this Kosovo city
and staged mass rallies to demand the suspect's release.
</P>
<P>
   French soldiers backed by six armored personnel carriers blocked
the main bridge over the Ibar River, which divides the Serb and
ethnic Albanian community, refusing to allow even U.N. employees to
cross.
</P>
<P>
   Serb leaders warned of more violence if the suspect, one of a
group of tough Serb men who guard the north side of the bridge, was
not released. A Serb delegation was to meet U.N. officials
Wednesday to discuss the issue.
</P>
<P>
   U.N. spokesman Mike Keats said the trouble started after the
suspect, Dalibor Vukovic, was arrested Monday evening on charges of
setting fire to Albanian cars June 9.
</P>
<P>
   Hundreds of angry Serbs laid siege to the main U.N. police
station in the Serb area, pelting it with stones until French
peacekeepers fired tear gas and stun grenades to disperse them.
</P>
<P>
   French officials said four Serbs and two U.N. policemen were
injured in the Monday night clash. Serb media put the figure at
nine Serbs injured, including a 15-year-old boy who suffered a
gunshot wound.
</P>
<P>
   An unidentified U.N. policeman was seized by the crowd Monday
night but later released after a local Serb leader intervened on
his behalf, U.N. police said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
   The arrest provoked a strong public reaction here in the largest
Serb community remaining in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Several hundred Serbs -- men, women and children -- massed Tuesday
afternoon in front of the police station, and speakers claimed the
detention was another example of U.N. and NATO favoritism toward
the ethnic Albanian majority.
</P>
<P>
   ''The international bad guys are provoking us,'' a member of the
Serb National Council, Dr. Milan Ivanovic, told the crowd. ''We
cannot stand idly by and see the Clintons and the Albrights do
whatever they want.''
</P>
<P>
   Serbs in the crowd said that unless Vukovic was freed Tuesday,
they would attack U.N. and NATO targets here in Kosovo's most
ethnically tense city.
</P>
<P>
   But the United Nations refused to release Vukovic. After hours
of meetings between Serb leaders and U.N. officials, Serbs later in
the day barricaded all roads leading into their part of the city
with trucks and tractors.
</P>
<P>
   About 1,000 of them staged another rally Tuesday evening, with
leaders vowing daily protests.
</P>
<P>
   ''Over the last 10 months, during clashes around bridges, we had
more than 100 people injured and not a single Albanian is jailed,''
Serb leader Oliver Ivanovic told The Associated Press.
''Fifty-three Serbs were killed or abducted and not a single
Albanian is in jail.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, on the south bank of the river, dozens of U.N.
employees who live and work on the Serb side milled about, stranded
by the bridge closure. The United Nations moved reinforcements --
special Pakistani riot police -- into the Albanian side in case
unrest on the Serb side got out of hand.
</P>
<P>
   As the sun set, Polish infantry in full combat gear were seen
taking positions on the Albanian-controlled south bank, presumably
to prevent extremists from that ethnic community from exploiting
tension by firing weapons across the river.
</P>
<P>
   The unrest happened while NATO Secretary-General Lord Robertson
and ambassadors of the NATO-member states were visiting Kosovo for
a firsthand look at the situation here, more than a year after the
beginning of the NATO peacekeeping mission.
</P>
<P>
   Robertson told reporters that he had come with a warning to both
Serbs and ethnic Albanians that they must do more to halt the
ethnic violence, which he called a cancer threatening the
province's future despite the presence of peacekeepers.
</P>
<P>
   ''We are determined that we will finish the job that we set out
to do and that means by protecting all of the people, not simply
one group,'' Robertson told reporters in Pristina. ''Both of these
leaderships have a heavy, heavy responsibility to move on from the
bloodshed of the past and present to something decent and honorable
for the future.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
