<HEADLINE> Niagara Falls Council split on plan for truck lane on bridge  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   NIAGARA FALLS, N.Y. (AP) - A resolution that seeks more
information on a plan to add a dedicated truck crossing at the
Whirlpool Bridge has been narrowly approved.
</P>
<P>
   Opponents of the resolution - passed by the Niagara Falls City
Council - called it anti-bridge and said the truck bridge proposal
is an opportunity for potential jobs and economic development in
the city's distressed North End.
</P>
<P>
   But the four Council members supporting it said the resolution
doesn't support or oppose the concept, just makes it clear the
Council has concerns it wants the Niagara Falls Bridge Commission
to address when it makes another presentation to the Council on
Sept. 25.
</P>
<P>
   Councilman Charles A. Walker, one of the initial sponsors of the
resolution, said he would like the Council to decide by then if it
will support or oppose the bridge commission plan.
</P>
<P>
   According to opponents a truck crossing could create jobs and
economic development because of the amenities it would require. But
according to others the resolution was premature because many of
the details are not known yet.
</P>
<P>
   The four sponsoring Council members said that is part of their
problem with the plan. Councilman John G. Accardo said an
appearance by Allen Gandell, general manager of the bridge
commission, two weeks ago left him with more questions than
answers.
</P>
<P>
   He and Walker also said the Council had not received any
information until they sponsored a resolution opposing the plan,
which they withdrew after Gandell's appearance and redrafted for
Monday's meeting.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
