<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-18 16:59 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> NBC May Add to Reality TV Genre  </HEADLINE>
By LYNN ELBER
<TEXT>
<P>
   PASADENA, Calif. (AP) -- NBC may be getting into the reality TV
business with a show that features a woman chained to a quartet of
prospective boyfriends.
</P>
<P>
   But that doesn't mean the network is throwing good taste or its
popular shows to the wind, NBC executives Scott Sassa and Garth
Ancier told the Television Critics Association on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ''We're not going to abandon what I think is the hallmark of our
network, quality dramas and sitcoms, but we can't ignore this
(reality trend) as something that may go away a year from now or
two years from now,'' Sassa said.
</P>
<P>
   NBC, home of top-rated shows including ''ER'' and ''Friends,''
is discussing a deal for the woman-in-chains show. As with many
other reality concepts, it originated in Europe.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's a relationship show. ... It's a pretty fun show. It adds
a little diversity and spice to your schedule,'' said Ancier.
</P>
<P>
   ''Everything can't be 'West Wing,''' he said of the White House
drama.
</P>
<P>
   Shows like CBS' ''Survivor'' and ''Big Brother'' are pushing
TV's envelope of acceptability, the executives said, and the limits
have to be determined on a case-by-case basis.
</P>
<P>
   Sassa, NBC's West Coast president, reportedly has faced sharp
criticism from his bosses for missing the reality TV bandwagon
carrying ABC (''Who Wants to Be a Millionaire'') and CBS to ratings
success.
</P>
<P>
   ''We weren't as aggressive as we should have been in this
area,'' Sassa admitted. He's assembled a team to develop reality
programs, especially for the summer rerun season.
</P>
<P>
   The reality genre, Sassa said, appears to be more than a fad.
Other networks are pursuing more such shows, including ABC's
planned ''The Chase'' and ''The Mole.''
</P>
<P>
   In other announcements, NBC said it is planning ''In His Life:
The John Lennon Story,'' a two-hour movie on the late
singer-songwriter set to air this fall.
</P>
<P>
   The network also is beefing up the casts of a number of its fall
series. Among those coming aboard new shows are Bebe Neuwirth, Tom
Conti, Lili Taylor and Hope Davis on ''Deadline'' and Tim Meadows
and William Devane on ''The Michael Richards Show.''
</P>
<P>
   The ''Michael Richards'' additions are part of a reworking of
the series, which the network was dissatisfied with, said Ancier,
NBC's entertainment president.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-07-18-00 1659 </TRAILER>
