<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-18 17:03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Unemployment hits three-decade low in New Jersey  </HEADLINE>
By RALPH SIEGEL
<TEXT>
<P>
   TRENTON, N.J. (AP) - State unemployment dropped to 3.4 percent
in June, the lowest since Richard Nixon was president and Jimi
Hendrix was living, breathing and playing guitar.
</P>
<P>
   New Jersey Labor Commissioner Mark Boyd called it a spectacular
sign of a spectacular economy, not so much for the one-month mark,
which is based on surveys with a certain error margin, but for the
fact that for five out of the last six months, unemployment in New
Jersey was below 4 percent and trending downward from there.
</P>
<P>
   ''We are tracking it, and we are amazed. This is fantastic
economy, and there are so many opportunities,'' Boyd said, noting
that when job vacancies are taken into account, there are probably
more openings than there are people looking for jobs.
</P>
<P>
   Economists said this low rate signifies virtually full
employment in the state. May unemployment was 3.8 percent, and the
June rate was the lowest record since the 3.3 percent unemployment
mark set in March 1970. The state's record low is 3.2 percent set
in January 1970.
</P>
<P>
   June also marked the 33rd straight month that the state's
unemployment rate has remained under 5 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ''This is sort of a Mark McGwire economy. This is the equivalent
of getting 70 home runs,'' said Rutgers University economist James
Hughes. ''As we are in this 3 percent range, it doesn't get any
better than this, at least from the perspective of a job seeker.''
</P>
<P>
   The June mark was well below the national unemployment rate of 4
percent and marked the largest one-month drop since the state's
unemployment rate slipped below 4 percent in March.
</P>
<P>
   But the ever-diligent economist can find a dark spot to this
bright picture.
</P>
<P>
   The tightness of the labor market and the duration of this
tightness set off the warning that New Jersey employers may soon
begin to find it so difficult to fill high-technology, high-skill
jobs, they will begin toning down their ambitions to expand.
</P>
<P>
   ''What has happened with this shortage of labor is that it is
now impacting economic output,'' Hughes said. ''It is what would be
expected after 97 months of economic expansion in New Jersey: After
97 months, were have essentially run out of labor.''
</P>
<P>
   David Rosen, an economic forecaster with the nonpartisan Office
of Legislative Services, said when unemployment hits the bottom
extreme, it creates a risk of inflation because employers may start
artificially increasing the wages they offer to an ever smaller
pool of applicants.
</P>
<P>
   ''The other fear traditionally has been that when unemployment
gets this low, that it fuels inflation because then you get salary
competition,'' Rosen said. ''(But) we haven't yet seen any strong
evidence of that.''
</P>
<P>
   Hughes said if Federal Reserve Board Chairman Alan Greenspan saw
unemployment rates like this across the United States, he probably
would become terrified of an upward jolt in inflation and would
immediately boost interest rates a full percentage point to throw
ice on the economy.
</P>
<P>
   Until now, Greenspan has been using quarter-point increases in
the interest rate to keep the heat in check.
</P>
<P>
   But Hughes added low unemployment could not have this sort of
inflation effect in a single state or region since many New Jersey
salaries are covered by national sales of such products as
prescription drugs and over-the-counter health supplies.
</P>
<P>
   Boyd would not have his enthusiasm doused, noting the
consistency of the good employment news in all corners of the
state. ''I have an unemployment rate that is falling all across the
state. It is falling in urban centers. It is falling all across
South Jersey,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   New Jersey employers had 3.931 million people on their payrolls
in June, which is actually down 3,500 positions since May, a drop
largely attributed to layoffs by the Census Bureau as it scales
back its temporary field workers. Manufacturing also fell by about
1,000.
</P>
<P>
   Among more permanent jobs, construction increased by 700,
wholesale trade by 500 and retail trade by 1,500.
</P>
<P>
   But the unemployment rate is not measured by jobs. It is
measured by polls asking people if they are working or looking for
work, then comparing those numbers and adjusting the results to
project the trend for the entire state.
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   http://www.state.nj.us/labor
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
