<HEADLINE> New York spraying to kill African virus that causes encephalitis  </HEADLINE>
By VERENA DOBNIK
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) - An African encephalitis virus that killed seven
New Yorkers last year has returned, some borne by Asian mosquitoes
believed to have arrived in shipments of used tires.
</P>
<P>
   For the first time this year, the West Nile virus was detected
in dozens of mosquitoes and birds from Long Island, to New York
City, to suburban Westchester County.
</P>
<P>
   A human infection ''would be the next step we would expect to
see,'' said Barbara Reynolds, a spokeswoman for the federal Centers
for Disease Control and Prevention.
</P>
<P>
   To reduce that possibility, health officials on Tuesday were
mobilizing trucks to spray insecticides.
</P>
<P>
   ''But the big message we're trying to get out is, people should
use common sense and take preventive action: Wear long shirts and
pants, and use mosquito repellant containing DEET,'' said spokesman
John Signor of the state Health Department.
</P>
<P>
   In Suffolk County on Long Island, health officials took
aggressive measures including spraying. On Tuesday, trucks were
ready to roll in the towns of Lindenhurst and West Babylon from 7
p.m. to 10:30 p.m., according to county health officials, who also
are distributing free repellant.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm afraid of being infected,'' said Robert DiPalo, a
22-year-old employee of the Stuff-A-Bagel bakery in Lindenhurst.
''I'm putting on repellant and just basically making sure there's
no water collecting near the house.''
</P>
<P>
   When he sees a mosquito, ''I kill it immediately.''
</P>
<P>
   One bug got through a few days ago. The day after, DiPalo said,
''I was sweating, I was very cold and I had no idea what it was.''
It was a false alarm, probably just ''a normal bug,'' said DiPalo,
who called spraying ''a good thing - as long as we don't get
infected.''
</P>
<P>
   The town of Huntington went high-tech with its war on infected
bugs: At the central water treatment plant, a ''mosquito magnet''
was set up that attracts mosquitoes with a plume of warm carbon
dioxide, then sucks them to their death.
</P>
<P>
   Fire Island, a popular Suffolk beach resort, was to be sprayed
on Tuesday from 5:30 p.m. to 9:30 p.m. in the Point O'Woods area.
</P>
<P>
   And the New York City borough of Staten Island was braced for
spraying, beginning at 10 p.m. Wednesday to 5 a.m. Thursday in the
Rossville and Westerleigh neighborhoods. Two infected crows were
found dead there earlier this month.
</P>
<P>
   The next night, Westchester County joins in, spraying the
insecticide in the communities closest to where infected birds and
mosquitoes have been found: New Rochelle, Eastchester, Tuckahoe,
Bronxville, Mamaroneck and Scarsdale in the south and North Castle,
Mount Pleasant, New Castle, Pleasantville, Mount Kisco, Pound
Ridge, Lewisboro and Bedford in the north.
</P>
<P>
   New Castle includes Chappaqua, where President and Hillary
Rodham Clinton have a home.
</P>
<P>
   People and pets are advised to stay indoors during spraying.
</P>
<P>
   The West Nile virus first appeared in the Western Hemisphere
last summer, killing seven people in the New York area and
infecting 62 others. The outbreak prompted a massive campaign of
aerial and ground spraying.
</P>
<P>
   If a mosquito transfers the virus to human blood, the bite can
cause encephalitis, a swelling of the brain that is sometimes
fatal. Early symptoms include a stiff neck and a fever.
</P>
<P>
   The virus that appeared in New York last year apparently
survived the winter, in hibernating insects.
</P>
<P>
   This time, state health officials were ready with a huge
preventive effort: They have tested 700 birds, 55,000 mosquitoes
and 200 humans so far.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, State Health Commissioner Antonia Novello announced
that the virus had been found in mosquitoes collected in early July
in Westchester and Suffolk counties.
</P>
<P>
   In the Westchester hamlet of Armonk, it was detected in the
Aedes japonicus, a type of mosquito that feeds on blood round the
clock. Last year, the virus was found only in the common house
mosquito, Culex pipiens, which is active from dusk to dawn.
</P>
<P>
   Aedes japonicus, native to Japan and Korea, is believed to have
arrived in the Northeast in recent years, traveling in shipments of
used tires, said Signor. Water collects in tires, providing a good
breeding site.
</P>
<P>
   In Army tests, japonicus was found to be even better at
spreading the West Nile strain than Culex pipiens.
</P>
<P>
   In Armonk, a pool of 10 of the Asian mosquitoes, destroyed and
tested as a lump, came out positive for West Nile, Signor said. At
about the same time, the virus was found in a pool of 26 Culex
pipiens mosquitoes collected in the Suffolk town of Babylon.
</P>
<P>
   In the past month, 19 birds tested positive in all of New York
state, including 11 in Rockland County, three in Suffolk, three in
Westchester and the two on Staten Island. They included 14 American
crows, three bluejays and two redtailed hawks.
</P>
<P>
   Birds, like humans, get the virus from mosquitoes.
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   New York State Health Department site:
http://www.health.state.ny.us/nysdoh/westnile/index.htm
</P>
<P>
   Westchester County Health Department site:
http://www.westchestergov.com/health/Westnile.htm
</P>
<P>
   Suffolk County mosquito-spraying site:
http://www.co.suffolk.ny.us/health/pesticide
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
