<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New law aimed at saving abandoned babies  </HEADLINE>
By MICHAEL HILL
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) - Mothers who abandon their newborns in
hospitals or other safe havens will be protected from prosecution
under a measure signed into law Tuesday by Gov. George Pataki.
</P>
<P>
   The new law is aimed at reducing incidents of babies left to die
in places like trash bins, woods and bathroom stalls. Parents who
desert their newborns are now shielded from facing child
abandonment charges, provided the baby is unharmed and left in a
safe place.
</P>
<P>
   ''This new law will help save lives by giving often young,
desperate mothers an opportunity to place their child in a safe
place,'' Pataki said.
</P>
<P>
   Under the law, parents will not be prosecuted if they deliver an
unabused baby not more than five days old to a safe location and
promptly notify someone. Local law enforcement officials have
latitude in deciding whether the baby was left in a safe haven.
</P>
<P>
   The law went into effect Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Some district attorneys in New York have already been holding
off on pursuing child abandonment charges in certain cases.
Rensselaer County District Attorney Ken Bruno, speaking at Pataki's
bill signing ceremony, described it as a lifesaving policy.
</P>
<P>
   ''We would much rather save the life of a newborn baby than
prosecute a mother for murder,'' said Bruno, whose father - Senate
Majority Leader Joseph Bruno - also spoke at the bill-signing
ceremony.
</P>
<P>
   Ken Bruno cited gruesome cases of a baby being suffocated in a
toilet bowl and another left to die in the woods, but speakers at
the state Capitol ceremony could not quantify how widespread the
problem was. Federal statistics show that of the 105 known
abandoned babies in 1998, 33 were found dead. That's up from 1991,
when 65 babies were left in public places and eight died.
</P>
<P>
   Thirteen other states have similar laws and many more have
abandonment bills on the table. But New York's law is unique in
allowing local prosecutors to determine what a safe have is, said
state Sen. Nancy Larraine Hoffmann, a prime sponsor of the New York
bill. Hoffmann said other states' laws specifically list the sorts
of places infants may be left.
</P>
<P>
   Hoffmann, a Republican from Onondaga County, said new mothers
who because of their age or distraught mental state are inclined to
abandon babies in trash bins might get newborns into safe hands if
they knew they would not be prosecuted as criminals.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
