<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Report: Romania PM To Run for Pres.  </HEADLINE>
By ALISON MUTLER
<TEXT>
<P>
   BUCHAREST, Romania (AP) -- Romania's prime minister reportedly
told a colleague Tuesday that he will seek the presidency, entering
a contest that could determine whether the country moves toward
greater democracy or the communist-style leadership of the past.
</P>
<P>
   Reports that reform-minded Prime Minister Mugur Isarescu will
campaign for Romania's top job came after President Emil
Constantinescu announced Monday that he would not seek another
term.
</P>
<P>
   Though polls showed his chances of re-election were slim,
Constantinescu's surprise statement left politicians here
scrambling to figure out how to capitalize on his withdrawal.
</P>
<P>
   Isarescu, who previously said he wanted to return as governor of
the National Bank after November elections, apparently revealed his
change of plan Tuesday, national radio reported.
</P>
<P>
   However, he said nothing about it Tuesday and party officials
said he would not announce officially for another month.
</P>
<P>
   Ion Diaconescu, the chairman of the Peasant Party and head of
the Chamber of Deputies, said Isarescu would run for president,
national radio reported.
</P>
<P>
   Isarescu's entry into the race could change the complexion of
the contest, transforming it into a vote for choosing between the
economic hardship of free-market reform or retaining the safety net
of the communist-era system.
</P>
<P>
   The average monthly salary is less than $100 and inflation is
expected to be nearly 30 percent this year. Foreign investors
complain of corruption, bureaucracy and shifting legislation.
</P>
<P>
   Romania's center-right parties, who are faring poorly in opinion
polls ahead of November elections, hope that Isarescu can attract
voters. A former central bank governor, Isarescu is respected by
Western officials for his efforts to reform Romania's public
administration and to help Romania's institutionalized children.
</P>
<P>
   He will likely face two key former communist leaders, Ion
Iliescu and Teodor Melescanu, who have both criticized efforts to
dismantle the inefficient government.
</P>
<P>
   Iliescu, 69, a top communist official educated in Moscow, took
over during the 1989 anti-communist revolt and was elected
president twice in 1990 and 1992, before losing to Constantinescu
in 1996. Iliescu's party relies on his popularity as a
father-figure among rural voters and older people, and the party
has no obvious candidate to replace him.
</P>
<P>
   Still, some members of his own party think it is time for him to
step aside in favor of a younger candidate.
</P>
<P>
   Melescanu was a high-ranking diplomat before 1989 and was
Iliescu's foreign minister before leaving to form his own party.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
