<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-18 17:37 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ground spraying ordered for half of county  </HEADLINE>
By JIM FITZGERALD
<TEXT>
<P>
   WHITE PLAINS, N.Y. (AP) - Officials reluctantly ordered a double
dose of insecticide on Tuesday for about half of Westchester County
after mosquitoes infected with the West Nile virus were found in a
trap in Armonk.
</P>
<P>
   ''It is a very difficult decision for me personally, and
certainly in a county like Westchester that is so environmentally
conscious,'' said County Executive Andrew Spano. ''But we have made
that decision. We feel we have been given enough warning.''
</P>
<P>
   So beginning at 11:30 p.m. Thursday, a contractor's tanker
trucks will wind through 1,500 miles of streets and highways,
spreading a mist of the insecticide sumethrin, or Anvil, through
communities near where infected birds or mosquitoes have been
found.
</P>
<P>
   The affected towns are New Rochelle, Eastchester, Tuckahoe,
Bronxville, Mamaroneck and Scarsdale in the south and North Castle,
Mount Pleasant, New Castle, Pleasantville, Mount Kisco, Pound
Ridge, Lewisboro and Bedford in the north.
</P>
<P>
   New Castle includes Chappaqua, where President and Hillary
Rodham Clinton have a home.
</P>
<P>
   The same areas will be resprayed - ''a booster shot,'' Spano
called it - after the weekend. Spano said there are no plans now
for aerial spraying, which was undertaken last year when the virus
first appeared. The county then undertook an aggressive campaign to
kill mosquito larvae and eliminate breeding grounds.
</P>
<P>
   Westchester's spraying, which will cost $195,000, will follow
similar applications in Suffolk County, the other area where
infected mosquitoes have been found, and Staten Island in New York
City, where infected crows were found.
</P>
<P>
   Spano said West Nile's high mortality rate - he pegged it at 12
percent - was another reason to spray, whereas Lyme disease or
ehrlichiosis, which are spread by ticks and are also summertime
scourges, have much lower rates.
</P>
<P>
   ''Our first priority is human health,'' said County Health
Commissioner Joshua Lipsman, ''and for that reason we are going
ahead with the ground spraying.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
