<DOCNO> APW20000718.0116 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-18 17:44 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Train-Whistle Plan Criticized  </HEADLINE>
By JENNIFER LOVEN
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Thousands of families in Rita Mullins'
bustling Chicago suburb would get blasted with train horns about 70
times a day under a government plan requiring trains to sound their
whistles at all crossings lacking state-of-the-art safety devices.
</P>
<P>
   ''It will effectively destroy everything the state of Illinois
has fought so hard to achieve,'' the mayor of Palatine, Ill., told
a House Transportation panel Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   A long line of witnesses, including House Speaker Dennis
Hastert, echoed her plea that was aimed less at the largely
sympathetic congressional panel than at the Federal Railroad
Administration, which made the proposal as it attempted to meet a
1994 congressional mandate.
</P>
<P>
   An FRA analysis concluded crossings with conventional gates but
no whistles have 62 percent more accidents than those where horns
are blown. But the agency has been inundated with complaints since
announcing its plan earlier this year.
</P>
<P>
   Those testifying warned that if the regulation is adopted as
proposed, the quality of life would be ruined for residents near
the 2,058 railroad crossings around the country where tooting
trains are now banned. About a third of those crossings are in the
Chicago area. Wisconsin, Minnesota, Indiana and Virginia also have
large numbers of crossings where train horns are not alllowed.
</P>
<P>
   ''The impact to my constituents and the people of Illinois
cannot be underestimated,'' said Hastert, who represents a suburban
Chicago district crisscrossed by railroad tracks.
</P>
<P>
   Hastert and Rep. Bill Lipinski, D-Ill., have proposed an
alternative to the FRA that would exempt all intersections that
have been accident-free for five years and those with conventional
gates and lights that have had fewer than three accidents.
</P>
<P>
   Their plan also would extend from two years to 10 years the
deadline for communities to upgrade crossings before the horns must
start to blow. It also would count as an acceptable upgrade
lower-cost, less-intrusive methods such as automated horns blown
only at the crossing.
</P>
<P>
   ''There are modifications to the proposed rule that must be made
if we are going to be able to accept this,'' Lipinski said.
</P>
<P>
   John Wells, an FRA deputy administration, stressed that the
regulation would look much different when finalized. He suggested
one acceptable option -- not now included -- might be a combination
of conventional gates and flashing lights with aggressive
enforcement and public awareness.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, he said, the current proposal already contains
significant flexibility that could minimize the changes needed.
</P>
<P>
   Some of those testifying said the FRA proposal could lessen
safety rather than increase it.
</P>
<P>
   Richard Mathias, chairman of the Illinois Commerce Commission,
said it would divert limited funds to already safe crossings in
whistle-ban communities and away from improving crossings in rural
areas that often have little more than a sign.
</P>
<P>
   Mathias noted Illinois has seen a 79 percent drop in crossing
accidents in two decades while traffic has increased 50 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ''Illinois' program is working, it is successful, it is saving
lives, and it is achieving all of this without the sounding of the
horns,'' testified Rep. Henry Hyde, R-Ill.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: Federal Railroad Administration:
http://www.fra.dot.gov/site/horns/index.htm
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-07-18-00 1744 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000718.0117 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-18 17:47 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Coaster accident's family files negligence suit  </HEADLINE>
By JOHN CURRAN
<TEXT>
<P>
   OCEAN CITY, N.J. (AP) - A man whose wife and daughter were
killed in a roller coaster accident last summer filed suit Tuesday
against the amusement park's owners, saying the accident should not
have happened.
</P>
<P>
   John J. Bailey Jr., of Pomona, N.Y., who lost his wife Kimberly,
39, and 8-year-old daughter Jessica, says the park's owners knew
the Wild Wonder was defective but failed to close it down before
the Aug. 28, 1999, accident.
</P>
<P>
   The family is seeking $275 million for Bailey and his 5-year-old
daughter, who tried to accompany her mother and sister but couldn't
because she didn't meet the height requirement for the ride.
</P>
<P>
   She watched the accident happen, according to the suit.
</P>
<P>
   It names ride manufacturer Zamperla Inc., of Parsippany,
Gillian's Wonderland Pier of Ocean City, Air Tech Systems, of
Barnegat, and Point Machine Shop, a Somers Point machine shop that
fabricated replacement parts for the coaster after earlier
malfunctions.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's not going to replace the wife and daughter he lost,''
said Bailey's lawyer, Michael Grossman. ''If we can't settle it for
something fair and just, we're going to go to trial.''
</P>
<P>
   The Baileys died after the car they were riding in slipped on a
35-foot incline that started the ride. The car plummeted backward
and rounded a 90-degree turn, ejecting both. They were thrown
against a steel support structure.
</P>
<P>
   A probe by state safety investigators blamed the accident on a
faulty replacement brake and an improperly fastened restraining bar
inside the car.
</P>
<P>
   It said an anti-rollback device on the ride, which has sharp
steel teeth designed to bite into the rails and prevent slipping,
was made from steel much weaker than what was called for by the
ride's maker and was badly worn.
</P>
<P>
   The park's owners had replaced the original anti-rollback device
on Aug. 17, installing a new one made by Point Machine Shop,
according to the state, which fined Gillian's $25,000 and Zamperla
$30,000.
</P>
<P>
   ''The defendants knew or should have known that the Wild
Wonder's anti-rollback device and other component parts were made
with inferior materials and were not reasonably fit for their
intended purpose,'' according to the 14-page complaint filed
Tuesday in Superior Court for Morris County, in Morristown.
</P>
<P>
   The suit was lodged there because Zamperla is based in
Parsippany, Grossman said.
</P>
<P>
   Witnesses to the accident told state investigators that the
ride, which was brand new when it opened July 1, malfunctioned less
than two hours before the Baileys' accident, injuring two riders.
</P>
<P>
   Gillian's officials could not be reached for comment on the suit
Tuesday. Jay Gillian, general manager of the park, did not return
two telephone messages. The park's lawyer, Lary Zucker, was not in
his office Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   A Zamperla spokeswoman said company officials had not seen the
lawsuit yet.
</P>
<P>
   ''We have not seen the document or been served the papers. Until
we do, we don't believe we can comment intelligently,'' said
Deborah Israel, director of public relations.
</P>
<P>
   A woman who answered the telephone at Point Machine Shop
referred calls to lawyer Andrew Siegeltuch, who was out of his
office Tuesday and could not be reached for comment.
</P>
<P>
   Air Tech Systems, which is based in Barnegat, installed the
ride, according to the suit. Officials there could not be reached
Tuesday; there was no telephone listing for Air Tech.
</P>
<P>
   No dollar figure was cited in the suit.
</P>
<P>
   But in a notice of claim filed last November, Bailey said he
would seek $100 million for each victim, $50 million for ''loss of
services'' for his wife and $25 million for loss of services for
his daughter.
</P>
<P>
   Grossman said Bailey, 40, a firefighter in Scarsdale, N.Y., was
shattered by the loss of his wife and daughter and is in
counseling, as is Kathryn Bailey, now 6.
</P>
<P>
   She suffered ''severe and permanent emotional distress, mental
anguish and suffering'' seeing her mother and sister die, the suit
said.
</P>
<P>
   A worker on the Wild Wonder who saw the earlier malfunction told
the victims of it that the ride would be closed, according to
Grossman.
</P>
<P>
   ''He (Bailey) feels that if they'd done what they'd said they
would do, his wife and daughter would be here today. And he's not
wrong,'' Grossman said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
