<HEADLINE> Hillary Clinton proposes expanding Children's Health Insurance Program </HEADLINE>
By KAREN MATTHEWS
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) - Hillary Rodham Clinton said Tuesday that if
elected to the Senate she would work to expand a federal health
insurance program for children to include families earning up to
three times the poverty level.
</P>
<P>
   ''The United States is, to our shame, the only industrialized
nation that does not extend health care coverage to its people,
even to its children,'' Clinton said in a speech at New York
Presbyterian Hospital.
</P>
<P>
   The Children's Health Insurance Program, passed in 1997,
provides health insurance to children in working poor families that
do not qualify for Medicaid.
</P>
<P>
   The program provides coverage to children in families that earn
up to twice the federal poverty level, or $34,000 for a family of
four. Clinton said that under her plan children in families earning
up to three times the poverty level, or $51,000 for a family of
four, would qualify.
</P>
<P>
   ''That will enable us to cover the vast majority, if not
completely, all the families that are caught between Medicaid and
affordable insurance either from an employer or that they pay for
on their own,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   As she has in the past, Clinton said that her failed attempt at
a national health insurance plan taught her that the best way to
implement change was incrementally.
</P>
<P>
   ''I decided at the end of 1994 to just get back to work,'' she
said. ''And I took with me in that work the lessons that I learned
from that experience. And one of the biggest lessons that I took
away from it is that in our political system the most effective way
to get things done is to work step by step, making the changes that
are needed toward achieving the same larger goal.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition to expanding the existing federal insurance program
to include more children, Clinton said she favored expanding it to
include parents and other adults.
</P>
<P>
   She said she would propose a ''carrot-and-stick approach'' of
financial incentives to reward states that succeed in enrolling
children who are eligible for Medicaid and the Children's Health
Insurance Program and penalize those that do not.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said her plan would provide access to health insurance
to at least 1.1 million New Yorkers including 700,000 children. She
did not say how much the proposals would cost but said,
''Everything I've proposed would be part of a balanced budget.''
</P>
<P>
   But Bill Cal Col, the campaign manager for her Republican
opponent in the Senate race, Rep. Rick Lazio, said in a news
release that Clinton ''is now keeping secrets about the financing
of her health care scheme.''
</P>
<P>
   Dal Col alluded to Clinton's ''disastrous 1993 plan to socialize
the nation's health care system'' and asked, ''If Mrs. Clinton was
wrong on health care then, how can New Yorkers trust that she's not
wrong on health care now?''
</P>
<P>
   The first lady spoke as controversy continued over an allegation
that she uttered an anti-Semitic slur 26 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton did not take questions, but her spokesman Howard Wolfson
said, ''I think this dust-up will pass, I think people will see
this for the garbage that it is, and they'll know that Hillary
Clinton is a strong advocate of a safe and secure Israel.''
</P>
<P>
   Also Tuesday, three Jewish members of Congress from New York
sent a letter to Lazio scolding him and his campaign for using ''a
false allegation of anti-Semitism for political gain.'' Lazio has
expressed doubts about the first lady's denial, calling the
statement ''disturbing''
</P>
<P>
   ''Your political use of this ridiculous allegation will only
hurt our efforts to combat true anti-Semitism,'' said the letter
signed by Reps. Nita Lowey, Jerrold Nadler and Anthony Weiner.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
