<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kids call President Clinton world's most important person  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   MAHWAH, N.J. (AP) - Impeached by Congress, embarrassed by his
affair with a 25-year-old intern, President Clinton still reigns
supreme among American children.
</P>
<P>
   He beat out Pope John Paul II, Microsoft founder Bill Gates,
astronaut John Glenn and retired NBA star Michael Jordan in a
survey that asked children to name the world's most important
person.
</P>
<P>
   The survey, conducted by the World Almanac for Kids, offered
readers aged 6 to 14 the chance to win prizes by naming their picks
and explaining why they chose them. It was contained on the last
page of the 2000 edition of the book.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, the choice of 30 percent of the respondents, was cited
because of his peacekeeping negotiations, his improvements to
education and because he is ''the ruler of a free world.''
</P>
<P>
   The pope, who got 20.6 percent, helps make the world a better
place, the children said. Neither poor health nor an assassination
attempt could stop him, one said. ''That is a sign of a truly
inspirational person,'' the child said.
</P>
<P>
   ''My Mom'' got 20.4 percent, ''My Dad,'' 15.8 percent, and Gates
15 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Others receiving votes: civil rights pioneer Rosa Parks,
astronaut Neil Armstrong, ''Harry Potter'' author J.K. Rowling,
slain civil rights leader Martin Luther King Jr., first lady
Hillary Clinton, talk show host Rosie O'Donnell and soccer star Mia
Hamm, who beat out God by a slight margin.
</P>
<P>
   ''The mix of names on the list of most important people chosen
by these kids is just fascinating,'' said Ken Park, the almanac's
publisher. ''Almost one-third of the respondents chose President
Clinton. We wonder how many more there might have been had there
been no scandals last year.''
</P>
<P>
   Frank McGuire, 10, of Orlando, Fla., won top prize - an
expense-paid trip to Washington, D.C. - for his entry, which named
Bill Gates, Nelson Mandela and Chinese president Jiang Zemin. The
entry was designed like a newspaper page and listed each of his
choices' contributions to society.
</P>
</TEXT>
