<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Officials say virus likely to reappear in Connecticut  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   NEW HAVEN, Conn. (AP) - It is just a matter of time before
mosquitoes carrying a deadly virus reappear in Connecticut, state
environmental officials said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The 100 birds and 38,000 mosquitoes tested so far this year in
Connecticut have all tested negative for the West Nile-like and the
Eastern Equine strains of the encephalitis virus. For the week of
July 18, 13,042 mosquitoes were tested from 46 sites statewide.
</P>
<P>
   But the West Nile-like virus has been found recently in
mosquitos and birds in New York's Westchester County, Suffolk
County and Staten Island.
</P>
<P>
   Theodore Andreadis, chief entomologist for the Connecticut
Agricultural Experiment Station, said the virus is not likely to
recognize state border lines.
</P>
<P>
   ''I fully anticipate that with what is going on in the region,
that we are probably going to detect it soon,'' Andreadis said.
''The virus is re-emerging in multiple areas, and it could
re-emerge just about anywhere in lower Fairfield or New Haven
County where we had evidence of virus last year.''
</P>
<P>
   The West Nile virus first appeared in the Western Hemisphere
last summer, killing seven people in the New York area and
infecting 62 others.
</P>
<P>
   If a mosquito transfers the virus to human blood, the bite can
cause encephalitis, a swelling of the brain that is sometimes
fatal. Early symptoms include a stiff neck and a fever.
</P>
<P>
   The virus was found in birds and mosquitoes in Connecticut, but
not in humans.
</P>
<P>
   It apparently survived the winter, in hibernating insects.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, the virus was found only in the common house
mosquito, Culex pipiens, which is active from dusk to dawn. But
this year it has been found in Aedes japonicus, a type of mosquito
that feeds on blood around the clock.
</P>
<P>
   Aedes japonicus, native to Japan and Korea, is believed to have
arrived in the Northeast in recent years, traveling in shipments of
used tires, said Signor. Water collects in tires, providing a good
breeding site.
</P>
<P>
   In Army tests, japonicus was found to be even better at
spreading the West Nile strain than Culex pipiens.
</P>
<P>
   The appearance of the virus in New York has prompted officials
there to intensify insecticide spraying. In Connecticut, the
Department of Environmental Protection has provided larvicide to 41
shoreline communities.
</P>
<P>
   But state DEP Commissioner Arthur Rocque Jr. said spraying is
not likely to prevent the virus from appearing here.
</P>
<P>
   ''The idea that we're going to wipe all these evil mosquitoes
off the face of Connecticut's map is just erroneous,'' he said.
''It is not going to happen.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
