<HEADLINE> Police: Driver killed in boat crash was legally drunk  </HEADLINE>
By JOHN CURRAN
<TEXT>
<P>
   OCEAN CITY, N.J. (AP) - The driver of a speedboat involved in a
fatal crash last month was legally drunk when it happened, State
Police said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Toxicology tests conducted on the body of Dominick Laspata, 26,
of Westville, showed he had blood alcohol content above the 0.10
percent legal limit for drivers, according to Sgt. Al Della Fave.
</P>
<P>
   Della Fave said he was not permitted to release the exact BAC
reading.
</P>
<P>
   Laspata and three passengers in his 26-foot Sonic died June 11
when a cabin cruiser broadsided the boat in Peck's Bay, along the
Intracoastal Waterway.
</P>
<P>
   The driver of the 30-foot cabin cruiser, John Lego, 52, of
Lansdale, Pa., has been issued summonses for failing to avoid a
collision. His toxicology tests came back clean: He had no alcohol
or drugs in his system, State Police said.
</P>
<P>
   No criminal charges have been filed in the accident. Laspata's
blood-alcohol reading will be considered by Cape May County
Prosecutor David Blaker as he decides whether to charge Lego,
according to Della Fave.
</P>
<P>
   Blaker said no determination has been made about whether to
charge Lego. Asked if Laspata's blood-alcohol content would
mitigate in favor of Lego, he said: ''I can't answer that question.
We have to review the whole file. It would be premature for me to
speculate.''
</P>
<P>
   Lego had hosted a graduation party for a group of North Penn
High School students the day of the accident. He was giving eight
of them a sightseeing ride when the accident occurred.
</P>
<P>
   According to State Police, the cabin cruiser was headed south
and attempting to maneuver to the left when it slammed into the
left side of the speedboat, which was heading north.
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't clear whether the operators saw one another.
</P>
<P>
   Lego and all eight of his passengers were thrown overboard on
impact, but none were injured seriously.
</P>
<P>
   Laspata and his cousin, John ''Mickey'' Flynn, 42, of
Sicklerville died at the scene. The bodies of Jean Greenwood, 30,
and James G. Fisler, 25, both of Sewell, were recovered three days
later.
</P>
<P>
   Lego could not be reached for comment on Laspata's toxicology
findings Tuesday. His telphone number in Lansdale, Pa., is
unlisted, and no one answered the door at his bayfront condominium
in Ocean City.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
