<DOCNO> APW20000718.0124 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-18 18:36 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton accuser has colorful past  </HEADLINE>
By BETH J. HARPAZ
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) - He can no longer practice law because someone
paid him to alter a court document.
</P>
<P>
   He suffered a brain disorder that led to memory loss and an
addiction to phenobarbitol.
</P>
<P>
   He wrote a letter to Hillary Rodham Clinton begging her
forgiveness for saying things about her ''without factual
foundation.'' And he holds a divinity degree from a Baptist
theological school.
</P>
<P>
   He is Paul Fray, the man who's accusing Clinton of calling him a
''Jew b------'' during an argument in 1974.
</P>
<P>
   The accusation - contained in a new book, ''State of A Union:
Inside the Complex Marriage of Bill and Hillary Clinton'' by Jerry
Oppenheimer - has rocked Clinton's New York Senate campaign and
become fodder for Web sites, newspaper headlines and cable TV news
shows.
</P>
<P>
   While other accusations - some sleazy, some unprovable - have
sometimes been ignored by the Clintons and unreported by the
mainstream press, this one spurred the first lady to action.
</P>
<P>
   She unequivocally denied the allegation during an emotional
press conference in the garden of her Westchester home. The
president phoned a New York Daily News managing editor and called
the accusation ''crap.''
</P>
<P>
   Fray did not return several calls placed for comment. But he
told the Fox News Channel Tuesday that he'd like a ''face-to-face''
meeting with the first lady ''and we'll get everything resolved and
this matter will go away. ... I don't want to adversely affect her
race. I do not want to get me into a position where I said this to
create problems for her.''
</P>
<P>
   He added, ''I'm the victim.''
</P>
<P>
   Fray claims that Hillary Clinton made the comment in
Fayetteville, Ark., on the night that Bill Clinton lost a
Congressional election. Fray had worked on the campaign. He and his
wife, Mary Lee, went inside a room with Bill Clinton and his
then-girlfriend, Hillary Rodham, and an argument ensued. The fight
has been described in a half-dozen Clinton biographies, but
Oppenheimer's is the first to include Fray's assertion that Hillary
Clinton used an anti-Semitic slur.
</P>
<P>
   Fray holds a Master of Divinity degree from Southwest Baptist
Theological School in Fort Worth. But he told Oppenheimer that his
father was Jewish.
</P>
<P>
   Another campaign aide, Neil McDonald, told Oppenheimer he heard
the comment while standing outside the door. Efforts to reach
McDonald on Tuesday were not successful.
</P>
<P>
   Fray has a colorful past. On Oct. 6, 1980, the state Supreme
Court of Arkansas accepted the surrender of his law license.
Individuals typically voluntarily submit to such a procedure in
lieu of having their licenses revoked by the state.
</P>
<P>
   In March 1984, Fray applied to have his license reinstated. In
denying the application, the court's Committee on Professional
Conduct wrote that Fray was altered a court document to erase a
drunken driving conviction for a client and ''stated that he did
not recall accepting $500 for the serious impropriety.''
</P>
<P>
   The committee also wrote that Fray later suffered a cerebral
hemorrhage which led to seizures, addiction to prescription pain
killer, erratic behavior and memory loss.
</P>
<P>
   ''We are not satisfied that he possesses the good moral
character necessary for a law license,'' the committee wrote. ''The
alteration of the court record occurred before he suffered the
cerebral hemorrhage. The act demonstrates a basic lack of
integrity.''
</P>
<P>
   One committee member dissented, attributing Fray's behavior to a
medical condition.
</P>
<P>
   Oppenheimer said Tuesday he was ''completely 100 percent
satisfied that the Frays and Neil McDonald are telling the truth.''
Oppenheimer has worked for The National Enquirer, the Philadelphia
Daily News, the Washington Star and United Press International. He
says he is a liberal who voted for Clinton in 1992.
</P>
<P>
   Gail Sheehy, author of ''Hillary's Choice,'' said when she
interviewed the Frays, Mary Lee Fray mentioned the anti-Semitic
comment. Sheehy decided not to include it in her book because Paul
Fray ''skirted the issue. That's why I didn't use it. I realized
that even he didn't back it up.'' She added that she found the
Frays ''only moderately reliable. They were kind of flaky.''
</P>
<P>
   Oppenheimer dismissed the loss of Fray's legal license as
irrelevant. ''That's what the Arkansas Bar is now considering about
Bill Clinton too,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The Arkansas Supreme Court is considering whether to revoke the
president's law license on the grounds that he gave misleading
testimony regarding the Monica Lewinsky scandal.
</P>
<P>
   Mayor Rudolph Giuliani, who didn't have a lot of nice things to
say about Hillary Clinton when he was running for Senate against
her before dropping out of the race, spoke up for her Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ''What she did say or didn't say 26 years ago, I can't imagine
it has any relevance today,'' he said. ''I'm willing to accept her
at her word.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-07-18-00 1836 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000718.0125 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-18 18:38 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Boy Scouts Charter Repeal Urged  </HEADLINE>
By LAURENCE ARNOLD
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Some Democratic lawmakers who support gay
rights want Congress to repeal an 84-year-old honorary charter of
the Boy Scouts because the organization has a policy against gays.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Lynn Woolsey, D-Calif., said the Boy Scouts of America
claims to be open to all boys but, in a recent Supreme Court case,
scouting officials defended the organization's right to exclude
homosexuals.
</P>
<P>
   ''We're not saying they're bad,'' Woolsey said Tuesday. ''We're
saying intolerance is bad, and I don't see any reason why the
federal government should be supporting it.''
</P>
<P>
   Woolsey planned to introduce legislation on Wednesday to repeal
the federal charter of the Boy Scouts.
</P>
<P>
   A charter from Congress is an honorary recognition given to
patriotic, charitable and education organizations. About 90 groups
have them. The Boy Scouts got its charter in 1916, six years after
it was founded.
</P>
<P>
   The charter is open-ended and does not need periodic votes to
reauthorize it. But it contains a clause noting that Congress has
the right to repeal or amend it at any time.
</P>
<P>
   Though the charter confers no tangible benefits, Woolsey said it
''gives the impression that an organization has a congressional
seal of approval.''
</P>
<P>
   Boy Scouts spokesman Gregg Shields said the organization is one
of many recognized by Congress as ''patriotic societies'' that
limit membership to certain people, such as Jewish War Veterans
U.S.A.
</P>
<P>
   ''We're honored to have such a charter,'' Shields said, ''but we
also ask other Americans to recognize our rights to freedom of
association as described by the Constitution and upheld by the
Supreme Court.''
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. Supreme Court, in a 5-4 decision, ruled June 28 that
the Boy Scouts can bar homosexuals from serving as troop leaders.
The ruling may also permit the 6.2-million-member organization to
reject gay boys as members.
</P>
<P>
   Woolsey is a former Girl Scout, and her grown son is a former
Boy Scout. One of her constituents is Steven Cozza of Petaluma,
Calif., a 15-year-old Eagle Scout who founded a group called
''Scouting for All'' that advocates the elimination of the
prohibition on gays scouts.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-07-18-00 1838 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000718.0126 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-18 18:39 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Dow Ends Down 64; Nasdaq Drops 98  </HEADLINE>
By BRUCE MEYERSON
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Technology stocks led the market lower Tuesday
as investors locked in some gains from that group's rebound despite
some strong profit reports by major companies and a mostly tame
reading on inflation.
</P>
<P>
   The Dow Jones industrial average fell 64.35 to close at
10,739.92 after falling as much as 101 points during the session.
</P>
<P>
   Among broader market indicators, the technology-dominated Nasdaq
composite index fell 97.50 to 4,177.17, the Standard &AMP; Poor's 500
fell 16.75 to 1,493.74, and the Russell 2000 index of smaller
companies fell 8.90 to 536.28.
</P>
<P>
   ''We're getting some profit-taking in the market and that's
about it,'' said Richard A. Dickson, technical analyst at Scott &AMP;
Stringfellow Inc. in Richmond, Va. ''The Nasdaq gained 5.5 percent
last week. The Dow was up every day last week and off just 8 points
yesterday. So the market is just acting a little tired.''
</P>
<P>
   Declining issues outnumbered advancers by about a 3-to-2 margin
on the New York Stock Exchange and the Nasdaq Stock Market. NYSE
composite volume came to 1.105 billion shares, almost even with
Monday's tally.
</P>
<P>
   Before the start of trading, the Labor Department reported that
consumer inflation jumped 0.6 percent in June, chiefly reflecting
surging gasoline prices and a record rise in the cost of natural
gas, but most other prices posted modest increases. Analysts had
expected the report to show a 0.5 percent increase in the Consumer
Price Index.
</P>
<P>
   The Federal Reserve has boosted interest rates six times over
the past 13 months to slow economic growth and keep inflation in
check. With recent reports suggesting that the Fed's rate increases
are working, some economists believe the central bank will leave
rates unchanged at its meeting Aug. 22.
</P>
<P>
   Merrill Lynch, General Motors and Johnson &AMP; Johnson led the
early parade of second-quarter profit reports with
better-than-expected results. However, the day's most anxiously
awaited reports weren't released until after the close, when both
Intel and Microsoft topped Wall Street forecasts.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the strong showing, shares of Merrill Lynch fell $3.75
to $128.25, while GM rose 43.8 cents to $60.813 and J&AMP;J rose 64.1
cents to $95.
</P>
<P>
   Intel fell $3.313 to $143 in Nasdaq trading before its report,
making it the Dow's biggest decliner, but then recovered to $144.25
in extended trading on other markets. Microsoft struggled higher in
advance of its report, rising 31.2 cents to $78.50, and then
advanced to $79.938 in extended trading.
</P>
<P>
   Among other leading names, Honeywell slipped 18.8 cents to
$36.875 and Philip Morris rose 56.3 cents to $24.063 after both
companies matched Wall Street profit forecasts.
</P>
<P>
   Unisys tumbled nearly 18 percent, or $2.516 to $11.609, after
the struggling computer systems company posted disappointing
results. The stock continued lower to $11.25 in late trading.
</P>
<P>
   Health insurance stocks fell sharply after Aetna issued a
warning that its second-quarter results would come in well below
analysts' expectations. Shares of Aetna fell $6.937 to $59.688, a
loss of more than 10 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Overseas, Japan's Nikkei stock average fell 1.98 percent,
Germany's DAX index fell 0.32 percent, Britain's FT-SE 100 fell
1.15 percent, and France's CAC-40 fell 1.58 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
