<HEADLINE> Big Movers in the Stock Market  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks that were moving substantially or trading
heavily Tuesday on the New York Stock Exchange and the Nasdaq Stock
Market.
</P>
<P>
NYSE
</P>
<P>
   Aetna, down $6.937 to $59.688
</P>
<P>
   The insurer warned that second-quarter earnings may be well
below Wall Street expectations due to rising medical costs at its
health maintenance organizations. Aetna said HMO costs were between
10 percent and 12 percent higher compared with year-ago levels,
mostly from rising use of services such as emergency and outpatient
care.
</P>
<P>
   Unisys, down $2.516 to $11.609
</P>
<P>
   The computer system maker's second-quarter earnings declined to
$56.3 million, less than half of what it was for the same period a
year ago, and below Wall Street's already deflated expectations.
Unisys, which warned of weak business in June, blamed the shortfall
on the deferral of several large technology contracts, continued
weakness in its federal and financial services businesses and
unfavorable foreign exchange rates.
</P>
<P>
   Merrill Lynch, down $3.75 to $128.25
</P>
<P>
   Second-quarter earnings at the brokerage rose 34 percent to $902
million, helped by strong underwriting revenue. The results beat
analyst expectations by a wide margin.
</P>
<P>
   General Motors, up 43.8 cents to $60.813
</P>
<P>
   Second-quarter earnings at the automaker rose 1 percent to $1.75
billion, topping Wall Street forecasts, with a variety of higher
costs in its automotive business offsetting growing revenues.
</P>
<P>
NASDAQ
</P>
<P>
   Intel, down $3.313 to $143
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft, up 31.3 cents to $78.50
</P>
<P>
   Intel's shares pulled back sharply in advance of its
second-quarter profit report, which came out after the close of
trading and topped most Wall Street forecasts. Microsoft's shares
struggled higher before its quarterly report, which also exceeded
projections. Both stocks rose afterwards in extended trading on
other markets.
</P>
<P>
   Copper Mountain, down $29.5 to $94.188
</P>
<P>
   The maker of digital subscriber line systems posted
better-than-expected second-quarter results after Monday's close,
but failed to meet the more optimistic forecasts circulating among
investors before the report.
</P>
<P>
   eLot, up 59.4 cents to $2.469
</P>
<P>
   A House bill that would have banned gambling on the Internet was
voted down late Monday afternoon by an unusual coalition of
libertarian lawmakers, pro-gambling Internet entrepreneurs and
anti-gambling social groups.
</P>
<P>
   Somnus Medical Technologies, up 84.3 cents at $3.781
</P>
<P>
   The company received clearance from the Food and Drug
Administration to sell a new device designed to reduce enlarged
tonsils.
</P>
</TEXT>
