<HEADLINE> Whitman, Menendez are top picks of NJ convention delegates  </HEADLINE>
By LAURENCE ARNOLD
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) - New Jersey convention delegates are playing
favorite son - and favorite daughter - when it comes to the search
for vice presidential candidates.
</P>
<P>
   Gov. Christie Whitman is the No. 1 choice for the No. 2 spot
among Republican delegates from New Jersey, while Rep. Bob Menendez
is the preferred pick of Democrats, according to an Associated
Press survey of the state's convention delegates.
</P>
<P>
   Twenty-nine of the state's 54 GOP delegates offered their
thoughts on vice president, and more than half of them - 16 - named
Whitman as their top pick.
</P>
<P>
   Pennsylvania Gov. Tom Ridge, the top choice among Republicans
nationally, was a distant second to Whitman in New Jersey,
collecting five votes.
</P>
<P>
   Menendez, D-Union City, was mentioned by 18 of the 82 Democratic
delegates who offered their thoughts on the vice presidential slot.
He trailed only ''undecided,'' which got 42 votes.
</P>
<P>
   ''He's an outstanding congressman, and he's right on the
issues,'' said Julio Mendez of Vineland, Democratic chairman in
Cumberland County, a delegate who named Menendez as his top pick
for vice president. ''His Hispanic-Latino background will help
bring in tremendous amounts of support in a lot of the key
states.''
</P>
<P>
   Behind Menendez, with six votes, was former New Jersey Sen. Bill
Bradley, who unsuccessfully challenged Al Gore for the Democratic
nomination and has made clear he is not interested in being No. 2.
</P>
<P>
   The top pick among Democrats nationally, Indiana Gov. Evan Bayh,
got only two votes from Garden State delegates. That's one vote
less than another favorite son, New Jersey Sen. Robert Torricelli,
who rarely makes any speculative vice presidential ''short list''
but who has indicated an interest in running for governor next
year.
</P>
<P>
   Whitman and Menendez did less well among delegates nationally.
Whitman ended up in sixth place among Republicans with 53 votes.
Menendez was 12th among Democrats with 20 votes, meaning he was the
pick of only two delegates outside New Jersey.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley got 106 votes nationally, placing him third behind Bayh
and California Sen. Dianne Feinstein.
</P>
<P>
   Other Democrats who got at least one vote from New Jersey
delegates are Feinstein, Housing and Urban Development Secretary
Andrew Cuomo, Minnesota Gov. Jesse Ventura, House Minority Leader
Dick Gephardt, Energy Secretary Bill Richardson, Defense Secretary
Bill Cohen, North Carolina Gov. Jim Hunt and Massachusetts Sen.
John Kerry.
</P>
<P>
   Besides Whitman and Ridge, New Jersey Republican delegates gave
two votes each to Sen. John McCain of Arizona and retired Gen.
Colin Powell.
</P>
<P>
   Getting one vote each were Rep. J.C. Watts of Oklahoma, New York
Gov. George Pataki, former Labor Secretary Elizabeth Dole and Ohio
Rep. John Kasich.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
