<HEADLINE> Insurer issues profit warning  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   HARTFORD, Conn. (AP) - Aetna warned Tuesday that its
second-quarter earnings were likely to be well below analyst
predictions, blaming an increase in medical costs for its health
maintenance organizations.
</P>
<P>
   Aetna's share prices fell sharply Tuesday - closing at $59.688,
down $6.93, or 10.4 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Aetna's share prices also fell sharply Monday - closing at
$66.625, down $4.50, or a little more than 6 percent - amid reports
that a deal was getting close to sell its financial services and
international businesses to the Dutch company ING Group.
</P>
<P>
   In its announcement Tuesday, Aetna predicted quarterly earnings
of 85 cents to 95 cents per share. Analysts surveyed by First Call
on Monday had estimate earnings in the area of $1.20 per share. The
company is scheduled to report its earnings Aug. 4.
</P>
<P>
   The second-quarter commercial HMO cost trend was up between 10
percent and 12 percent over last year's levels, Aetna said. Most of
the increase was due to more people seeking services, including
emergency room and outpatient care, the company said.
</P>
<P>
   Costs are also up in its Prudential HMO and Medicare HMO
businesses, Aetna said.
</P>
<P>
   ''While our current-period information is not complete, we
wanted to alert our shareholders to this rise in medical costs,''
said Aetna's chairman and chief executive officer, William H.
Donaldson.
</P>
<P>
   ''We are highly focused on actions we are taking to address the
underlying causes of these higher costs and to offset their impact
on our customers and on earnings going forward,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Aside from administrative cost-cutting, Aetna is looking at
beefing up its ''on-site'' consultations on medical practices and
planning to demand premium increases in health plans that renew in
the fourth quarter.
</P>
<P>
   The company also said it might retool its plans to use ''tiered
co-pays,'' which it said have an effect on demand for medical
service.
</P>
<P>
   The Wall Street Journal and The Hartford Courant reported last
week that ING was again the leading candidate to buy the Aetna
businesses, despite the earlier collapse of exclusive talks.
</P>
<P>
   Aetna's board was reported to be considering the deal over the
weekend. The Courant, citing analysts, said a delay in announcing
any agreement may be due to the complexity of the deal, which Aetna
wants to structure so that it minimizes the tax consequences.
</P>
<P>
   ''It wouldn't be shocking if that can hold up a deal for three
days,'' said Ken Abramowitz of Sanford C. Bernstein &AMP; Co.
</P>
<P>
   Aetna and ING have refused to comment on the reports.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
