<HEADLINE> German Hostage Returns Home  </HEADLINE>
By JUERGEN VOGES
<TEXT>
<P>
   BERLIN (AP) -- The German woman held almost three months as a
hostage in the Philippines by Muslim rebels arrived back in Germany
Tuesday to headlines heralding her release and welcoming her home.
</P>
<P>
   ''Free! Free! Finally Free!'' the mass-market Bild newspaper
trumpeted, echoing the rest of the German media.
</P>
<P>
   About 20 hours after her release, Renate Wallert, 56, stepped
off a Lufthansa jet in Frankfurt supported by her son Dirk, 30.
Clutching a bouquet and looking tired but happy, she waved quickly
to gathered onlookers.
</P>
<P>
   A helicopter quickly whisked her away to Goettingen for
examination. Doctors said Tuesday the 56-year-old woman was in good
physical health, although exhausted and traumatized. During her
captivity, she suffered from high blood pressure and anxiety and
repeatedly pleaded to be set free to seek medical help.
</P>
<P>
   Left behind as captives in the Philippines were her husband,
Walter, 57, and her 27-year-old son Marc. They were on an Easter
holiday diving vacation at a Malaysian resort when they were
captured along with 18 other hostages and taken to Jolo island.
</P>
<P>
   ''It was not good,'' Wallert said of the hostage situation
before boarding the flight from the Philippines.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout the ordeal, neighbors have trimmed the family's lawn
and tended their garden, keeping faith that Wallert's captives
would set her free.
</P>
<P>
   Chancellor Gerhard Schroeder said Monday that while all of
Germany was excited about Wallert's release, the government
remained equally concerned about the fate of the remaining
hostages.
</P>
<P>
   That was a sentiment shared by Wallert's neighbors.
</P>
<P>
   ''The hostage takers are nothing but pirates,'' said next-door
neighbor Herbert Gatzemeier. ''The responsible governments should
negotiate with them and money should not play a role.''
</P>
<P>
   Officials said Monday that no ransom was paid to secure her
release, but Schroeder was vague.
</P>
<P>
   ''What had to be done was done,'' Schroeder said. ''It really
makes no sense to spread details now.''
</P>
<P>
   Foreign Minister Joschka Fischer, who stopped in the Philippines
last week to push for a resolution to the hostage crisis, declined
to comment.
</P>
<P>
   The Abu Sayyaf rebels abducted the hostages from a Malaysian
diving resort on April 23.
</P>
<P>
   The hostage negotiations were suspended for more than a month
after the rebels' demands began escalating. But contacts resumed
last week.
</P>
<P>
   Demands have included government assistance for various
development projects and creation of an independent nation for the
Philippines Muslim minority.
</P>
<P>
   The Abu Sayyaf is the smaller of two groups fighting for a
separate Islamic state.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
