<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-18 19:14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Broadway producer David Merrick remembered  </HEADLINE>
By MARY CAMPBELL
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) - Broadway producer David Merrick, last of the
independent, flamboyant impresarios, was remembered Tuesday as a
showman, tyrant and publicity wizard at a memorial service at the
St. James Theater, where his ''Hello, Dolly!'' and ''42nd Street''
ran for years.
</P>
<P>
   Zack Manna, executive director of the David Merrick Arts
Foundation, said Merrick ''was the last of the great American
showmen, respected, feared, admired and hated but never ignored. He
was no saint and he worked hard making sure people understood
that.''
</P>
<P>
   Merrick died April 25 in London. He had been ill for some time,
having suffered a stroke in 1983 that left him severely disabled
and forced him to use a wheelchair.
</P>
<P>
   Merrick dominated New York theater in Broadway's Golden Age
after World War II, producing more than 80 shows including
''Oliver!,'' ''Carnival,'' ''Fanny,'' ''Look Back in Anger,''
''Becket,'' ''Irma La Douce,'' ''Play It Again, Sam,'' ''A Taste of
Honey,'' ''Stop the World - I Want to Get Off,'' ''Cactus Flower,''
''Philadelphia, Here I Come,'' ''Forty Carats,'' ''I Do! I Do!''
and ''Promises, Promises.''
</P>
<P>
   About 800 people attended the memorial service. Music from his
productions played a focal part.
</P>
<P>
   Brent Barrett sang the title song from Merrick's first success,
''Fanny,'' and Melissa Brezinsky sang from an opera Merrick
produced on Broadway, Gian Carlo Menotti's ''Maria Golovin.'' Brian
Stokes Mitchell, whose first leading part on Broadway was in
Merrick's ''Oh, Kay!,'' sang from ''Dolly,'' and Karen Ziemba from
''42nd Street.'' Howard McGillin, star of ''Mack and Mabel'' in
London, sang ''I Won't Send Flowers'' from that show.
</P>
<P>
   Clive Barnes, the theater critic of the New York Post, said
Merrick liked to terrorize theater critics. Then he could believe
their bad notices were spite and their good notices were the result
of terror, he said. He added that Merrick had the courage to close
failures, like ''Breakfast at Tiffany's'' and ''Mata Hari.''
</P>
<P>
   Howard Kissel of the Daily News, author of a Merrick biography,
joked that Merrick timed his death well - a few days after that of
his lifelong Broadway producer rival Alexander Cohen. Cohen's
obituary ran on a Saturday and Merrick's in better-read midweek
editions, and on page 1.
</P>
<P>
   Merrick liked playing stunts as a way of getting publicity,
Kissel said. One of his most famous involved the musical ''Subways
Are for Sleeping,'' which received tepid notices from the critics.
Undeterred, Merrick placed a newspaper ad with rave quotes from
seven men who just happened to have the same names as the critics
for New York's seven daily newspapers. The ad ran in one edition of
the New York Herald-Tribune before it was noticed - and then
yanked.
</P>
<P>
   Kissel said Merrick wanted to be known as a crude tyrant, which
he was, but he also loved theater and was a monumental figure in
American theater.
</P>
<P>
   Samuel Liff, an associate producer who worked with Merrick on 45
Broadway shows between 1963 to 1973, said Merrick was a master
showman and someone who had guts and hated to lose. He loved a
fight, Liff said, citing one with Actors Equity that he knew he'd
lose, saying, ''Otherwise, where's the fun?''
</P>
<P>
   His productions won countless Tony Awards - ''Hello, Dolly!''
alone picked up 10 Tonys in 1964 - as well as other theater prizes
including the New York Drama Critics' Circle Award and London's
Olivier Award.
</P>
<P>
   ''Dolly'' was one of the producer's biggest triumphs. It was
based on Thornton Wilder's ''The Matchmaker,'' which Merrick had
produced successfully on Broadway nearly 10 years earlier with Ruth
Gordon as Dolly Levi.
</P>
<P>
   Merrick was not above bringing culture and serious drama to
Broadway either, particularly the work of British playwrights. He
imported plays by John Osborne, Tom Stoppard, Shelagh Delaney and
Joe Orton, as well as Irish author Brian Friel.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-07-18-00 1914 </TRAILER>
