<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Whitman signs school construction bill  </HEADLINE>
By KATHLEEN CANNON
<TEXT>
<P>
   CRANFORD, N.J. (AP) - From the poorest neighborhood to the
richest enclave, schools throughout New Jersey will be repaired and
replaced under landmark legislation signed into law Tuesday by Gov.
Christie Whitman.
</P>
<P>
   The state will borrow $8.6 billion - $6 billion for the state's
30 so-called special needs districts, $2.6 billion for all other
schools - to finance the construction project, New Jersey's largest
ever.
</P>
<P>
   The law's enactment comes more than two years after the state
was ordered by the state Supreme Court to provide full funding to
improve overcrowded and aged facilities in the 30 poor districts.
</P>
<P>
   But the legislation also provides aid to wealthier districts,
such as this Union County town where the governor staged a bill
signing ceremony.
</P>
<P>
   Cranford, where residents enjoy a municipal pool and clay tennis
courts, was considered too wealthy to qualify for state aid under
the old funding formula. But like all school districts, it is now
eligible for a minimum 40 percent state reimbursement for any new
construction project.
</P>
<P>
   To mark the bill's impact on the poor schools, Whitman later
Tuesday traveled to Burlington City, one of the 30 poor districts,
to tour a 79-year-old school earmarked for demolition. City school
officials are eager to replace the school, where two years ago, an
auditorium ceiling fell on vacant seats occupied just hours earlier
by children attending an assembly.
</P>
<P>
   ''Today marks the delivery of the most important promise of all:
making sure we provide safe, secure and sturdy schools for all
students,'' the governor said in Cranford. ''This bill answers the
Supreme Court mandate responsively and responsibly.''
</P>
<P>
   The state Economic Development Authority will oversee most of
the construction. It will be a huge undertaking, but the governor
gave the agency a vote of confidence.
</P>
<P>
   ''The EDA has a long history of completing projects and doing
them well,'' she said. ''This is an awful lot of money to spend,
but I think we'll do a very good job.''
</P>
<P>
   Whitman said some maintenance jobs may start this school year,
but predicted that large-scale building projects will have to wait
until spring 2001.
</P>
<P>
   The governor thanked lawmakers for finally passing the bill,
despite two years of political haggling over its terms. The version
she signed Tuesday contained changes she previously suggested in an
earlier conditional veto of the original measure.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the sponsors of the bill, Whitman singled out
Senate President Donald DiFrancesco for special thanks. The bill
signing was held in his legislative district.
</P>
<P>
   DiFrancesco, who negotiated the final version of the legislation
with the governor in the last frantic weeks before summer recess,
said he was ''on pins and needles'' when the bill was before the
state Assembly for final passage last week.
</P>
<P>
   ''This was a difficult bill to get through,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ''I appreciate you finally putting your pen to this
legislation,'' DiFrancesco told the governor. ''Children can now
look forward to brighter, safer and improved schools and school
boards and parents can look forward to the tax benefits,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The bill continues the trend of shifting the costs of public
education from the local property taxpayer to the state, the Senate
president said.
</P>
<P>
   Lynn Strickland of the Garden State Coalition of Schools said
suburban taxpayers will appreciate the relief. Richer districts
previously had to shoulder a far larger share of local building
projects, she noted.
</P>
<P>
   ''We're grateful the state recognized the needs that affect our
communities and kids,'' she said. ''We are awed at the task
ahead.''
</P>
<P>
   Frank Belluscio, spokesman for the New Jersey School Boards
Association, said taxpayers in poor districts also deserve, and
will receive, tax relief under the new law.
</P>
<P>
   ''These are developments for the community that are of historic
proportion,'' agreed Burlington City School Superintendent Edward
Gola.
</P>
<P>
   Despite a fresh coat of paint, and careful attention to
maintenance, the Watts Middle School in the city is not prepared to
meet the educational challenges of the new century, Gola said. It
is not air-conditioned; the classrooms are too small and can't
accommodate high technology.
</P>
<P>
   The school would cost $11 million to replace. Under the new law,
the state will foot the entire bill.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
