<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-18 20:04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.N. Refugee Official Enters Debates  </HEADLINE>
By NICOLE WINFIELD
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- The top U.N. refugee official weighed in Tuesday
on the U.S.-led campaign to better care for the world's
''internally displaced,'' saying the debate sparked by U.S.
Ambassador Richard Holbrooke was obscuring the real issues.
</P>
<P>
   Sadako Ogata, the U.N. High Commissioner for Refugees, said she
welcomed the new spotlight that Holbrooke has placed on the plight
of the internally displaced -- people who flee their homes but don't
cross borders to seek asylum as refugees do.
</P>
<P>
   But she said the debate has been ''too narrowly focused'' on the
disparity in care between the internally displaced and refugees --
as well as the responsibilities of the various U.N. agencies in
helping them.
</P>
<P>
   ''All the talk of mandates and comparative advantages obscures
certain hard realities,'' Ogata said in a speech sponsored by the
Center for the Study of International Organization, a joint project
of New York University and Princeton University.
</P>
<P>
   The real issue is about solving the wars and other conflicts
that spawn mass population flows -- and moblizing the international
community to try to help end them, she said.
</P>
<P>
   Holbrooke has launched a campaign of sorts for the United
Nations to better care for the world's internally displaced, saying
they should have the same protections as refugees.
</P>
<P>
   International law gives special protections to people who seek
asylum in different countries after being driven from their homes,
and the refugee group was created a half-century ago specifically
to care for them.
</P>
<P>
   But today, the internally displaced number 20 million to 25
million compared to some 15 million refugees.
</P>
<P>
   It's more difficult to provide care for the internally displaced
than for refugees, because aid agencies have to get approval from
governments to gain access. That can get tricky when it is the
government or its policies that the people are fleeing.
</P>
<P>
   In a bid to level the playing field, Holbrooke has suggested the
United Nations refer to the internally displaced as ''internal
refugees.''
</P>
<P>
   But Ogata even cautioned against that seemingly innocuous and
semantic suggestion.
</P>
<P>
   ''Blurring the distinction between refugees and internally
diplaced people may suggest to some that protection provided within
borders is equivalent to the international protection afforded to
refugees,'' Ogata said.
</P>
<P>
   ''We must take care not to undermine the unique legal status of
refugees or to lend encouragement to strategies aimed at containing
displacement. The asylum door has to remain open for people who
genuinely need protection,'' she said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-07-18-00 2004 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000718.0152 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-18 20:05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Senate Rejects Blocking Monuments  </HEADLINE>
By ALAN FRAM
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Senate rejected an effort by Western
Republicans on Tuesday to curb President Clinton's ability to
create any new national monuments as part of his effort to preserve
federal lands.
</P>
<P>
   But across the Capitol, GOP senators joined a fresh battle
against the White House by pushing a bill through a committee that
would make it harder for the Justice Department to pursue the
multibillion-dollar federal lawsuit against the tobacco industry.
</P>
<P>
   The action came as lawmakers on both sides of the Capitol
focused on spending bills for fiscal 2001, which begins Oct. 1.
Just one of the 13 annual bills has so far been signed into law,
and House and Senate leaders are trying to complete as many as
possible before lawmakers take their August recess for the
political conventions.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate began the day by approving a $15.5 billion measure
financing the Interior Department and federal cultural programs.
</P>
<P>
   The measure -- similar to a House-approved bill -- faces a White
House veto threat because it trims Clinton proposals for federal
land purchases and some energy efficiency programs. It also
contains provisions he opposes like letting ranchers who lease
public lands renew their leases without getting environmental
reviews.
</P>
<P>
   But in a 50-49 vote, senators rejected an amendment by Senate
Majority Whip Don Nickles, R-Okla., that would have forbidden
Clinton to name any new national monuments without congressional
approval. Clinton has so far this year set aside nearly 2 million
acres of federal land as monuments, a designation that limits the
type of allowable recreational and commercial uses.
</P>
<P>
   ''I happen to be in favor of national monuments,'' Nickles said.
''But I think we should have local input.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton has designated the monuments under a 1906 law that lets
him do so without consulting lawmakers.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Richard Durbin, D-Ill., contrasted Nickles' proposal with
the actions of President Theodore Roosevelt, a Republican who led
early 20th century efforts to create national parks.
</P>
<P>
   ''The party of Teddy Roosevelt officially abandons its
commitment to his environmental legacy,'' Durbin said of Tuesday's
vote.
</P>
<P>
   The vote highlighted the sensitivity that environmental issues
have in an election year. Of the six GOP senators who voted ''no,''
five are up for re-election in November.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, by a single 28-0 vote, the Senate Appropriations
Committee approved a pair of bills: a $36.6 billion measure
financing the Commerce, Justice and State departments, and a $22.5
billion bill financing energy and water projects and nuclear
weapons testing.
</P>
<P>
   The Commerce-Justice bill contains language forbidding federal
agencies from transferring money to the Justice Department so it
can continue its suit against cigarette companies. With the legal
action, the government hopes to recover its costs of treating the
elderly, veterans and others for tobacco-related illnesses -- an
effort that federal officials say will cost $20 billion a year.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Ernest Hollings, D-S.C., offered an amendment to provide
the Justice Department with $20 million for the lawsuit's costs
next year. It was rejected on a 14-14 tie, with only Sen. Arlen
Specter, R-Pa., crossing party lines to vote for Hollings'
proposal.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, the House dealt the cigarette industry a defeat on
the same issue, voting to let Justice accept money from other
agencies.
</P>
<P>
   The Commerce-Justice bill also provides $500 million for
supporting U.N. peacekeeping missions, nearly $239 million less
than Clinton wanted.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the House Appropriations Committee used a voice vote
to approve a $29.1 billion bill financing the Treasury Department
and some smaller agencies.
</P>
<P>
   That bill would pave the way for a 2.7 percent cost-of-living
salary increase for members of Congress, which next January would
add $3,800 to their current $141,300 salaries. An amendment by Rep.
Virgil Goode, R-Va., to block the increase lost by voice vote.
</P>
<P>
   The bill faces a White House veto threat because of cuts to
Clinton proposals for the Internal Revenue Service and some
anti-terrorism programs.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-07-18-00 2005 </TRAILER>
