<BODY>
<HEADLINE> No Indians in New Fiji Cabinet  </HEADLINE>
By PAUL ALEXANDER
<TEXT>
<P>
   SUVA, Fiji (AP) -- The swearing-in of Fiji's Cabinet was
postponed Wednesday after the island's new president became ill,
delaying a process aimed at helping Fiji recover from a paralyzing
hostage crisis.
</P>
<P>
   The postponement came just one day after the lineup for the
panel was revealed, an announcement that drew protest from George
Speight, who threw Fiji into crisis in May when he led an armed
gang into Parliament and took dozens of hostages.
</P>
<P>
   Speight said enough of his supporters weren't in the Cabinet and
he objected to not having been adequately consulted in the
formulation process.
</P>
<P>
   There was speculation that he convinced his people not to show
up for the ceremony.
</P>
<P>
   Local radio reported that five of the 20 Cabinet ministers did
not show up along with four of the 12 assistant ministers. it was
not immediately clear how many of those who didn't attend were
supporters of Speight.
</P>
<P>
   President Ratu Josefa Iloilo ''is ill disposed this morning,''
said Prime Minister Laisenia Qarase. ''So regrettably, the swearing
in ceremony is deferred until further notice.''
</P>
<P>
   Details of Iloilo's condition could not be independently
verified. The frail and elderly tribal chief, who suffers from
Parkinson's disease, was sworn in as president Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Speight's May 19 coup was carried out in the name of
guaranteeing political superiority and affirmative action for
indigenous Fijians and promising redistribution of resources to
benefit them.
</P>
<P>
   The last 18 of the dozens of legislators taken hostage in
Parliament were freed last Thursday as part of a deal that Speight
said would disenfranchise ethnic Indians, who make up 44 percent of
the population but who dominate the economy.
</P>
<P>
   Confusion was apparent after Qarase's announcement, though there
were no immediate signs of unrest. Two Landrovers, however, were
found torched in front of Parliament Wednesday morning. They were
believed to have been burned overnight.
</P>
<P>
   ''We are peeved,' said Kaliopate Tavola, tapped to be foreign
minister in the new Cabinet, of the postponement. ''We want to go
ahead,'' he said, but added that ''there is obviously a genuine
reason for it.''
</P>
<P>
   At his swearing-in ceremony Tuesday, Iloilo committed himself to
forging reconciliation in his ethnically divided South Pacific
nation.
</P>
<P>
   ''We are one, as one nation and one people,'' Iloilo said.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, Speight promised further unrest over the Cabinet.
</P>
<P>
   ''The fun is just beginning,'' he said. ''They are treading on
some dangerous ground. I think they are going to meet some stiff
resistance.''
</P>
<P>
   The British government said Tuesday it was recalling its top
diplomat in Fiji for talks about the deal that won the hostages'
release but left the large ethnic Indian minority with little
representation.
</P>
<P>
   ''Relief at the safe release of all the hostages should not
obscure the fact that the crisis for Fiji is not over,'' Foreign
Minister John Battle said in announcing the recall of British High
Commissioner Michael Dibben.
</P>
<P>
   In the Cabinet named Tuesday, members of Fiji's ethnic Indian
minority initially accepted posts but later withdrew ''due to
concern for the safety of their families,'' according to a
statement from President Ratu Josefa Iloilo's office. Indo-Fijians
make up 44 percent of Fiji's population, but the only Indian in the
new administration will be George Shiu Raj, one of two assistant
ministers for multiethnic affairs -- a non-Cabinet post.
</P>
<P>
   Qarase, who retains the interim post he was appointed to last
week, has released a blueprint for Fiji's future guaranteeing
political superiority and affirmative action for indigenous Fijians
and redistribution of resources to benefit them.
</P>
<P>
   The coup has left Fiji badly damaged: The crucial tourism
industry is in tatters, the hundreds of thousands of Indo-Fijians
have as much as been told they're second-class citizens and many
are planning to leave the country.
</P>
<P>
   The absence of ethnic Indians and presence of Speight supporters
in the Cabinet is likely to prompt more nations to follow New
Zealand's lead, slapping sanctions on Fiji to press for a return to
multiracial democracy. Australia announced Tuesday it would slash
non-humanitarian aid to Fiji, cut most military ties, impose travel
bans on students and athletes and recall its most senior diplomat
for consultations.
</P>
<P>
   Iloilo said Tuesday that the new Cabinet would not allow ethnic
Indians to be completely sidelined.
</P>
<P>
   ''As head of state and as the symbol of national unity in Fiji,
I cannot appoint a Cabinet that is expressly committed to excluding
a particular community,'' he said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier Tuesday, at his swearing-in ceremony, Iloilo committed
himself to forging reconciliation in the ethnically divided nation.
</P>
<P>
   ''We are one, as one nation and one people,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The government has a mandate to guide Fiji to elections in about
18 months.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-07-18-00 2040 </TRAILER>
