<HEADLINE> Los Alamos Judge Rejects Motion  </HEADLINE>
By RICHARD BENKE
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBUQUERQUE, N.M. (AP) -- Evidence seized in a search of the home
of a scientist accused of breaching security at Los Alamos National
Laboratory can be used at the man's trial, a judge ruled Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. District Judge James Parker rejected defense arguments that
the April 1999 search of Wen Ho Lee's home by federal agents was
illegal.
</P>
<P>
   Parker said personal items that prosecutors decide not to use
should be listed for the court by Thursday and promptly returned to
Lee.
</P>
<P>
   The 60-year-old scientist is charged with 59 counts, most
alleging he transferred restricted information from secure to
unsecure computers and computer tapes. He has pleaded innocent and
his trial is due to begin Nov. 6.
</P>
<P>
   Lee's lawyers contended the search warrant allowed agents to
seize virtually anything. Among books seized was the collected
plays of Tennessee Williams. Defense attorneys Mark Holscher and
John Cline wanted the entire search ruled illegal and the evidence
barred.
</P>
<P>
   But Parker said the fact that agents seized less than 10 percent
of what they searched showed the warrant's specificity.
</P>
<P>
   Neither Cline nor prosecutor George Stamboulidis would comment
on the ruling. A message was left seeking comment from Holscher in
Los Angeles.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
