<HEADLINE> Agent: Titans, George Reach Deal  </HEADLINE>
By TOM SHARP
<TEXT>
<P>
   NASHVILLE, Tenn. (AP) -- Eddie George became one of the
highest-paid running backs in the NFL on Tuesday when the Tennessee
Titans announced they gave the three-time Pro Bowl selection a
$41.25 million multiyear contract extension.
</P>
<P>
   The deal extends George's contract for six years and gives him
the option to play a seventh, for an extra $4 million. It also
includes a $10 million signing bonus.
</P>
<P>
   Last year the Indianapolis Colts signed rookie running back
Edgerrin James to a seven-year, $49 million contract, while the St.
Louis Rams signed Marshall Faulk to a seven-year, $45 million deal.
Jamal Anderson of the Atlanta Falcons picked up a five-year, $32
million contract last year.
</P>
<P>
   The Titans had made signing George their top priority after
giving coach Jeff Fisher a new contract in the offseason. George,
the 1995 Heisman Trophy winner from Ohio State, has been the focus
of the offense since he was drafted in 1996. He said he wanted the
deal done before reporting for training camp Friday.
</P>
<P>
   George, who turns 27 in September, has not missed a game in his
first four seasons and has 25 100-yard games with the Titans
winning 20 of those. He turned in a career-high with 1,762 combined
yards and a career-best 13 touchdowns last season as the franchise
reached its first Super Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   George is one of four running backs to rush for at least 1,200
yards in each of their first four seasons, along with Eric
Dickerson, Earl Campbell and Barry Sanders.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-07-18-00 2044 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000718.0163 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-18 20:50 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> State sues factory owners over Coxsackie cleanup  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) - A $7 million lawsuit has been filed by the
state Attorney General's Office to recoup cleanup costs for the
toxic waste site of a former factory in Greene County
</P>
<P>
   The suit charges that Jack Guterman and his son Frederick
violated the state's Superfund law and created a public nuisance at
the American Valve Manufacturing Corp. in Coxsackie. The company
operated the factory from 1920 until 1988.
</P>
<P>
   The site was declared a state Superfund hazardous waste site in
1991 after engineering tests uncovered polluted soil and surface
water leaching onto adjoining properties, as well as hazardous
materials stored in the building.
</P>
<P>
   The pollution includes lead-laden sand and perchloroethylene, a
toxic solvent that was dumped there and contaminated the
groundwater.
</P>
<P>
   In 1992, the state began emergency cleanup efforts, stopping the
polluted soil and surface water from flowing onto adjoining parcels
and removing pollutant laden-drums from the factory.
</P>
<P>
   Though state Department of Environmental Conservation officials
said last year that the company's owners were hard to find and that
the state might have to pay the bill, the Attorney General's Office
said it had located the Gutermans, who now operate American Valve
in Greensboro, N.C.
</P>
<P>
   The long-delayed site cleanup is expected to begin in the fall.
The state decided in 1999 to make the project a one-phase effort
instead of two.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-07-18-00 2050 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000718.0164 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-18 20:51 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sherman Prepares For Training Camp  </HEADLINE>
By GREG BEACHAM
<TEXT>
<P>
   GREEN BAY, Wis. (AP) -- Mike Sherman believes all the pieces are
in place for the Green Bay Packers to be a contender again. He says
it's up to him to put those pieces in the right order.
</P>
<P>
   Sherman, the Packers' third head coach in 19 months, realizes
the enormity of the task facing him in his first training camp,
which gets under way Wednesday. He must combine his new players and
coaching staff with the Packers' veterans, and then he must
convince everyone that Green Bay is still a championship city.
</P>
<P>
   ''This is a huge undertaking,'' he said. ''But I'm looking
forward to it. I've been waiting my entire career for this
challenge, and I'm glad I got it in Green Bay.''
</P>
<P>
   Ray Rhodes -- hired last season to replace Sherman's mentor, Mike
Holmgren -- had a one-year term as the Packers' coach that ended
hours after Green Bay beat Arizona in the season finale. The
Packers finished 8-8 and missed the playoffs for the first time in
seven seasons.
</P>
<P>
   After one dynamite interview with general manager Ron Wolf,
Sherman was named the 13th coach in the Packers' 80-year history in
January. He spent the offseason holding four minicamps and
shuffling a new coaching staff into town, all in preparation for
the task awaiting them this fall.
</P>
<P>
   Sherman also made the rounds for speeches and public
appearances, all designed to convince the team's fan base that the
Packers' glory days aren't over. Sherman and Wolf both believe
Green Bay doesn't need to rebuild; it needs only to recapture the
drive and acumen that led the team to consecutive NFC titles less
than three years ago.
</P>
<P>
   The Packers' rookies, free agents and quarterbacks reported to
the dorms at St. Norbert College in De Pere on Tuesday. They'll be
joined by the veterans on the weekend, with just two weeks to
prepare for the Aug. 4 preseason opener against the New York Jets.
</P>
<P>
   Early indications are that Sherman, a stickler for preparation
who said he already had scripted out the first four weeks of
training camp by April, will run a more structured workout regimen
than either Holmgren or Rhodes. Practices begin promptly at 8:45
a.m. almost every day, with the second session of the day usually
lasting past 4 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   Sherman said the first two weeks of camp will be critical. While
Green Bay will still use the West Coast offense, the Packers will
be learning an entirely new defense brought to town from Denver by
new defensive coordinator Ed Donatell, and the teaching process
will take weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Green Bay's veteran defensive stalwarts -- LeRoy Butler, Santana
Dotson, Vonnie Holliday and others -- will be changing their games
toward a smaller, faster style of play anchored by new nose tackle
Russell Maryland. And though Donatell will largely run that show,
Sherman is the one who must sell it to his players and the fans.
</P>
<P>
   ''We don't have the size up front that we used to have, but we
do have a tenacious style of defense and defenders that hopefully
can make things happen,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   In keeping with his fan-friendly attitude, Sherman also has
opened to the public an extra week of practices. The crowds of
Green Bay faithful who gather daily at the Don Hutson Center will
now be allowed to watch until Aug. 24, just 10 days before the
Packers' regular season opener against the Jets on Sept. 3.
</P>
<P>
   The players will once again be housed in dorms on the St.
Norbert campus. To foster a spirit of camaraderie, Sherman, a
former English teacher, used team buses to transport players to the
Don Hutson Center during minicamps, and he plans to continue the
practice in training camp.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's just a way to get guys feeling like a team,'' Sherman
said. ''We're out here to learn and to teach, but we're also here
to get to know each other. These guys already know a lot about how
to play football. We have to learn to work with each other and for
each other.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
