<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-18 21:05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Raceway takes another punch to its purse  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   MONTICELLO, N.Y. (AP) - Hit hard by shrinking crowds and
dwindling receipts, Monticello Raceway was disappointed again.
</P>
<P>
   New York City Off Track Betting won't be simulcasting Monticello
races, at least for July. The halt could cost the track about
$6,000 per racing day, which management shares evenly with the
horsemen.
</P>
<P>
   The reason depends on whom you believe.
</P>
<P>
   The president of OTB said there's just not enough daytime space
on the OTB broadcast schedule. OTB has commitments to simulcast
thoroughbred racing during the day. Thoroughbred tracks bring OTB
at least $300,000 each a day in bets. Monticello, a harness track,
brings in about $100,000.
</P>
<P>
   ''There's just no room,'' said Bill Carnevale, the president of
OTB, who said the track could be back on the air by August.
</P>
<P>
   Raceway president Cliff Ehrlich, along with the new head of the
horesmen's association, wonder. The raceway didn't support a bill
to allow night simulcasting of out-of-state thoroughbred races.
With more betting opportunities, they say less would be bet at
Monticello and other harness tracks.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
