<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Titans, George Reach 6-Year Deal  </HEADLINE>
By TOM SHARP
<TEXT>
<P>
   NASHVILLE, Tenn. (AP) -- Eddie George became one of the
highest-paid running backs in the NFL on Tuesday when the Tennessee
Titans announced they signed the three-time Pro Bowl selection to a
$41.25 million multiyear contract extension.
</P>
<P>
   The deal extends George's contract for six years and includes an
option for a seventh for an extra $4 million. It also includes a
$10 million signing bonus in what general manager Floyd Reese
called ''probably the biggest deal we've ever done.''
</P>
<P>
   ''We wanted to keep our core players. That's the way to build a
team,'' said team president Jeff Diamond. ''He hasn't missed a game
in his career, he's a solid guy on and off the field, a great
credit to the team and the community. You have to have confidence
in the type of people you make these commitments to.''
</P>
<P>
   The contract takes George through the 2006 season, which would
be his 11th in the NFL.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's not often a professional athlete stays with one
organization his whole career, and I have an opportunity to do
that,'' George said. ''I'm glad we could get it done. It's a big
weight off my shoulders.''
</P>
<P>
   Last year the Indianapolis Colts signed rookie running back
Edgerrin James to a seven-year, $49 million contract, while the St.
Louis Rams signed Marshall Faulk to a seven-year, $45 million deal.
Jamal Anderson of the Atlanta Falcons picked up a five-year, $32
million contract last year.
</P>
<P>
   The Titans had made signing George their top priority after
giving coach Jeff Fisher a new contract in the offseason. George,
the 1995 Heisman Trophy winner from Ohio State, has been the focus
of the offense since he was drafted in 1996. He said he wanted the
deal done before reporting for training camp Friday.
</P>
<P>
   ''It really doesn't matter who is the highest paid,'' he said.
''I've always concerned myself with fair-market value.''
</P>
<P>
   Reese said George, known for his devotion to fitness, ''is
probably one of the few guys who could make seven years and maybe
go farther.''
</P>
<P>
   George said he does not believe the contract will change his
role on the team.
</P>
<P>
   ''The only thing that changes is my bank account,'' he said.
''I'll continue to challenge myself and my teammates to have a
better season than we had last year. ... I'll take it a season at a
time and hopefully at the end I'll have seven rings.''
</P>
<P>
   George, who turns 27 in September, has not missed a game in his
four seasons, and has 25 100-yard games with the Titans winning 20
of those. He turned in a career-high with 1,762 combined yards and
a career-best 13 touchdowns last season as the franchise reached
its first Super Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   George is one of four running backs to rush for at least 1,200
yards in each of their first four seasons, along with Eric
Dickerson, Earl Campbell and Barry Sanders.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
