<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-18 21:18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> House Again Votes on China Trade  </HEADLINE>
By JIM ABRAMS
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) - Two months after voting to end the annual
battle over trade with China, the House debated and defeated a
resolution again Tuesday to block renewal of normal trade relations
in the coming year.
</P>
<P>
   The vote became necessary because the Senate has yet to take up
the bill the House passed in May that grants China permanent normal
trade status in conjunction with China's approaching entry into the
World Trade Organization.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike in past years, Tuesday's outcome was never in doubt. The
House voted down on a 281-147 vote a resolution to reject President
Clinton's decision extending normal trade status to China for
another year.
</P>
<P>
   The debate did give critics of China another chance to express
views that China, because of its human rights violations, weapons
proliferation and trade practices, does not deserve low tariffs and
other privileges enjoyed by other U.S. trading partners.
</P>
<P>
   ''We've been sold a bill of goods,'' said Rep. Dana Rohrabacher,
R-Calif., the resolution's sponsor. China's persecution of
dissidents and weapons transactions ''have been going in the wrong
direction'' since the previous vote on permanent normal trade
relations, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Archer, R-Texas, the House Ways and Means Committee
chairman, countered that he was disappointed that the House had to
return to China trade after it approved the bill to provide
''unprecedented access to China's once forbidden markets.''
Agriculture exports alone would triple as a result of permanent
trade status, Archer said.
</P>
<P>
   Since China's 1989 suppression of the Tiananmen student
movement, anti-communist and human rights advocates from both right
and left have tried to block the president's annual renewal of
China's trade status. They came close but failed to overcome a
majority who argued that unilateral sanctions do not work, and
expanded trade with China is the best way to promote a more open
and democratic Chinese society.
</P>
<P>
   As part of China's agreement to remove trade barriers so that it
can join the WTO, the House voted 237-197 in May to extend
permanent trade status, which supposedly ended the annual debates.
</P>
<P>
   While support for permanent status is strong in the Senate,
however, hopes of a vote in July, before Congress leaves on its
August recess, have faded because of a dispute over a companion
bill that would impose sanctions on China for future violations of
weapons proliferation treaties.
</P>
<P>
   Senate Majority Leader Trent Lott, R-Miss., suggested Tuesday
that the Senate might begin debate next week but wouldn't complete
work on the trade bill until lawmakers return to Washington in
September.
</P>
<P>
   The White House called Lott's comment ''a positive step.
</P>
<P>
   ''But with wide bipartisan support for this agreement, it is
critical that the Senate lock in the final vote,'' said White House
spokesman Jake Siewert.
</P>
<P>
   Senate GOP leaders have argued the anti-proliferation bill,
sponsored by Sen. Fred Thompson, R-Tenn., must be taken up first.
That tactic was partly to fend off possible amendments to the trade
bill offered by lawmakers insistent that the United States not give
up its ability to punish China when it violates international norms
of behavior.
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton administration has opposed the Thompson bill, and
efforts to reach a compromise on a bill to monitor China's weapons
sales have broken off.
</P>
<P>
   ''Today's announcement is a positive step, but with wide
bipartisan support for this agreement, it is critical that the
senate lock in the final vote.'' White House Spokesman Jake Siewert
</P>
<P>
   Senate Foreign Relations Committee Chairman Jesse Helms, R-N.C.,
among the staunchest opponents of the trade bill, opened two days
of hearings Tuesday on the human rights and national security
effects of the legislation. ''It seems to me regrettable that many
in this town have deluded themselves into believing that a trade
deal with China will somehow transform that communist dictatorship
into a normal government that behaves itself,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   At least one longtime foe of granting China normal trade status,
Rep. Nancy Pelosi, D-Calif., admitted ''the House has spoken on
this issue'' with its vote last May.
</P>
<P>
   ''What choice do I have but to see this as an opportunity,'' she
said, speaking of the permanent trade bill's creation of a
commission to monitor China's human rights activities.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   The bill is H.J.Res. 103
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: Congressional summary: http://thomas.loc.gov
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
