<HEADLINE> Tuesday's Canada News Briefs  </HEADLINE>
By The Associated PressNote: All dollars are Canadian unless otherwise noted
<TEXT>
<P>
   National Crime Rate at Lowest Level in 20 Years
</P>
<P>
   OTTAWA (AP) -- The national crime rate fell last year to its
lowest level in two decades, new statistics show.
</P>
<P>
   Statistics Canada released figures Tuesday indicating the crime
rate, based on police data, fell five per cent -- the eighth
consecutive annual drop.
</P>
<P>
   Youth crime was down 7.2 per cent and was 21 per cent lower than
in 1989.
</P>
<P>
   Substantial drops in the three largest provinces drove the
overall decline. The crime rate fell 7.8 per cent in Quebec, 7.4
per cent in Ontario and 4.9 per cent in British Columbia.
</P>
<P>
   The rate of violent crime fell 2.4 per cent in 1999, the seventh
consecutive drop. However, the rate was still five per cent higher
than in 1989 and 57 per cent higher than in 1979.
</P>
<P>
   ---
</P>
<P>
   Prime Minister Looks at Alberta Tornado Aftermath
</P>
<P>
   PINE LAKE, Alberta (AP) -- Prime Minister Jean Chretien got a
first-hand look Tuesday at the ''incredible destruction'' left by a
deadly tornado in central Alberta and offered sympathy and help to
the victims.
</P>
<P>
   Chretien said his heart went out to survivors of the tornado,
which claimed the lives of 11 people after it ripped through the
Green Acres campground and trailer park Friday night.
</P>
<P>
   He was escorted by park owners Danny and Lexy Fisher, who
explained that the site has been a holiday destination for 53 years
and visited by four generations of families. The Fishers knew all
the regulars and lost several friends to the twister. Chretien
wished them luck in rebuilding their lives.
</P>
<P>
   ''This is certainly a very difficult period and I'm here to
offer my sympathy to all concerned and to have a look at the
damage,'' he said.
---
</P>
<P>
   Cops Release Drawings of Suspect Who Stabbed Doctor
</P>
<P>
   VANCOUVER, British Columbia (AP) -- Police released two composite
drawings Tuesday in the hopes they will generate leads across North
America on a man they believe stabbed abortion provider Dr. Garson
Romalis.
</P>
<P>
   Const. Anne Drennan, spokeswoman for the Vancouver police, said
officers are hoping the composite sketches of the man, drawn with
information obtained from two independent witnesses, will jog
someone's memory.
</P>
<P>
   ''Both of these witnesses had substantial opportunity to view
the suspect prior to the stabbing of Dr. Romalis,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   ''Both witnesses describe these composites as a very good
likeness of the suspect.''
---
</P>
<P>
   Databank To Trace Antibiotic Resistance
</P>
<P>
   TORONTO (AP) -- A new national system to track antibiotic
resistance -- recently deemed a major threat to global health by the
World Health Organization -- is being set up across Canada.
</P>
<P>
   The Surveillance Network was announced Tuesday by Bayer Inc. The
pharmaceutical giant is funding the project, which will amass and
crunch data from 67 contributing sites across Canada.
</P>
<P>
   The system will give doctors up-to-date information on
resistance trends, allowing them to refine patient care and
prescribe antibiotics more appropriately.
</P>
<P>
   ''The surveillance system not only helps you make decisions
about therapy, but it also makes you aware of or allows you to see
emerging trends that you might not have expected otherwise,'' said
Dr. Donald Low, acting chief of microbiology at Mount Sinai
Hospital in Toronto.
</P>
<P>
   The tracking system is the second in the world, following on the
heels of a system established in the United States. It, like the
Canadian database, is run by a company called MRL, of Herndon, Va.,
which specializes in monitoring antimicrobial resistance.
---
</P>
<P>
   Propane Spill on Vancouver Island Raises Explosion Fears
</P>
<P>
   LANGFORD, British Columbia (AP) --Tourists, truckers and
residents whisked from their homes, vehicles and campsites near
Victoria remained stranded Tuesday after a truck carrying
potentially explosive propane flipped over and began to leak.
</P>
<P>
   The Trans Canada Highway, the main artery between Victoria and
Nanaimo, was closed after the crash, which occurred at 10 p.m.
Monday and killed the driver.
</P>
<P>
   The truck was carrying 38,000 litres of liquid propane. As it
leaks, it turns to gas.
</P>
<P>
   It was Tuesday morning before officials could even get near the
spill.
</P>
<P>
   Stew Young, mayor of Langford, a suburb of Victoria, said a
propane industry emergency response team from Vancouver would
siphon off the propane into another holding tank.
</P>
<P>
   Officials worried the slightest spark could cause an explosion.
---
</P>
<P>
   Ontario Government Apologizes for Water Report Reluctance
</P>
<P>
   TORONTO (AP) -- The Ontario government apologized Tuesday for its
initial reluctance to release a report that details water-quality
problems at more than 100 towns, cities and campgrounds across the
province.
</P>
<P>
   ''There are no excuses, this information should have come out
sooner,'' said Tim Hudak, Minister of Northern Development and
Mines.
</P>
<P>
   Hudak, who faced an angry throng of reporters in place of
vacationing Environment Minister Dan Newman, released the document
Tuesday -- a day after it came to light in a newspaper report.
</P>
<P>
   The incident is the latest in a series of setbacks for the
Environment Ministry, which has repeatedly come under fire since
mid-May, when E. coli-infested tap water in the Ontario farming
community of Walkerton killed six people and sickened 2,000.
</P>
<P>
   Hudak insisted Tuesday the ministry is committed to disclosing
all information about water quality, and suggested it had been a
mistake not to release the Environment Ministry report sooner.
</P>
