<HEADLINE> Grizzlies Sign Stromile Swift  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   VANCOUVER, British Columbia (AP) -- Fresh off a week of workouts
with new Vancouver Grizzlies teammate Shareef Abdur-Rahim, Stromile
Swift signed his first pro contract Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The 6-foot-10 forward from Louisiana State, the No. 2 overall
pick in last month's NBA draft, signed for the maximum allowed
under the collective bargaining agreement, $8.388 million for three
seasons.
</P>
<P>
   Swift signed the deal, then hit the floor at the Grizzlies'
training facility for the first of four days of workouts with 20
free agents and undrafted rookies hoping to get a spot on the team
Vancouver will take to Salt Lake City next week for six summer
league games.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm just ready to get started and looking forward to having
fun,'' said Swift, who averaged 16.2 points and 8.2 rebounds last
season as a sophomore at LSU.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm taking everything as a learning experience, try to learn
some things I can take with me to the real training camp.''
</P>
<P>
   Swift spent last week at Abdur-Rahim's offseason home in
Atlanta, where the two worked on ballhandling and shooting and
lifted weights. Abdur-Rahim is a notoriously hard worker and Swift
said his biggest challenge was trying to ''keep up with him.''
</P>
<P>
   ''It was real good,'' Swift said. ''He has a nice facility in
his home and we had some good workouts. When we finish with summer
league, I'm going back to Atlanta and we'll probably talk a little
more about what I need to expect in the league.
</P>
<P>
   ''I realize there's a lot he can teach me. I'm ready to learn.''
</P>
<P>
   Swift, a native of Shreveport, La., left school after only two
years, but his mother Mary made him promise to return to school and
finish his degree in sports medicine.
</P>
<P>
   Vancouver struggled to a 22-60 record last season and was ranked
26th in the league in scoring and 17th in points allowed.
</P>
<P>
   Swift joins Abdur-Rahim, Mike Bibby, Michael Dickerson and
Othella Harrington in a young lineup slowly taking shape.
</P>
<P>
   Grizzlies president Dick Versace said he and general manager
Billy Knight are continuing to actively pursue free agents with a
view to adding some backcourt depth.
</P>
<P>
   ''We have a wonderful pair of starting guards and then there's
just a big drop off there. That has to be attacked and we plan on
doing that,'' Versace said.
</P>
</TEXT>
