<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-18 21:30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Congress Pays Tribute to Coverdell  </HEADLINE>
By JEFFREY McMURRAY
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- With his slight frame and a less-than-fiery
speaking style, Paul Coverdell often got lost in the media shuffle
of the Senate. But to Republican leaders, the Georgia senator was
their go-to guy -- willing to take on any task, glamorous or
otherwise.
</P>
<P>
   Lawmakers from both parties said they lost more than a colleague
Tuesday when Coverdell, 61, died from a stroke. They also lost a
rising star, a man who seldom sought credit despite his potential
to climb much higher on the leadership ladder.
</P>
<P>
   ''He was just a gentleman -- a Georgia peach in every sense,''
said Sen. Max Cleland, D-Ga. ''Quiet, calm leadership, gets the job
done.''
</P>
<P>
   When news of Coverdell's death spread, senators observed a
moment of silence on the floor and the House clerk read a
resolution honoring him.
</P>
<P>
   Senate Majority Leader Trent Lott, R-Miss., was visibly choked
up. New York Democrat Pat Moynihan called Coverdell ''a man of
peace,'' and close friend Bill Frist, a Tennessee Republican,
called him a ''mentor.''
</P>
<P>
   ''It's going to take a while for people to realize what they've
lost,'' said Rep. John Linder, R-Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Linder won his primary election Tuesday night against challenger
Vince Littman, but he said dealing with the death of his friend was
his top priority.
</P>
<P>
   Coverdell, Linder and former House Speaker Newt Gingrich are
credited with redefining the Georgia Republican Party. A small
group met every Friday afternoon to map out a strategy for
elevating GOP candidates into key offices.
</P>
<P>
   ''Paul was the guy who pushed things,'' Linder said. ''He was
the logistical guy. When some of us would take a weekend off to
play golf, he would take time away to study politics.''
</P>
<P>
   ''He wasn't necessarily the headlines guy or the bombastic
speaker, but he could organize parties and gather support like
nobody else,'' said Georgia Republican Chairman Chuck Clay. ''While
he may not have got a lot of the credit, you can rest assured most
legislation had the footprints and fingerprints of Paul Coverdell
all over it.''
</P>
<P>
   At state conventions, Coverdell would facilitate business from
behind a screen in the back. Seldom would he get up to speak. He
followed the same pattern in Congress, quietly accepting tasks Lott
handed him.
</P>
<P>
   ''When asked, a lot of people say: 'Thank you very much, but
I've got more than I can say grace over,''' said Sen. Don Nickles,
R-Okla. ''Paul Coverdell was the type of senator who would take it
on. This is the most depressing thing that's happened to us in a
long, long time.''
</P>
<P>
   Coverdell's latest project was scripting Republican priorities
for the budget surplus -- a list led by Social Security and Medicare
preservation. It was unknown whether he heard the Congressional
Budget Office's announcement Monday that it had underestimated the
next decade's surplus by almost half.
</P>
<P>
   Before that, Lott gave Coverdell the somewhat dubious honor of
steering debate on the Elementary and Secondary Education Act,
currently stuck in legislative limbo. Coverdell knew Democrats
would probably block the GOP effort, but he worked late into the
night on it all the same.
</P>
<P>
   ''You have to come to understanding the legislative process or
it will drive you crazy,'' Coverdell said several weeks ago, after
the debate reached a standstill. ''The ultimate goal is making
things better, and the interim frustrations are just part of the
system. They've made me a more patient person.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-07-18-00 2130 </TRAILER>
