<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Pedestrian struck by falling debris from building  </HEADLINE>
By DEEPTI HAJELA
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) - A Pennsylvania man was badly injured Tuesday
when a part of a brick facade fell on top of him as he walked along
Seventh Avenue, near Madison Square Garden, police said.
</P>
<P>
   John Edward, 37, was taken to Bellevue Hospital where he was
listed in serious condition and was scheduled for surgery Tuesday
night, a hospital spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
   The debris fell from the roof of a 14-story office building at
423 Seventh Avenue, near 34th Street, at about 4:30 p.m., police
said. The area is heavily traveled by pedestrians and vehicles.
</P>
<P>
   Traffic along Seventh Avenue was blocked as police investigated
the accident's cause. It appeared that decorative material above a
14-story window had broken off and fallen, but police were still
interviewing witnesses to determine exactly what had struck the
victim.
</P>
<P>
   Edward, of Dressler, Penn., was in New York for a religious
convention taking place at Madison Square Garden.
</P>
<P>
   Zakia Davis was sitting in a restaurant at the building's lobby
level when she heard what ''sounded like a bomb was going off.''
</P>
<P>
   ''I saw this man on the ground lying in a pool of blood,'' she
said, adding that chunks of concrete were scattered around him. The
victim kept lapsing in and out of consciousness, and did not move
for a while, Davis added.
</P>
<P>
   Falling debris has injured or killed several pedestrians in the
city over the past two years. Last July, two women walking through
a Queens street fair were killed when the facade of a clothing
store collapsed on them.
</P>
<P>
   In March 1999, a 15-foot metal rod tumbled 22 stories from the
top of 1 Times Square, injuring three women.
</P>
<P>
   In August 1998, bricks from a Bear Stearns building in midtown
fell 39 stories onto Lexington Avenue, injuring one woman.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
