<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-18 21:46 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Inmate families take concerns to Rowland's hometown  </HEADLINE>
By DONNA TOMMELLEO
<TEXT>
<P>
   WATERBURY, Conn. (AP) - Until more prison space is available in
Connecticut, state prison officials plan to renew a contract with
Virginia to house hundreds of inmates in that state.
</P>
<P>
   ''We may only need to manage people for a year in Virginia, but
Connecticut hasn't offered us any options,'' state Department of
Correction spokeswoman Christina Polce said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Since October, the state has transferred about 480 prisoners to
Wallens Ridge Prison in Big Stone Gap, Va.. The move, officials
said, is needed because of cramped prisons, save the state money
and weed out troublesome prisoners.
</P>
<P>
   Polce said the state spends an average of $62 a day per prisoner
in Virginia compared with $71 a day in Connecticut.
</P>
<P>
   But families of those inmates say money should be no object when
it comes to human rights. A group of about 30 family and friends
gathered on the steps of the Waterbury Superior Courthouse early
Tuesday to protest the transfers, claiming the prisoners have been
abused and beaten by Virginia guards.
</P>
<P>
   Two Connecticut inmates have died at Wallens Ridge. The death of
David Tracy earlier this year that was ruled a suicide.
</P>
<P>
   Lawrence James Frazier, a diabetic inmate convicted of rape,
died on July 4 after struggling on June 29 with correctional
officers who repeatedly used a stun gun on the prisoner.
</P>
<P>
   Prison officials have said the stun gun was not a factor in
Frazier's death.
</P>
<P>
   One of the protesters, Randy Taylor, a Waterbury resident and
co-founder of an organization known as Friends and Families Who
Care, said they are not opposed to inmates serving their sentences.
</P>
<P>
   ''But they should not be abused by the system. The system is not
above the law,'' Taylor said.
</P>
<P>
   Taylor said his group corresponds with at least 60 inmates at
Wallens Ridge. He said families, relatives and friends are
frustrated with the lack of response from officials. The protesters
chose the courthouse in Gov. John G. Rowland's hometown to make
their case.
</P>
<P>
   ''Governor Rowland sent them there. The racist rednecks in
Virginia can't treat the inmates like human being and Governor
Rowland should bring them back,'' Taylor said.
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for the governor said Rowland maintains his support
for the transfers, especially if it removes the most violent
criminals out of state.
</P>
<P>
   ''That's in order to keep both the Connecticut prison population
safe as well as the correction employees,'' Chris Cooper said.
</P>
<P>
   Virginia authorities have denied any wrongdoing. Delegations
from Connecticut have traveled to Wallens Ridge to inspect the
prison and the treatment of inmates, and members of the state
Commission on Human Rights and Opportunities next month will
investigate allegations that guards have used excessive force and
racial slurs against Connecticut inmates.
</P>
<P>
   Polce said the agreement is automatically reinstated if the
state doesn't notify Virginia that it intends to terminate the
pact.
</P>
<P>
   ''Since we have chosen not to terminate the contract, it will
automatically rollover at the end of October,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   The state Department of Correction also is in the process of
trying to find more prison space in the state.
</P>
<P>
   A recent letter went out to every city and town asking local
officials to consider building a prison or expanding existing new
prisons. A informational meeting will be held at the department's
Cheshire training complex on Wednesday, July 26, she said.
</P>
<P>
   Members of Tracy's family were at the protest including his
father, Thomas Tracy, who said the relatives are frustrated by a
continued lack of information. Tracy insisted his son did not hang
himself.
</P>
<P>
   ''We put our trust in Henry Lee and he betrayed us,'' Tracy
said, referring to the state's top forensic expert, who observed
the autopsy and said Tracy died from a lack of blood to the brain -
an injury consistent with a hanging suicide.
</P>
<P>
   A state-sponsored bus trip last week took several relatives to
the Virginia prison to visit their loved ones. Karen Brown, whose
fiance is serving time for manslaughter, refused to go.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm not going on no bus trip. I'm not encouraging it or
influencing it because I want him to come back,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   ''I don't think he shouldn't be punished for what he did, but I
don't think he should be sent to Virginia just because the state
wants to save money,'' said Brown, of Waterbury. ''I mean you're in
jail and you lose a lot of rights, but you're still human.''
</P>
<P>
   She said they intend to marry when his sentence is up in two
years, ''If he's alive.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
