<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 10 p.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Tuesday, July 18, 2000
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Camp David Talks Continue
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   THURMONT, Md. (AP) -- President Clinton searched for Mideast peace settlement
terms today that would balance the diverse demands of Israeli Prime Minister
Ehud Barak and Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat. While Clinton was scheduled to
fly to Japan on Wednesday for a weekend summit with leaders of seven other
nations, he could delay his departure if the two sides moved closer to at least
partial settlement. ''There are intense discussions and negotiations going on
now between the two parties,'' White House spokesman Joe Lockhart said as
evening set in over the serene Catoctin Mountains.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Boy Arrested in School Shooting
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   SEATTLE (AP) -- A 13-year-old boy accused of climbing onto a cafeteria table
and firing a shot into the ceiling during a summer school session surrendered to
authorities today at his grandparents' house. No one was injured in yesterday's
shooting at nearby Dimmitt Middle School, but the boy remained at large after
the incident. Classes were canceled until Thursday although the school planned
to have counselors available tomorrow.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Fiji Swearing-In Postponed
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   SUVA, Fiji (AP) -- The swearing-in of Fiji's Cabinet was postponed Wednesday
after the island's new president became ill, delaying a process aimed at helping
Fiji recover from a paralyzing hostage crisis. The postponement came just one
day after the lineup for the panel was revealed, an announcement that drew
protest from George Speight, who threw Fiji into crisis in May when he led an
armed gang into Parliament and took dozens of hostages.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Georgia Senator Dies at Age 61
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   ATLANTA (AP) -- Sen. Paul Coverdell, a longtime Republican politician in
Georgia, died today of a stroke. He was 61. Coverdell had surgery yesterday to
relieve pressure from a cerebral hemorrhage but died from swelling in the brain,
Piedmont Hospital said. Coverdell, who served as Peace Corps director in the
Bush administration, was first elected to the Senate in 1992.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Caroline Kennedy to Address Party
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Caroline Kennedy, the only surviving member of the slain
president's immediate family, will address next month's Democratic National
Convention. Details, including when she will speak, have yet to be decided, said
Mark Fabiani, a spokesman for Vice President Al Gore. Fabiani also could not
indicate the topic of her remarks.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Heat Wave Continues in the South
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   MONTGOMERY, Ala. (AP) -- No relief was expected anytime soon from the heat
wave baking Alabama, Texas, Arizona, New Mexico, Arkansas, Louisiana, Oklahoma
and Kansas. The heat has been blamed for the deaths of two elderly Dallas
residents. In Louisiana, three deaths were being investigated as possibly heat
related. Two of the deaths were elderly residents of a hotel for homeless and
poor people that did not have air-conditioning.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Microsoft 4Q Profits Up 9 Percent
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   SEATTLE (AP) -- Fourth-quarter profits at Microsoft Corp. were up 9 percent
despite flat sales, helping the software giant beat Wall Street's expectations.
For the three months ended June 30, Microsoft made $2.409 billion, or 44 cents
per share, on sales of $5.80 billion. In the same period a year ago, Microsoft
made $2.202 billion, or 40 cents per share, on sales of $5.76 billion. Analysts
who follow Microsoft had estimated earnings of 42 cents per share, according to
First Call/Thomson Financial.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Consumer Prices Jump 0.6 Percent
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Soaring gasoline prices and a record jump in the cost of
natural gas were largely responsible for a sharp increase in consumer inflation
last month. Most other prices were tame. The split picture left economists
divided about whether the Federal Reserve will push interest rates higher next
month to keep inflation in check.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Tokyo Stocks Fall
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   TOKYO (AP) -- Tokyo stocks fell early Wednesday, dampened by declines on Wall
Street. The dollar was higher against the yen. The Nikkei Stock Average shed
210.64 points to 16,734.43 in early trading. On the stock market, the Nikkei
lost more ground amid uncertainty about the direction of the stock market,
traders said. In New York, the Dow Jones industrial average fell 64.35 points to
10,739.92 at Tuesday's close. The Nasdaq composite index lost 97.50 points to
4,177.17.
</P>
