<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-18 22:04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> AF Asks Judges Toss Out Gay Suit  </HEADLINE>
By CHRISTINE HANLEY
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO (AP) -- The Air Force has asked a federal judge to
throw out a lawsuit by a gay officer discharged under the
military's ''Don't Ask, Don't Tell'' policy, and renewed its demand
that he pay back more than $70,000 the Air Force spent to send him
to medical school.
</P>
<P>
   Air Force attorneys maintain that John Hensala deliberately
timed his announcement that he is gay to get out of his four-year
military commitment and insist he is obligated under Air Force code
to reimburse the government for his education.
</P>
<P>
   Hensala argued in his May 18 lawsuit that the Air Force could
not recoup the funds because he had indicated he wanted to fulfill
his four years of active duty after disclosing his homosexuality,
but he was denied the opportunity.
</P>
<P>
   Hensala said the Air Force noted in his discharge notice of
February 1997 that it could only collect educational expenses if he
had voluntarily failed to complete his service, had been found
guilty of misconduct or had made a homosexual statement or engaged
in homosexual conduct for purposes of triggering separation.
</P>
<P>
   But in a brief response filed Monday, the Air Force argued that
Hensala never expressed a desire to continue serving, disputed the
contents of the discharge notice and said Hensala waived his right
to a full hearing before a discharge board.
</P>
<P>
   The Air Force also argued that Hensala was relying on
reimbursement rules that don't apply to him, and he is not entitled
to a jury trial.
</P>
<P>
   Hensala said Tuesday he had not seen the response and would not
comment until he did. His attorney, Stephen Collier, was on
vacation.
</P>
<P>
   An Air Force spokesman and Justice Department attorney working
on the case did not return messages.
</P>
<P>
   The next hearing is scheduled for Sept. 11.
</P>
<P>
   Hensala, 35, lives and practices psychiatry in San Francisco.
His lawsuit is the first filed by an ousted gay service member to
fight reimbursing the government for education costs.
</P>
<P>
   Hensala earned a medical degree at Northwestern University under
the Armed Forces Health Professions Scholarship Program in 1986,
serving 20 weeks of active duty over four years in exchange for
tuition.
</P>
<P>
   The Air Force agreed to defer his active duty service during his
three-year residency at Yale, and then put it off again while he
took a two-year fellowship in child psychiatry at the University of
California at San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, in 1994, the Air Force told him that his four years of
active duty would have to begin the following year. Days later,
after he hired a lawyer, Hensala told his superiors that he is gay.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
