<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Obituaries in the News  </HEADLINE>
Paul Coverdell
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA (AP) -- Sen. Paul Coverdell, a longtime Republican
politician in Georgia who became a congressional workhorse and
quickly ascended to a leadership post, died Tuesday of a stroke. He
was 61.
</P>
<P>
   Coverdell, who served as Peace Corps director in the Bush
administration, was first elected to the Senate in 1992 by
defeating incumbent Democrat Wyche Fowler Jr.
</P>
<P>
   He became the fourth-leading Republican in the Senate, serving
as GOP Conference secretary and sitting on several committees,
including agriculture, finance and foreign relations.
</P>
<P>
   He also was the Senate liaison for George W. Bush's presidential
campaign and had been busy preparing for the Republican National
Convention, which begins in Philadelphia in two weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Coverdell's signature issue in the Senate the past four years
was education, specifically his proposal to expand higher education
savings accounts to allow tax-free withdrawals for school expenses
from kindergarten through high school.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton vetoed the measure in 1998, and forced
Republicans to pull it from a year-end budget bill in 1997 under
threat of a veto. The president maintained that the measure would
hurt public schools and benefit only wealthy families. Coverdell
had been pushing the legislation again this year.
</P>
<P>
   Coverdell also was one of Clinton's most outspoken critics in
the Senate, both on domestic and foreign policy issues.
</P>
<P>
William Russell Mote
</P>
<P>
   SARASOTA, Fla. (AP) -- William Russell Mote, who rescued a small
marine laboratory on Florida's Gulf Coast and turned it into a
major conservation and education institution, died Tuesday. He was
93.
</P>
<P>
   Mote founded the marine laboratory in 1965 when he came across
the small Cape Haze Marine Laboratory that was on the verge of
shutting down.
</P>
<P>
   Now Mote Marine is home to 30 researchers and draws more than
400,000 visitors a year to the lab and its aquarium. It includes
the National Center for Shark Research, an international effort to
understand and preserve the species.
</P>
<P>
   Its mission is marine conservation and protection of species,
but the laboratory often makes news for rescuing injured marine
animals and nursing them back to health.
</P>
<P>
   Mote was awarded the International Oceanographic Foundation's
Gold Medal Award which recognizes the layperson who does the most
to promote the study of the sea.
</P>
<P>
Aligi Sassu
</P>
<P>
   MADRID, Spain (AP) -- Italian painter, sculptor and engraver
Aligi Sassu, a pioneer of Italian contemporary art, died Monday
following a lengthy illness. He was 88.
</P>
<P>
   Sassu, who was most famous for his futurist painting, started in
the world of art as a teen-ager, exhibiting his work at a Milan
gallery in 1927.
</P>
<P>
   He was soon widely accepted in the futurist movement, which
emphasized the dynamism, speed and power of the machine. He also
wrote a movement manifesto called ''Dynamism and Muscular
Strength.''
</P>
<P>
   Sassu went to Paris in the 1930s where he studied Impressionist
masters, abandoning futurism and moving toward post-Impressionism.
</P>
<P>
   Among Sassu's most famous paintings are the 1931 ''Uomini
Rossi'' or ''Red Men,'' and the 1944 ''Martiri di Piazzale Loreto''
or ''Martyrs on Piazzale Loreto.''
</P>
<P>
Jose Angel Valente
</P>
<P>
   MADRID, Spain (AP) -- Spanish poet Jose Angel Valente, whose
mystical and metaphysical poetry won him dozens of literary awards,
died Tuesday of cancer. He was 71.
</P>
<P>
   Valente, a winner of Spain's prestigious Queen Sofia Poetry
Award, was 18 when he published his first poems in 1947.
</P>
<P>
   He also held positions with the Spanish government and the
United Nations, and was an assistant professor at the University of
California-Irvine, where he taught a course on the Spanish civil
war.
</P>
<P>
   He wrote poems in Spanish and in Galician, the language of the
coastal northwest region of Spain where he lived.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
