<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-18 22:09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Williams a No-Show at Cowboys Camp  </HEADLINE>
By JAIME ARON
<TEXT>
<P>
   WICHITA FALLS, Texas (AP) -- Pro Bowl right tackle Erik Williams
didn't show for the first day of practices at the Dallas Cowboys'
training camp.
</P>
<P>
   ''He's not here and he's not on his way,'' team owner Jerry
Jones said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Jones indicated Williams' absence was not a surprise to the team
and gave no details.
</P>
<P>
   ''I had a good visit with him last week and was aware of some
issues and concerns,'' Jones said. ''When we counted heads
yesterday, we thought he might be a late arrival. Then we started
visiting with his agent and realized he wouldn't be here.''
</P>
<P>
   His agent, Alan Herman, did not immediately return a message
left at his New York office by The Associated Press.
</P>
<P>
   Williams is due $1.85 million this season and next under a
six-year deal he signed after the 1995 season. By comparison,
Cincinnati recently signed right tackle Willie Anderson to a
six-year deal that averages $5.1 million, just higher than the
$5.08 million per year deal Philadelphia gave tackle Jon Runyan.
</P>
<P>
   If Williams isn't holding out for more money, it could be to
avoid some of the grind of training camp.
</P>
<P>
   ''Whether he is fined or how much, that's an internal matter,''
Jones said.
</P>
<P>
   Williams is coming off his third Pro Bowl selection in four
years and the fourth of his nine-year career.
</P>
<P>
   Dallas will replace him with second-year lineman Solomon Page,
who started one game in Williams' place last season and allowed no
sacks in 21 pass plays. He started six games in all as a rookie and
played in 14, working at both tackle and guard.
</P>
<P>
   ''He might be the best athlete of our group of offensive
linemen,'' coach Dave Campo said. ''I'm confident he'll be able to
step in and play.''
</P>
<P>
   With Page moving to the first team, Tony Hutson and Jorge Diaz
will see more playing time on the second team.
</P>
<P>
   Williams is missing a chance to become more familiar with
Dallas' new, motion-filled offense. His absence also is the first
roadblock Campo has faced in his six-month tenure.
</P>
<P>
   ''This is a business, people have to remember that,'' Campo
said. ''I look at it from the standpoint we'd like to see the whole
football team here and I think Erik Williams is part of the team.
</P>
<P>
   ''I don't look at it as a crisis at this point. You may talk to
me two weeks from now and I may look at it as more of a crisis.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
