<BODY>
<HEADLINE> NFL Camps Roundup  </HEADLINE>
By The Associated Press	   Eddie George became one of the highest-paid running
backs in the
NFL on Tuesday, when the Tennessee Titans announced a $41.25
million six-year contract extension.
<TEXT>
<P>
   The deal gives George the option to play a seventh year, for an
extra $4 million. It also includes a $10 million bonus.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's not often a professional athlete stays with one
organization his whole career, and I have an opportunity to do
that,'' George said. ''I'm glad we could get it done. It's a big
weight off my shoulders.''
</P>
<P>
   Last year the Indianapolis Colts signed rookie Edgerrin James to
a seven-year, $49 million contract, while the St. Louis Rams signed
Marshall Faulk to a seven-year, $45 million deal.
</P>
<P>
   George, who turns 27 in September, has not missed a game in four
seasons and has 25 100-yard rushing games. The Titans are 20-5 when
he rushes for 100 yards, and George had a career-high 1,762
combined yards and a career-best 13 touchdowns last season as the
franchise reached its first Super Bowl in 40 years.
</P>
<P>
   ''The only thing that changes is my bank account,'' he said.
''I'll continue to challenge myself and my teammates to have a
better season than we had last year. ... I'll take it a season at a
time and hopefully at the end I'll have seven rings.''
</P>
<P>
   Rookie Chris Samuels is also a multimillionaire, signing a deal
worth anywhere from $31 million to $55 million with the Washington
Redskins.
</P>
<P>
   Samuels, on offensive tackle from Alabama chosen third overall
in the NFL draft, got his first taste of NFL practice later
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Unheralded rookie defensive tackle Jerry DeLoach put Samuels on
the ground twice, the second time with a takedown.
</P>
<P>
   ''I got whipped early,'' said Samuels, who didn't allow a sack
his junior or senior year. ''I hadn't hit since the SEC
championship. He won that battle then, but I got better as the day
went.''
</P>
<P>
   Although veteran Andy Heck is listed first on the depth chart at
left tackle, Samuels is expected to start right away.
</P>
<P>
   ''We didn't draft the guy with the third pick in the draft as a
backup,'' offensive line coach Russ Grimm said. ''He's a big strong
guy that's got quick feet. Most tackles, especially left tackles,
are more your finesse guys. They've got real good feet, but they're
not powerful run blockers. This guy has a chance to excel in
both.''
</P>
<P>
   With No. 2 overall pick LaVar Arrington close to signing an even
wealthier deal and Pro Bowl running back Stephen Davis also
unsigned, the Redskins will have the most expensive NFL roster in
history. They have already paid about $35 million in signing
bonuses this year, a figure likely to exceed $50 million once
Arrington and Davis are signed.
</P>
<P>
   A gap of about $500,000 between Tennessee and NFL career sack
leader Reggie White is too wide to coax the defensive end out of
retirement, according to coach Jeff Fisher.
</P>
<P>
   ''There's a lot of work to be done and the biggest hurdle is to
at least get into the same range of numbers that would work for
both sides,'' Fisher said in a story in The Tennessean on Tuesday.
''The sooner the better, out of fairness for both sides.''
</P>
<P>
   The Titans won't bring the former Green Bay and Philadelphia
star in for a physical and discussions about his potential role
with the team until the numbers are closer on what is believed to
be an incentive-laden, one-year deal.
Cowboys:
</P>
<P>
   Four-time Pro Bowl selection Erik Williams was a no-show for the
first day of Dallas' training camp, and team owner Jerry Jones said
the absence was not a surprise to the team and gave no details.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm disappointed he's not here,'' Jones said. ''What his
status is and where we go have to evolve. It is an internal matter.
I thought he would be a late arrival, and I talked to his agent and
realized he wasn't coming.''
</P>
<P>
   Jones said the team will treat the absence as if Williams, a
tackle, was injured and make temporary lineup adjustments. He said
Williams could be subject to a fine.
Rams:
</P>
<P>
   Al Saunders was promoted to associate head coach and Bobby
Jackson to offensive coordinator Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Saunders, 53, joined St. Louis in 1999 as wide receivers coach.
He was head coach of the San Diego Chargers from 1986-88, and
assistant head coach and receivers coach for the Kansas City Chiefs
from 1989-98. He will continue as wide receivers coach.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson, 60, joined St. Louis in February as running backs coach
after five seasons with the Washington Redskins.
Giants:
</P>
<P>
   Cornerback Conrad Hamilton was waived by the Giants after
failing a team physical.
</P>
<P>
   Hamilton made just three appearances last season, including two
starts, after injuring his knee and ankle in the team's first
intrasquad scrimmage.
</P>
<P>
   He started at cornerback in 1998, after Jason Sehorn's
season-ending knee injury. Hamilton had a career-high 91 tackles,
17 passes defended and one interception.
</P>
<P>
   Hamilton originally joined the Giants as a seventh-round draft
choice from Eastern New Mexico in 1996.
Eagles:
</P>
<P>
   John Frank, Philadelphia's sixth-round draft pick, retired from
football even before his NFL career started.
</P>
<P>
   Frank, a defensive end from Utah, reported to the Eagles for a
team meeting Saturday -- but never reported for practice.
</P>
<P>
   ''It was personal reasons. It was a situation where he intended
to come,'' director of football operations Tom Modrak said. ''He
had gone through some of the minicamps and at the last minute he
changed his mind. It caught us all off guard. It was probably a
very difficult decision for him.''
</P>
<P>
   Frank forfeits a signing bonus of about $63,000.
</P>
<P>
   Frank had a school-record 27 sacks at Utah, and was the 1999
Mountain West Conference defensive player of the year.
Browns:
</P>
<P>
   Running back Terry Kirby will miss 7-10 days of practice with
two small fractures in his left eye socket.
</P>
<P>
   Kirby was hurt Sunday during a blocking drill. At first the
injury was thought to be just a bruise.
</P>
<P>
   Kirby started the first nine games in 1999 and was the Browns'
leading rusher with 452 yards and six touchdowns. Errict Rhett, who
signed with the Browns as an unrestricted free agent, is the
expected starter at running back.
</P>
<P>
   ''I already know the offense,'' Kirby said. ''Hopefully, I'll be
out only about seven days. I'll be ready for the preseason
opener.''
</P>
<P>
   The Browns open July 30 against the Philadelphia Eagles.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
