<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-18 22:19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Activists oppose Millstone plan to expand fuel rod storage  </HEADLINE>
dcdsnldrhjc
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW LONDON, Conn. (AP) - A proposal to expand storage of spent
fuel rods at the Millstone Three nuclear power plant drew sharp
criticism at a hearing Tuesday night from activists and area
residents, who said they were concerned about a potential meltdown
or other accident.
</P>
<P>
   About 65 people from Connecticut and Long Island, including
model Christie Brinkley, attended a hearing before the Atomic
Safety and Licensing Board. No decisions were made. A formal
hearing before the board was scheduled for Wednesday, continuing
Thursday if necessary.
</P>
<P>
   With no solution in sight to the need for a nuclear fuel dump,
Northeast Utilities, which operates Millstone Three, is asking
federal regulators to increase the capacity of the plants' fuel rod
pool.
</P>
<P>
   NU officials want to store up to 1,860 spent fuel rod assemblies
at the plant's pool, which currently is approved to store 750 such
assemblies. NU spokesman Joe Pillittere said the pool was built to
store up to 2,000 assemblies, and he said the proposal was studied
thoroughly and deemed to be safe.
</P>
<P>
   Brinkley, the former Sports Illustrated swimsuit model and a
Long Island resident, said she was worried about the safety of her
children and other area residents.
</P>
<P>
   ''I do not qualify as a scientist, a politician or a lobbyist,''
Brinkley said. ''But I do qualify as a mom. I have three happy,
healthy children, and their health and the health of all of us is
being jeopardized by this issue.''
</P>
<P>
   Gordon Thompson, executive director of the Institute for
Resource and Security Studies in Cambridge, Mass., said the
expansion possibly could lead to a nuclear meltdown.
</P>
<P>
   ''The plume of radioactivity would be substantially great than
Chernobyl,'' Thompson said, referring to the massive nuclear plant
accident in the former Soviet Union.
</P>
<P>
   Thompson also said there was the chance of a fire occurring in
the spent fuel rod pool.
</P>
<P>
   The system looks like a 40-foot-deep, L-shaped swimming pool.
The fuel rods are stored in bundles called assemblies, which are
held on racks submerged at the bottom of the pool.
</P>
<P>
   Water laced with boron is circulated around the pool to keep the
fuel cool and prevent a nuclear reaction.
</P>
<P>
   The issue has attracted attention on both sides of Long Island
Sound near the Waterford nuclear complex. Anti-Millstone groups
from Connecticut and New York have been given permission to
participate in the hearing.
</P>
<P>
   Pillittere said the storage plan is safe and has been analyzed
from many angles as required by the Nuclear Regulatory Commission.
</P>
<P>
   ''To put this in terms a homeowner would understand, we're not
talking about adding a new room to our house. We're just finishing
the basement,'' Pillittere said.
</P>
<P>
   Nuclear plant operators need to store spent fuel on site because
the federal government has not yet come up with a permanent storage
place.
</P>
<P>
   Some anti-nuclear activists believe it would be safer to store
the fuel in secure concrete vaults, since the water storage system
could fail if pumps broke or water leaks out.
</P>
<P>
   Others oppose any expansion of the fuel storage capacity at all,
hoping that the plant will have to shut down if there is no place
to store the waste.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-07-18-00 2219 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
