<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-18 22:23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Leaked Memo Plagues Blair Party  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON (AP) -- The image of Prime Minister Tony Blair's Labor
Party is ''badly contaminated,'' according to a memo from a close
adviser published by newspapers Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The leaked memo, written by public opinion guru Philip Gould,
comes two days after newspapers printed a similar private memo from
Blair himself, warning that the government was perceived as ''out
of touch.''
</P>
<P>
   In the latest memo, written in early May, Gould warned that
''the New Labor brand has been badly contaminated.''
</P>
<P>
   ''It is the object of constant criticism, and even worse,
ridicule,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Like Blair, Gould feared that the government was out of step
with public opinion on issues such as health care and crime.
</P>
<P>
   ''How many ministers genuinely want to be tough on crime?'' he
asked.
</P>
<P>
   In his leaked memo, Blair warned that Labor appeared to be ''out
of touch with gut British instincts'' on issues such as law and
order, asylum, dissent and the family and called for ''eye-catching
initiatives'' to help the government regain momentum.
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for the prime minister's Downing Street office
dismissed the latest leak as an opposition ploy to draw attention
away from the $64 billion spending package unveiled by Chancellor
of the Exchequer Gordon Brown on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, Downing Street confirmed that Cabinet Secretary
Richard Wilson was overseeing an inquiry into the leaked Blair
memo.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
