<HEADLINE> Labor Party Unveils Spending Plan  </HEADLINE>
By MARA D. BELLA
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON (AP) -- The government unveiled its three-year spending
proposals Tuesday, promising a $64 billion cash injection for
hard-pressed public services -- notably education, health and
transportation -- if voters give the Labor Party a second term.
</P>
<P>
   Chancellor of the Exchequer Gordon Brown also promised to hike
defense spending to $37 billion a year by 2004 -- the first
real-term increase since 1985.
</P>
<P>
   The boost in public services spending was viewed as a bid to
shore up support for Prime Minister Tony Blair's Labor Party ahead
of the next general election -- likely to be held next year.
</P>
<P>
   Opposition politicians contended the government was embarking on
a risky spending binge that would ultimately lead to higher taxes,
and also accused Labor of starving public services during its first
three years in power to allow for a massive pre-election spending
increase.
</P>
<P>
   ''This government has been prudent for a purpose,'' Brown told
lawmakers in the House of Commons.
</P>
<P>
   Brown said lower welfare costs, a $30.4 billion budget surplus,
dropping debt and other savings allowed him to finally provide the
multibillion-dollar boost to public services.
</P>
<P>
   The package, which would take the government through 2004, comes
at a critical time for Blair's government, which has been plagued
in recent weeks by public relations gaffes and falling poll
results. The government must call an election by the spring 2002.
</P>
<P>
   Brown defended the increases, but the Conservative Party warned
that allowing spending to grow above the actual growth rate of the
economy was not sustainable.
</P>
<P>
   ''He has a surplus today. He now proposes to spend that and take
us back into deficit, and that's why the future under Labor must be
more tax rises again,'' said Michael Portillo, the Tories' treasury
spokesman.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
