<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-18 22:34 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Garciaparra: .400 Just a Number  </HEADLINE>
By JIMMY GOLEN
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON (AP) -- Nomar Garciaparra has the same attitude about
batting .400 that he had about the rookie of the year award, the
batting title and every other accomplishment on his baseball
resume.
</P>
<P>
   He ignores it, and he hopes everyone else does, too.
</P>
<P>
   ''I won't listen,'' the Red Sox shortstop said Tuesday when
asked about the attention that will inevitably surround him as he
chases Ted Williams, whose .406 average in 1941 was the last to top
.400. ''I'm more about playing. I'm concerned about making the
postseason more than anything. The other stuff I don't know
anything about.''
</P>
<P>
   Garciaparra brought a .400 average into Tuesday night's game
against the Montreal Expos before going 1-for-3 and see his average
drop to .399. Larry Walker, who was hitting .402 on July 18, 1997,
was the last player over .400 this late in the season.
</P>
<P>
   But Walker -- like John Olerud and Tony Gwynn and George Brett
and everyone else who has flirted with .400 since 1941 -- didn't
last, finishing at .366. Gwynn of the San Diego Padres finished
with a .394 average in the strike-shortened 1994 season -- the
highest since Williams' .406.
</P>
<P>
   ''(Hitting) .400 is a six-month deal. It's not five, it's not
five-and-a-half, it's six months. You've got to be able to do it
for six months, and no one's done it since Ted Williams,'' Gwynn
said. ''George Brett gave it a run, Rod Carew gave it a run, I
guess I gave it a halfhearted run, but the bottom line is it's a
six-month deal.''
</P>
<P>
   Gwynn, who's been watching Garciaparra on television while
recovering from knee surgery, said he is hoping someone does break
the .400 barrier -- even if it isn't him. In this age of home runs,
he wouldn't mind a little attention for the contact hitters.
</P>
<P>
   ''Wouldn't that be something? Everybody's talking about home
runs so much and then at the end of the year everybody (would be)
talking about hitting .400 and getting 258 hits?'' Gwynn said,
noting that Anaheim's Darin Erstad was batting .385, and his 155
hits puts him on a pace to break George Sisler's 80-year-old record
of 257.
</P>
<P>
   ''They're doing the grunt work in major league baseball. It
would be remarkable for me to see the hit record broken and
somebody hit .400 in a year where people just figure somebody was
going to hit 70, 80 home runs,'' Gwynn said.
</P>
<P>
   ''If home run records can fall, it could be that time where
somebody hits .400, or somebody breaks the hit record. And who
knows what else is out there?''
</P>
<P>
   Certainly not Garciaparra, who has done his best to ignore every
statistical furor he has ignited.
</P>
<P>
   ''I remember when he had that hitting streak. He didn't want to
talk about it,'' Red Sox catcher Scott Hatteberg said. ''It's just
a theory of not getting too wrapped up in the moment. He's also a
superstitious guy. I don't know if that has anything to do with it.
</P>
<P>
   ''If anyone's got a chance, it's him. But it's a long way off to
be talking about .400.''
</P>
<P>
   Garciaparra already has a slew of accomplishments in 3&AMP;frac12; years,
including the 1997 AL rookie of the year award, a rookie-record
30-game hitting streak and a league-leading .357 batting average
last season.
</P>
<P>
   But he doesn't covet individual awards, and he doesn't celebrate
them afterward, either.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's not that I don't enjoy it,'' he said. ''I just don't look
back.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-07-18-00 2234 </TRAILER>
