<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 11 p.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Tuesday, July 18, 2000
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
'Marriage Penalty' Eliminated by Senate
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Despite a veto threat from President Clinton and
Democratic criticism, Republicans won Senate passage today of a bill that would
eliminate the ''marriage penalty'' by cutting taxes for virtually all married
couples. The bill would cut taxes for approximately 45 million couples,
including about 25 million two-earner households in which couples pay more than
they would if single. The legislation, approved on a 61-38 vote, would reduce
government revenue by $248 billion over 10 years.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Quest for Mideast Peace Continues
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   THURMONT, Md. (AP) -- With tense Mideast peace talks at a crossroads,
President Clinton searched Tuesday for settlement terms that balance the diverse
demands of Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak and Palestinian leader Yasser
Arafat. As the clock ticked down to his scheduled departure for Japan on
Wednesday morning, Clinton had dinner on a patio of his cabin at Camp David,
Md., and met with his advisers. ''We will work the night'' through, said White
House spokesman P.J. Crowley.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Alleged Teen Gunman Surrenders
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   SEATTLE (AP) -- A 13-year-old boy accused of climbing onto a cafeteria table
and firing a shot into the ceiling during a summer school session surrendered to
authorities today at his grandparents' house. No one was injured in yesterday's
shooting at nearby Dimmitt Middle School, but the boy remained at large after
the incident. Classes were canceled until Thursday although the school planned
to have counselors available tomorrow.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Georgia Senator Dies at Age 61
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   ATLANTA (AP) -- Sen. Paul Coverdell, a longtime Republican politician in
Georgia, died today of a stroke. He was 61. Coverdell had surgery yesterday to
relieve pressure from a cerebral hemorrhage but died from swelling in the brain,
Piedmont Hospital said. Coverdell, who served as Peace Corps director in the
Bush administration, was first elected to the Senate in 1992.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
World Bank To Resume Aid to Kenya
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   NAIROBI, Kenya (AP) -- The World Bank will resume aid to Kenya after a
three-year suspension with a $150 million loan to reduce poverty and help
achieve reforms, a bank official said Tuesday. Kenya, which is suffering its
worst economic crisis since independence from Britain in 1963, with severe
drought and nationwide power and water shortages, depends on multilateral
lending institutions and grants from donors for development programs.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Heat Wave Shows No Signs of Lifting
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   MONTGOMERY, Ala. (AP) -- No relief was expected anytime soon from the heat
wave baking Alabama, Texas, Arizona, New Mexico, Arkansas, Louisiana, Oklahoma
and Kansas. The heat has been blamed for the deaths of two elderly Dallas
residents. In Louisiana, three deaths were being investigated as possibly heat
related. Two of the deaths were elderly residents of a hotel for homeless and
poor people that did not have air-conditioning.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Microsoft 4Q Profits Rise
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   SEATTLE (AP) -- Fourth-quarter profits at Microsoft Corp. were up 9 percent
despite flat sales, helping the software giant beat Wall Street's expectations.
For the three months ended June 30, Microsoft made $2.409 billion, or 44 cents
per share, on sales of $5.80 billion. In the same period a year ago, Microsoft
made $2.202 billion, or 40 cents per share, on sales of $5.76 billion. Analysts
who follow Microsoft had estimated earnings of 42 cents per share, according to
First Call/Thomson Financial.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Tokyo Stocks Fall
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   TOKYO (AP) -- Tokyo stocks fell early Wednesday, dampened by declines on Wall
Street. The dollar was higher against the yen. The Nikkei Stock Average shed
210.64 points to 16,734.43 in early trading. In New York, the Dow Jones
industrial average fell 64.35 points to 10,739.92 at Tuesday's close. The Nasdaq
composite index lost 97.50 points to 4,177.17.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Dan O'Brien To Leave Olympic Trials
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   SACRAMENTO, Calif. (AP) -- Dan O'Brien, the defending Olympic champion in the
decathlon and one of track and field's biggest names over the last decade, said
today he plans to withdraw from the U.S. trials and will miss the Sydney Games.
O'Brien, 34, said he partially tore the plantar fascia, connective tissue on the
bottom of his left foot, while practicing the high jump last Wednesday. He said
he had done everything he could to try to compete in spite of the injury. But
O'Brien said he wouldn't formally withdraw until just before the competition
begins.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Red Sox Beat Expos 3-1
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   BOSTON (AP) -- Pedro Martinez struck out 12 to earn his first victory since
June 8 and Darren Lewis broke a seventh-inning tie with a suicide squeeze
Tuesday night to give the Boston Red Sox a 3-1 victory over the Montreal Expos.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
AP NewsBrief by LISI de BOURBON
</SUBHEAD>
