<HEADLINE> Family Says Rightists Killed Lucio  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOGOTA, Colombia (AP) -- Right-wing militias executed a former
leftist guerrilla and senator, family and associates said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Officials had no immediate information about the apparent
slaying of Carlos Alonso Lucio, a one-time member of the M-19 rebel
group.
</P>
<P>
   But Lucio's father, Alonso Lucio, said he had received word from
rightist militias that they killed his son and a close political
associate, Jaime Moreno, in the northern mountains of Colombia on
Monday.
</P>
<P>
   ''All our sources indicate that he was assassinated,'' Alonso
Lucio said in an interview with RCN television.
</P>
<P>
   Carlos Alonso Lucio, 35, returned to Colombia earlier this year
from Cuba, where he fled to escape Supreme Court charges of making
false statements in a case involving a questionable bank loan he
received.
</P>
<P>
   Harold Padilla, a spokesman of the small political movement
Lucio and Moreno headed, claimed they were killed for their role in
promoting peace talks between the government and Colombia's
second-largest rebel group.
</P>
<P>
   The leftist National Liberation Army, or ELN, is engaged in
preliminary peace negotiations with President Andres Pastrana over
the bitter objection of rival rightist militias, headed by national
paramilitary boss Carlos Castano.
</P>
<P>
   Leaders of Colombia's two main political parties denounced
Lucio's apparent murder on Tuesday, and praised his peace efforts.
</P>
</TEXT>
