<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Gore Suggests Bush Will Up Interest  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. (AP) -- Al Gore suggested Tuesday that rival
George W. Bush's proposed tax cuts and other fiscal plans would
overheat the economy and push interest rates up. Already, Gore said
of the economy, ''We're pushing the envelope.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore, the Democratic presidential candidate, told contributors
to the Democratic National Committee Tuesday night that Bush and
his fellow Republicans justify what Gore called ''this huuu-uge tax
scheme'' by saying it will ''stimulate higher levels of economic
growth.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore then gave his $5,000-per-plate dinner party of just 25
people a lesson in Economics 101:
</P>
<P>
   ''You know, the economy is growing pretty fast right now. And,
one of the problems that people talk about when they look at the
economy isn't the need for higher levels of economic growth. That's
not what I hear. That's always great; in fact, we're pushing the
envelope and, with the so-called new economy, we're now getting
higher levels of economic growth without the inflation that has
come with them in the past. But the problem people worry about and
that the stock market types are focused on is, will the growth get
too high and cause a ripple in the market that results in monetary
policy being clamped down and interest rates going up.''
</P>
<P>
   A few minutes deeper into his speech, an older man across the
table from Gore called out too loudly: ''Mr. vice president, we're
with you all the way.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore took the cue and abruptly sat down to laughter. ''I rest my
case. I made a sale. Let's eat.''
</P>
</TEXT>
