<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-18 23:19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Pope Urges Angola's Foes Find Peace  </HEADLINE>
By CASIMIRO SIONA
<TEXT>
<P>
   LUANDA, Angola (AP) -- Pope John Paul II on Tuesday urged
Angola's warring parties to find a peaceful solution to the
conflict that has displaced millions of people over the past two
decades.
</P>
<P>
   ''I ask that the parties involved take bold and courageous
decisions so that once violence is defeated and the gap of hatred
and division is bridged, the Angolan people may finally know a
peaceful living,'' the pope said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
   His appeal for reconciliation was read by the Vatican's
representative in Angola, Aldo Cavalli, as the Congress for Peace --
a three-day conference aimed at persuading the government and UNITA
rebels to return to the negotiating table -- got under way in the
Angolan capital.
</P>
<P>
   The government and UNITA, a Portuguese acronym for the National
Union for the Total Independence of Angola, began fighting after
Angola gained independence from Portugal in 1975. Three peace
accords have since collapsed.
</P>
<P>
   Angolan church leaders, senior government officials and
opposition politicians, grassroots movements and international
observers were attending the conference.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the pope's plea, old feelings of mutual mistrust were as
present as ever.
</P>
<P>
   State-run media reported Tuesday that the government had
intercepted a message from UNITA hard-liner Paulo Lukamba Gato
saying the timing was not right for peace talks.
</P>
<P>
   But in a communique released Tuesday in Lisbon, UNITA reportedly
said it was ready ''to heed the nation's appeal for peace as soon
as (President) Jose Eduardo dos Santos is willing to.''
</P>
<P>
   As the conference began, some 200 European figures ranging from
politicians to journalists urged Angola's warring parties to
negotiate and the United Nations to lift sanctions imposed against
UNITA in a bid to cripple its ability to make war. They said both
sides failed to make peace.
</P>
<P>
   Dos Santos' government and Jonas Savimbi's UNITA rebels resumed
their two-decade-long war a year and a half ago when a 1994
U.N.-brokered peace accord unraveled.
</P>
<P>
   The call for dialogue is not new. Angola's religious leaders
recently have led an intensive campaign for peace and offered to
mediate talks between the two sides.
</P>
<P>
   But there is no end in sight. After the government launched a
sweeping offensive late last year, the two sides have been engaged
in low-intensity fighting.
</P>
<P>
   The government has financed its war effort with lucrative oil
exploration deals with foreign companies, some of which include
multimillion-dollar signing bonuses destined for the ruling elite's
pockets, human rights groups allege.
</P>
<P>
   Although an international ban on UNITA's diamond trade has
diminished the rebels' ability to wage war, the guerrillas continue
to receive fuel and arms shipments and are still able to disrupt
the vast country with hit-and-run attacks.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, an estimated 1 million people -- about a tenth of the
population -- rely on international aid. Food deliveries have been
hampered by road ambushes and fresh land mines planted by both
sides.
</P>
<P>
   The civil war has uprooted about 3.8 million people -- or
one-third of the southwest African country's population -- according
to state estimates. Many of them were living in makeshift camps,
and almost were relying on aid to survive.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
