<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-18 23:25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Heat Wave Continues in the South  </HEADLINE>
by 
V0971-----
u a *1110AP-Heat-Wave     07-18 0329
*1110 AP-Heat-Wave,0329   
Heat Wave Continues in the South
AP Photos
By DAVE BRYAN
<TEXT>
<P>
   MONTGOMERY, Ala. (AP) -- Tiya Jones endured another day of
100-degree temperatures Tuesday in a ground-floor apartment with no
air conditioning, caught in a regional heat wave that has been
blamed for more than 10 deaths.
</P>
<P>
   ''The fan don't really do much, just one little fan,'' Jones,
17, said as her 10-year-old brother played with two friends beneath
the shade of a large oak tree outside. ''Everybody been sweating
around here.''
</P>
<P>
   Jones and her brother aren't alone.
</P>
<P>
   No relief was expected anytime soon from the deadly heat wave
also baking Texas, Arizona, New Mexico, Arkansas, Louisiana,
Oklahoma and Kansas.
</P>
<P>
   The heat has been blamed for the deaths of 12 Texas residents.
In Louisiana, three deaths were being investigated as possibly heat
related. Two of the deaths were elderly residents of a hotel for
homeless and poor people that did not have air-conditioning.
</P>
<P>
   Hotspots in Alabama were Tuscaloosa and Evergreen, where the
temperature reached 101 degrees. The mercury edged past 100 in
Tuscaloosa at about 5 p.m. making it a record 14th straight day
that the temperature in the west Alabama town had broken the
century mark.
</P>
<P>
   Temperatures of 100 degrees were reported in Montgomery and
Dothan.
</P>
<P>
   Temperatures climbed past 100 for the seventh day in a row
Tuesday in north Texas, while readings elsewhere peaked into the
upper 90s.
</P>
<P>
   The high temperature in Louisiana was in the northern community
of Monroe, which peaked at 101. It was 97 in New Orleans.
</P>
<P>
   The hot weather and little rain added to concerns about
dwindling water resources and damage to Alabama's farmers.
</P>
<P>
   All 67 Alabama counties have been declared federal disaster
areas by Agriculture Secretary Dan Glickman.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-07-18-00 2325 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000718.0215 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-18 23:30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Black Leaders To Rally Beating  </HEADLINE>
By TINA MOORE
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA (AP) -- Black religious leaders said Tuesday they
can no longer ask their congregations to remain calm about the
police beating of a black suspect that was caught on videotape last
week by a TV news helicopter.
</P>
<P>
   The Rev. Vernal Simms, pastor of Morris Brown AME Church, said
it was time to ''mobilize'' and scheduled a rally Sunday evening at
his church -- which sits a few blocks from where officers kicked and
hit suspected carjacker Thomas Jones.
</P>
<P>
   ''We came out asking the community to be calm,'' Simms said.
''But how long, how long can we tell black folk to be quiet and
take it easy?''
</P>
<P>
   Simms, president of Black Clergy of Philadelphia, said the rally
was being sponsored his group and the Nation of Islam.
Majority-white churches, including the Archdiocese of Philadelphia,
were also being invited.
</P>
<P>
   Simms' church holds about 1,000 people, and if more than that
attend, religious leaders said, demonstrators will move into the
street.
</P>
<P>
   ''There may be more than that because the community really is
outraged,'' said the Rev. Joseph Patterson of Hickman Temple AME
Church. ''Not because they apprehended him, but for the atrocious
way they did it. I watched it on television again, and there were
officers running around trying to find a spot to beat him.''
</P>
<P>
   A television news camera captured white and black officers
kicking and hitting Jones last Wednesday, after a chase and
shootout in which he and an officer were both shot and wounded.
</P>
<P>
   Jones, 30, still hospitalized in good condition Tuesday, is
charged with the attempted murder of a police officer, assault,
resisting arrest and other offenses. He was also charged with three
purse-snatchings and is a suspect in other crimes, police said.
</P>
<P>
   No charges have been filed against the police in the beating,
and clergy members have been critical of District Attorney Lynne
Abraham.
</P>
<P>
   ''The district attorney always seems to find a way for them to
go free,'' Simms said.
</P>
<P>
   Cathie Abookire, a spokeswoman for Abraham, said the district
attorney would not comment on Simms' remarks.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday night, top police officials faced outrage at a
community meeting.
</P>
<P>
   Police Commissioner John F. Timoney and other top officials were
joined by politicians and community leaders who struggled to calm
emotions among the overflow crowd of about 200 people at Christ Our
Redeemer Freewill Baptist Church.
</P>
<P>
   ''Police officers are allowed to use force. The issue is ... did
they use unnecessary force, did they cross the line? You cannot
tell on the basis of that tape because you don't know what's going
on underneath,'' said Timoney, who was drowned out by shouts and
jeers.
</P>
<P>
   Also Tuesday, The Philadelphia Inquirer reported that a
satirical T-shirt depicting a scene from the incident was being
sold by police officers. The T-shirt reads ''Welcome America,'' a
Philadelphia tourism slogan.
</P>
<P>
   Timoney said he was outraged and threatened to fire any officers
involved.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
