<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-18 23:34 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Council Approves Lambeau Agreement  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   GREEN BAY, Wis. (AP) -- A proposed agreement on how to market
naming rights for Lambeau Field was passed by the City Council on
Tuesday night, clearing the way for scheduling a referendum on a
sales tax to help pay for renovating the Green Bay Packers'
stadium.
</P>
<P>
   Mayor Paul Jadin said the revised agreement was approved 8-4
after about two hours of debate Tuesday night.
</P>
<P>
   The council needed to approve a naming rights deal by July 28
for a stadium commission to set a Sept. 12 referendum on a proposed
half-percent sales tax in Brown County to raise $160 million for
the $295 million renovation and expansion project.
</P>
<P>
   ''I feel good that we were able to move this forward,'' Jadin
said, adding however that there still was a ''lot of ill will'' in
the community over the project.
</P>
<P>
   Opponents will do almost anything to try to block it, while
those on the other side are just as determined to see it
accomplished, Jadin said.
</P>
<P>
   The Packers, who proposed the project early this year, have
described the improvements to the 43-year-old stadium as critical
to keep the team financially competitive in the National Football
League.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to adding 10,000 seats, the proposal would add a
five-story, mall-like atrium to make the stadium more of a
year-round tourist attraction.
</P>
<P>
   The Packers hope to begin work next January and complete the
improvements in time for the 2003 season.
</P>
<P>
   The City Council a week earlier had deferred any action on the
naming rights agreement, which requires that the city and the
Packers equally split the proceeds.
</P>
<P>
   The latest version had revised language to allow seeking
proposals for a $120 million naming rights deal as early as 2002,
rather than 2003 as specified in the original proposal worked out
between the city and the Packers.
</P>
<P>
   The new agreement also allows the council to consult with
experts on the best time to market naming rights -- which a company
can buy to have its name used on a property.
</P>
<P>
   It also includes language saying the council should ask the
County Board to call a referendum on whether to sell naming rights.
</P>
<P>
   A naming rights referendum is to be followed by a council vote
to solicit proposals from companies interested in buying the
stadium's name.
</P>
<P>
   The rights could then go to the highest bidder, as long as the
company offers at least $120 million. If no company bids that
amount, the council could seek new proposals and accept the highest
bid of at least $100 million. If that amount is not reached, the
city and the Packers would determine whether to accept the best
offer.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
