<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bush, Gore Pay Tribute to Coverdell  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- George W. Bush and Al Gore separately paid
tribute Tuesday to the late Sen. Paul Coverdell, who died of a
stroke soon after suffering a cerebral hemorrhage.
</P>
<P>
   Coverdell, 61, was a close family friend and Senate liaison to
Bush, the likely Republican nominee and governor of Texas. And he
was a colleague to Democrat Gore, who as vice president serves as
president of the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   At the beginning of a speech to a $3 million party fund-raiser
in Chicago, Bush announced Coverdell has passed away, drawing an
audible gasp from a crowd of Republicans. He asked them to observe
a moment of silence for ''my great friend and friend of America.''
</P>
<P>
   After the observance, Bush said: ''May God bless him and his
family.''
</P>
<P>
   Coverdell served as Peace Corps director in the Bush
administration and had worked in the presidential campaigns of the
candidate's father.
</P>
<P>
   ''Paul's death is a huge loss to his family, his friends, his
constituents in Georgia and our country,'' Bush said in a statement
released earlier through his campaign office. ''Paul was a great
friend to Laura and me and we shared family and political ties for
more than 20 years.
</P>
<P>
   ''He listened to the people of Georgia and he was a leader for
them, at home and in Washington. Paul's soft-spoken, hard-working
ways will be sorely missed by all of us who knew him and loved him.
Our prayers are with Nancy and his family and the people of Georgia
tonight.''
</P>
<P>
   At a campaign stop in Kansas City, Gore cited his constitutional
role as president of the Senate as he opened the campaign rally
with a moment of silence for Coverdell.
</P>
<P>
   ''This is a partisan gathering, but we are all Americans,'' Gore
said, ''and when something like this happens we join together in
thinking of the family and thinking of our country and honoring the
service of an individual who helped to make our constitution work
and served in a distinguished way.''
</P>
</TEXT>
